s/listas/semana/4348-%C3%81lbumes-semana-13-2020|title=Top 100 Albumes \u2013 Semana 13: del 20.3.2020 al 26.3.2020|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|56|artist=Morrissey|album=I Am Not a Dog on a Chain|rowheader=true|accessdate=1 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|3|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=28 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UKIndependent|1|date=20200327|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardIndependent|44|artist=Morrissey|rowheader=true|accessdate=1 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|1700539}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|602d4071-2abc-4a94-9e1b-0a8dcba94561}}\n\n{{Morrissey}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Joe Chiccarelli]]\n[[Category:BMG albums]]\n[[Category:Morrissey albums]]\n", "name_user": "TJ Lusitanias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonnel:internal link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Am_Not_a_Dog_on_a_Chain"}
{"title_page": "The Golden Girls", "text_new": "{{about||the 1995 Hong Kong film|The Golden Girls (film)|other uses|Golden Girl (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American sitcom (1985 - 1992)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = The Golden Girls\n| image          = Golden Girls title.svg\n| genre          = [[Sitcom]]\n| creator        = [[Susan Harris]]\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n*[[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]]\n*[[Betty White]]\n*[[Rue McClanahan]]\n*[[Estelle Getty]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Andrew Gold]]\n| opentheme      = \"[[Thank You for Being a Friend]]\" written by Andrew Gold sung by Cynthia Fee\n| endtheme       = \"Thank You for Being a Friend\" Instrumental\n| composer       = [[George Tipton]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| num_seasons    = 7\n| num_episodes   = 180\n| list_episodes  = List of The Golden Girls episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plain list|\n*[[Susan Harris]]\n*[[Paul Junger Witt]]\n*[[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]]\n}}\n| camera         = [[Videotape]], [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime        = 22\u201324 minutes\n| company        = {{Plain list|\n*[[Witt/Thomas Productions|Witt/Thomas/Harris Productions]]\n*[[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]<ref>https://thewaltdisneycompany.com</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]] (current)\n| network        = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Aspect ratio|4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format   = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired    = {{Start date|1985|9|14}}\n| last_aired     = {{End date|1992|5|9}}\n| followed_by    = ''[[The Golden Palace]]''\n| related        = {{Plain list|\n*''[[Empty Nest]]''\n*''[[Nurses (American TV series)|Nurses]]''\n}}\n| website        =\n}}\n\n'''''The Golden Girls''''' is an American [[sitcom]] television series created by [[Susan Harris]] that originally aired on [[NBC]] from September 14, 1985, to May 9, 1992, with a total of 180 half-hour episodes spanning seven seasons. The show stars [[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]], [[Betty White]], [[Rue McClanahan]], and [[Estelle Getty]] as four older women who share friendship, and a home in [[Miami, Florida]]. It was produced by [[Witt/Thomas Productions|Witt/Thomas/Harris Productions]], in association with [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]], and [[Paul Junger Witt]]. [[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]] and Harris served as the original executive producers.\n\n''The Golden Girls'' received critical acclaim throughout most of its run and won several awards including the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]] twice. It also won three [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Awards for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news| title='L.A. Law' and 'Golden Girls' Win Series Emmys| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/21/arts/la-law-and-golden-girls-win-series-emmys.html| accessdate=November 8, 2013| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=September 21, 1987| agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Each of the four stars received an [[Emmy Award]], making it one of only three sitcoms in the award's history to achieve this. The series also ranked among the Nielsen ratings Top 10 for six of its seven seasons.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Galician| first1=Mary-Lou| last2=Merskin| first2=Debra L.| title=Critical Thinking About Sex, Love, and Romance In the Mass Media: Media Literacy Applications| year=2007| publisher=Psychology Press| isbn=978-0-8058-5615-6| page=109}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[TV Guide]]'' ranked ''The Golden Girls'' number 54 on its list of the 60 Best Series of All Time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/tv-guide-magazine-60-best-series-1074962/|title=TV Guide Magazine's 60 Best Series of All Time|work=TV Guide}}</ref> In 2014, the [[Writers Guild of America]] placed the sitcom at number 69 in their list of the \"101 Best Written TV Series of All Time\".<ref name=best101>{{cite web| title='101 Best Written TV Series Of All Time' From WGA/TV Guide: Complete List| url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/06/wgas-101-best-written-tv-series-of-all-time-complete-list/| date=June 2, 2013| website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe show had an [[ensemble cast]] and the plot revolves around four older single women (three widows and one divorc\u00e9e) sharing a house in Miami. The owner of the house is a widow named [[Blanche Devereaux]] (McClanahan), who was joined by fellow widow [[Rose Nylund]] (White) and divorc\u00e9e [[Dorothy Zbornak]] (Arthur), after they both responded to an ad on the bulletin board of a local grocery store a year before the start of the series. In the pilot episode, the three were joined by Dorothy's 80-year-old mother, [[Sophia Petrillo]] (Getty), after the [[retirement home]] where she had been living burned down.<ref>{{cite news| last=Bosman| first=Julie| title=The Grandchildren of 'The Golden Girls'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/08/business/media/08adco.html| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=The New York Times| date=November 8, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Du Brow| first=Rick| title='Golden Girl' Getty Will Miss Her TV 'Daughter'| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-28/entertainment/ca-840_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=April 28, 1992}}</ref>\n\n===Pilot===\nThe first episode featured a cook/butler named Coco (played by [[Charles Levin (actor)|Charles Levin]]), but the role was dropped before the second episode. The writers observed that in many of the proposed scripts, the main interaction between the women occurred in the kitchen while preparing and eating food. They decided that a separate cook would distract from their friendship. In addition, the character of Sophia had originally been planned as an occasional guest star, but Getty had tested so positively with preview audiences that the producers decided to make her a regular character.<ref>{{cite web| last=Kovalchik |first=Kara |title=7 Things You Might Not Know About The Golden Girls From Mental Floss |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/19134/7-things-you-might-not-know-about-golden-girls/ |accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Finale===\nAfter six consecutive seasons in the top 10, and the seventh season at number 30, ''The Golden Girls'' came to an end when Bea Arthur chose to leave the series. In the hour-long [[series finale]], which aired in May 1992, Dorothy meets and marries Blanche's uncle Lucas ([[Leslie Nielsen]]) and moves to Hollingsworth Manor in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Sophia was to join her, but in the end, she stays behind with the other women in Miami. This led into the spin-off series, ''[[The Golden Palace]]''.\n\nThe series finale of The Golden Girls was watched by 27.2 million viewers. As of 2016, it was the 17th-most watched television finale.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morin|first1=Natalie|title=These Are the Most-Watched TV Series Finales of All Time|url=http://tv-shows.prettyfamous.com/stories/21670/tv-series-episode-finales-popular-mash-cheers-friends#80-The-Golden-Girls-One-Flew-Out-of-the-Cuckoo-s-Nest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026121844/http://tv-shows.prettyfamous.com/stories/21670/tv-series-episode-finales-popular-mash-cheers-friends#80-The-Golden-Girls-One-Flew-Out-of-the-Cuckoo-s-Nest|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 26, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of The Golden Girls episodes}}\n{{:List of The Golden Girls episodes}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Main===\n[[File:Golden Girls cast miami song.png|thumb|Main characters in the final scene from the season two episode \"Big Daddy's Little Lady\" (''from left''): Estelle Getty as Sophia, Rue McClanahan as Blanche, Betty White as Rose, and Beatrice Arthur as Dorothy]]\n\n* [[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]] as [[Dorothy Zbornak]] (n\u00e9e Petrillo), a substitute teacher. Born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], to Sicilian immigrants Sophia and Salvadore Petrillo, Dorothy became pregnant while still in [[high school]], resulting in a marriage to Stanley Zbornak ([[Herb Edelman]]) [[shotgun wedding|to legitimize the baby]]. Stan and Dorothy eventually moved to Miami, but divorced after 38 years when Stan left her for a young flight attendant. The marriage produced two children; Kate, in her early 20s, and Michael, who was inconsistently aged between his mid-20s and late 30s (Michael was purportedly the cause of the shotgun wedding). In the series' final episode, Dorothy marries Blanche's uncle, Lucas Hollingsworth, and relocates to Atlanta. Arthur also played Dorothy's grandmother, Sophia's mother, in a flashback episode to when they lived in Brooklyn in the 1950s when Dorothy was a young adult (even though two episodes -- \"My Father, my Brother\" and \"The Days and Nights of Sophia Petrillo\" stated that Sophia's mother died when Dorothy was younger). In season one episode seven, Dorothy is stated to be 55.\n* [[Betty White]] as [[Rose Nylund]] (n\u00e9e Lindstr\u00f6m), a [[Norwegian American]] from the small farming town of [[St. Olaf, Minnesota]]. Often slightly naive and known for her humorously peculiar stories of life growing up in her hometown, Rose was happily married to Charlie Nylund, with whom she had five children; daughters Kirsten, Bridget, Gunilla; and sons Adam and Charlie, Jr. Upon Charlie's death, she moved to Miami. She eventually finds work at a grief counseling center, but later switches careers and becomes assistant to consumer reporter Enrique Mas at a local TV station. In later seasons, Rose became romantically involved with college professor Miles Webber. During season six, Webber was placed into the [[United States Federal Witness Protection Program|Witness Protection Program]], but returned later in the season. Their relationship continued throughout the series and shortly into the sequel series, ''The Golden Palace''.\n* [[Rue McClanahan]] as [[Blanche Devereaux]] (n\u00e9e Hollingsworth), a [[Southern belle]] employed at an art museum. Born into a wealthy family, Blanche grew up as the apple of her father's eye on a [[plantations in the American South|plantation]] outside of Atlanta, Georgia, prior to her relocation to Miami, where she lived with her husband, George, until his death. Their marriage produced six children; daughters Janet and Rebecca; and sons Doug, Biff, Skippy, and Matthew. A widow, Blanche was portrayed as man-hungry and clearly had the most male admirers and stories detailing various sexual encounters over the course of the series.\n* [[Estelle Getty]] as [[Sophia Petrillo]]<!-- If adding maiden name, please cite an episode or reliable source for verifiability -->, Dorothy's mother. Born in [[Sicily]], Sophia moved to New York after fleeing an [[arranged marriage]] to Guido Spirelli. She married Salvadore \"Sal\" Petrillo, with whom she had three children: Dorothy, Gloria, and Phil, a cross-dresser who later dies of a heart attack (episode \"[[Ebbtide's Revenge]]\"). Initially a resident of the Shady Pines retirement home after having a stroke prior to the start of the series, she moved in with Blanche, Rose, and Dorothy following a fire at the institution. During the series' run, Sophia married Max Weinstock, but they soon separated. Throughout the series, she held a few part-time jobs, mostly involving food, including as a fast-food worker and an entrepreneur of spaghetti sauce and homemade sandwiches.\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Herb Edelman]] as Stanley Zbornak, Dorothy's cheating, freeloading ex-husband who left her to marry a young flight attendant, who later left him. Stan married another woman in season 4, and they divorced off-screen in season 5. Stanley worked as an unsuccessful novelty salesman until he became a successful entrepreneur by inventing a baked potato opener that made him wealthy.\n* [[Harold Gould]] as Miles Webber (or Nicholas Carbone/Samuel Plankmaker) is Rose's professor boyfriend from season 5 onwards. In season 6, Miles reveals he is in the witness protection program and was a bookkeeper for a mobster. Gould also guest-starred once in the first season as Arnie Peterson, Rose's first serious boyfriend after her husband Charlie's death.\n* [[Sid Melton]] as Salvadore Petrillo, Sophia's late husband, who is usually seen in dreams or flashback sequences. Melton also appears as Don the Fool, a waiter at a medieval restaurant in season six.\n* Shawn Schepps and Debra Engle, as Blanche's daughter, Rebecca Devereaux. Initially an overweight former model in an emotionally abusive relationship, she later slimmed down and had a baby girl named Aurora by [[artificial insemination]].\n* [[Monte Markham]] and [[Sheree North]] as Blanche's siblings Clayton Hollingsworth and Virginia Hollingsworth. Virginia and Blanche were estranged for a long time, until they reconciled in season 1. They became estranged in season 5 after their father's funeral. Clayton is a closeted gay man who had troubled coming out to Blanche, who eventually accepted his orientation when Clayton and his new boyfriend got married.\n* [[Bill Dana]] and [[Nancy Walker]] as Sophia's siblings Angelo and Angela. Dana appears in seven episodes (seasons 3-7), while he also played Sophia's father in a season-four episode. Walker starred in two episodes in season 2.\n* [[Doris Belack]] and [[Dena Dietrich]] as Gloria Petrillo, Dorothy's younger sister who is married to a wealthy man in California. In a two-part episode, she has lost all of her money and becomes romantically involved with Stan, but she eventually comes to think of him as a \"yutz\" and breaks up with him.\n* [[Scott Jacoby (actor)|Scott Jacoby]] as Dorothy's traveling musician son Michael Zbornak.\n* [[Lynnie Greene]] (credited as Lynn Greene) as a younger Dorothy in flashbacks.\n* [[Lisa Jane Persky]] and [[Deena Freeman]], as Dorothy's daughter, Kate Zbornak who is in interior decorator in New York and married to Dennis who is a successful foot doctor.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Creation===\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; margin-right:2em; font-size:95%; color:black; width:35em; max-width:50%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"I was running all over the house grabbing anybody who would listen. I kept reading scenes to them and saying, 'God, this is brilliant [...] There's nothing trendy about this show. There are no tricks. It's a classic.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014NBC executive [[Warren Littlefield]] about reading the pilot script<ref name=\"ew-2\">{{cite news| first=Nicholas| last=Fonseca| title=Golden Girls: A 20th Anniversary Oral History| date=April 24, 2009| url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1100651_2,00.html| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]| accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\nIdeas for a comedy series about older women emerged during the filming of a television special at [[NBC]]'s Warner Bros. Studios in [[Burbank, California]], in August 1984.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> Produced to introduce the network's [[1984\u201385 United States network television schedule|1984\u201385 season schedule]], two actresses appearing on NBC shows, [[Selma Diamond]] of ''[[Night Court]]'' and [[Doris Roberts]] of ''[[Remington Steele]]'', appeared in a skit promoting the upcoming show ''[[Miami Vice]]'' as ''Miami Nice'', a parody about old people living in Miami.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{cite journal| last=Schwartz| first=Tony| title=The Real Mr. T| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7gBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=September 30, 1985| journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]| page=42| issn=0028-7369}}</ref> NBC senior vice president [[Warren Littlefield]] was among the executive producers in the audience who were amused by their performance, and he envisioned a series based on the geriatric humor the two were portraying.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/>\n\nShortly afterward, he met with producers Paul Junger Witt and [[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]], who were pitching a show about a female lawyer. Though Littlefield nixed their idea, he asked if they would be interested in delivering a [[television pilot|pilot script]] for ''Miami Nice'' instead. Their regular writer declined, so Witt asked his wife, [[Susan Harris]],<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> who had been planning to retire after the conclusion of their ABC series ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''.<ref name=\"Fitzharris\">{{cite web| last=Fitzharris| first=Dustin |title=Catching Up with the Golden Girls' Susan Harris| url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/television/2010/10/03/catching-golden-girls-susan-harris| work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=October 4, 2010}}</ref> She found the concept interesting, as \"it was a demographic that had never been addressed,\" and she soon began work on it.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> Though her vision of a sitcom about women in their 60s differed from NBC's request for a comedy about women around 40 years old,<ref name=\"Prague\">{{cite web| first=Jacke| last=Prague| date=April 8, 2010| title=Crackle's Creator Conversation: Soap's Susan Harris| url=http://www.crackle.com/blog/crackles-creator-conversation-soaps-susan-harris/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227145150/http://www.crackle.com/blog/crackles-creator-conversation-soaps-susan-harris/| archivedate=December 27, 2010| work=Crackle| publisher=Crackle.com| accessdate=June 9, 2011}}</ref> Littlefield was impressed when he received her pilot script and subsequently approved production of it.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' director [[Jay Sandrich]], who had previously worked with Harris, Witt, and Thomas on ''Soap'', agreed to direct.<ref name=\"Cronin\">{{cite web| last=Cronin| first=Brian| title=TV Legends Revealed #35| url=http://legendsrevealed.com/entertainment/2011/01/14/tv-legends-revealed-35/| publisher=Legends Revealed| accessdate=January 14, 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119085507/http://legendsrevealed.com/entertainment/2011/01/14/tv-legends-revealed-35/| archivedate=January 19, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe pilot included a gay houseboy, Coco ([[Charles Levin (actor)|Charles Levin]]), who lived with the girls. Levin had been suggested by then-NBC president [[Brandon Tartikoff]] based on  Levin's groundbreaking portrayal of a recurring gay character, Eddie Gregg, on NBC's Emmy-winning drama ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''. After the pilot, the character of Coco was eliminated from the series.<ref name=\"Colucci\">{{cite book| last=Colucci| first=Jim| title=The Q Guide to the Golden Girls| year=2006| publisher=Alyson Books| pages=8, 43\u201355}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book |last1=Bloom |first1=Ken |last2=Vlastnik |first2=Frank |last3=Lithgow |first3=John |title=Sitcoms: The 101 Greatest TV Comedies of All Time |year=2007 |publisher=Black Dog Publishing |isbn=978-1-57912-752-7 |page=137}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Rue McClanahan book signing.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Rue McClanahan]] in 2007]]\n\nThe part of [[Sophia Petrillo]] was the first of the four roles to be cast. Estelle Getty auditioned and won the role of the feisty mother of character [[Dorothy Zbornak]]. This was due, in part, to the rave reviews she garnered in her Off-Broadway role reprisal for the 1984 Los Angeles run of ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''. Afterwards, Getty had returned to New York but gained permission from her manager to return to California in early 1985. Getty figured it would be her last chance to find television or film work. She would return home to New York if she was unsuccessful.\n\nCasting director Judith Weiner had seen ''Torch Song Trilogy'' and thought Getty was terrific in it. She was also impressed by Getty's audition for the role of the mother of Steven Keaton (played by actor [[Michael Gross (actor)|Michael Gross]]) for a guest episode of ''[[Family Ties]]''. Although Getty was impressive, the show's producers went with another actress. Getty came to Weiner's mind soon after when it became time to begin casting of ''The Golden Girls.''<ref>Colucci, Jim. ''Golden Girls Forever''. HarperCollins Publishers Inc, 2016.</ref>\n\nGetty, who went through a three-hour transformation to become Sophia, wore heavy make-up, thick glasses, and a white wig to look the part.<ref name=\"Kinosian\">{{cite book| last=Kinosian| first=Janet| title=Making Up Is Hard to Do| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=52AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA157| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=February 1, 1988| work=[[Orange Coast (magazine)|Orange Coast]]| page=157| issn=0279-0483}}</ref> The character of Sophia was thought by the creators to enhance the idea that three retirement-aged women could be young. Disney's [[Michael Eisner]] explains, \"Estelle Getty made our three women into girls. And that was, to me, what made it seem like it could be a contemporary, young show.\"<ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web| title=The Golden Girls| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/shows/golden-girls-the| publisher=Archive of American Television| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> As surprising as it might sound, Estelle Getty continuously battled her stage fright. During an interview in 1988, Getty commented on her phobia and expressed how working with major stars, such as Arthur and White, made her even more nervous. At times, she even froze on camera while filming.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 20 Fun Facts About 'The Golden Girls'|url = http://mentalfloss.com/article/56215/20-fun-facts-about-golden-girls|website = [[Mental Floss]]|access-date = February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHired to film the pilot, director Jay Sandrich also became instrumental in helping to cast the roles of Blanche Devereaux and Rose Nylund. Both Rue McClanahan and Betty White came into consideration as the series ''[[Mama's Family]]'', in which the two co-starred, had been canceled by NBC. Originally, producers wanted to cast McClanahan as Rose and White as Blanche. The thinking for this was based on roles they previously played; White portrayed man-hungry [[Sue Ann Nivens]] on ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'', while McClanahan co-starred as sweet but scatter-brained [[Vivian Harmon]] in ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]''. Eager not to be [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]], they took the suggestion of Sandrich and switched roles last-minute.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/><ref name=\"Bloom\"/>\n\nIn the pilot script, Blanche was described as \"more Southern than [[Blanche DuBois]]\", so McClanahan was perplexed when she was asked by director Sandrich during the filming of the pilot not to use the strong [[Southern American English|southern accent]] she had developed, but to use her natural Oklahoma accent instead.<ref name=\"emmytv\">{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y_DGIgDOg6c| title=Rue McClanahan on Blanche's accent on \"The Golden Girls\"- EMMYTVLEGENDS.org| author=emmytvlegends.org| publisher=YouTube.com| date=June 11, 2010| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref> Once the show was picked up for a first season, the new director [[Paul Bogart]] felt exactly the opposite, insisting that McClanahan use a Southern accent. McClanahan deliberately exaggerated her accent, stating \"I played Blanche the way I felt Blanche. She thought an accentuated Southern accent...would be sexy and strong and attractive to men. She wanted to be a southern heroine, like [[Vivien Leigh]]. In fact, that's who I think she thought she was.\"<ref>{{cite book| title=Golden Girls Forever| first=Jim| last=Colucci| publisher=Harper Collins| year=2016| p=34}}</ref>\n\nThough Harris had created the character of Dorothy with a \"Bea Arthur type\" in mind, Littlefield and the producers initially envisioned actress [[Elaine Stritch]] for the part.<ref name=\"Bloom\"/> Stritch's audition flopped, however, and under the impression that Arthur did not want to participate, Harris asked McClanahan if she could persuade Arthur, with whom she worked previously on the CBS sitcom ''Maude'', to take the role. Arthur flipped upon reading the script, but felt hesitant about McClanahan's approach, as she did not \"want to play (their ''Maude'' characters) Maude and Vivian meet Sue Ann Nivens.\" She reconsidered, however, after hearing that McClanahan and White had switched roles.\n\nBea Arthur and Betty White worked well together in shared mutual respect but they did not pursue a personal friendship with one another outside of ''The Golden Girls'' set. Arthur's son, Matthew Saks, later spoke of tension between the two actresses, stating that his mother \"unknowingly carried the attitude that it was fun to have somebody to be angry at...It was almost like Betty became her nemesis, someone she could always roll her eyes about at work.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.closerweekly.com/posts/bea-arthur-feud-betty-white-golden-girls-138841/?display=listicle| title=Betty White and Bea Arthur's Friends Open Up About Their On-Set Feud| publisher=closerweekly.com}}</ref> Both actresses had dramatically different training and acting backgrounds; Saks commented on White's habit of [[breaking the fourth wall]] to engage and joke with the studio audience during breaks between filming, which Bea Arthur found unprofessional.<ref name=\"Michelle Darrisaw\">{{cite article|  url=https://www.southernliving.com/culture/betty-white-bea-arthur-golden-girls-feud| title=Say It Isn't So, Girls! Details on Betty White and Bea Arthur's Off-Screen Feud| author=Michelle Darrisaw| publisher=Southern Living| date=|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In 2011 White stated that she believed it was her \"positive attitude\" and perky demeanor which got on Arthur's nerves.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web| title=CNN Official Interview: Betty White: Bea Arthur was not fond of me| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-wTJ2hQCK8| publisher=CNN| date=May 4, 2011| accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Writing and taping===\nThe show was the second television series to be produced by the Walt Disney Company under the [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]] label, and was subsequently distributed by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista International, Inc.]] (which holds as the ownership stake in [[Disney Channel (Southeast Asia)|Disney Channel Southeast Asia]], now [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group]]).<ref name=\"studios\">{{cite web| title=ABC Studios| url=http://tviv.org/ABC_Studios| publisher=The TV IV| date=August 30, 2007| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCreator Susan Harris went on to contribute another four episodes to the first season, but became less involved with the sitcom throughout its run; she continued reading all scripts, though, and remained familiar with most of the storylines. Kathy Speer and Terry Grossman were the first head writers of the series and wrote for the show's first four seasons. As head writers, Speer and Grossman, along with Mort Nathan and Barry Fanaro, who won an Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing the first season, gave general ideas to lower staff writers, and personally wrote a handful of scripts each season.<ref name=\"Mills\">{{cite news| last=Mills| first=Nancy| title='Golden Girls' Polishes Its Scripts: Daily Revisions Geared to Sharpen Story and Hone Those Laugh Lines| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-10-30/entertainment/ca-11702_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=October 30, 1987}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Marc Sotkin, previously a writer on ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' and a producer on fellow Witt/Thomas series ''[[It's a Living (1980 TV series)|It's a Living]]'', assumed head-writing responsibilities, and guided the show (to varying degrees) during what were its final three seasons. Richard Vaczy and Tracy Gamble, previously writers on ''[[227 (TV series)|227]]'' and ''[[My Two Dads]]'', also assumed the roles of producers and head writers. Beginning in 1990, [[Marc Cherry]] served as writer and producer, years before creating ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', which ran on ABC from 2004 to 2012.<ref name=\"Mills\"/> [[Mitchell Hurwitz]] also served as writer for the show in its last two seasons. Hurwitz later created ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and later for Netflix.\n\nCherry commented on [[read-through]]s of the scripts that \"generally, if the joke was a good one, the women found a way to make it work the very first time they read it. You have a lot of table reads where the actors will mess it up because they don't understand what the characters are doing, or they misinterpret. But the women were so uniformly brilliant at nailing it the first time...we basically knew that if the women didn't get it right the first time, the joke needed to be replaced.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/02/marc-cherry-remembers-writing-for-golden-girls.html| title=Marc Cherry Shares His Memories of Writing for Golden Girls| first=Josef| last=Adalian| journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]| date=February 28, 2013| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEstelle Getty's [[stage fright]], which affected her from the beginning of the show, grew worse as the show went on, to the point that she would forget her lines more and more. Beginning in Season 5, she would have to read her lines off cue cards held off-camera or from props.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/flashback/golden-girls-werent-so-chummy-off-the-screen-stars-son-reveals/news-story/6f1a33f4d0f9713751c5efdd5b371141| title=Golden Girls weren't so chummy off the screen, star\u2019s son reveals| first=Stephanie| last=Nolasco| publisher=Fox News| via=news.com.au| date=November 9, 2017| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref> Rue McClanahan, who shared a dressing room with Getty, described the severity of Getty's stage fright: \"She'd panic. She would start getting under a dark cloud the day before tape day...You could see a big difference in her that day. She'd be walking around like [[Pig-Pen]] under a black cloud. By tape day, she was unreachable. She was just as uptight as a human being could get. When your brain is frozen like that, you can't remember lines.\"<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SaDIbjIXnlM| title=Rue McClanahan Interview - Part 4 of 5 - EMMYTVLEGENDS.org| author=Emmytvlegends.org| publisher=YouTube.com| date=September 9, 2009| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring season six there was some uncertainty over whether Bea Arthur would commit to future seasons, or leave the show once her contract expired to pursue other projects.<ref name=\"Unauthorized\"/><ref name=\"Lifetime\">{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E6lZupLt8HU| title=Bea Arthur 2002 Intimate Portrait (HD)| publisher=YouTube.com| date=September 17, 2016| access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> Arthur had expressed weariness with doing the show, and had also grown frustrated with the disparaging jokes made about her physical appearance which were often in the script.<ref name=\"Michelle Darrisaw\"/> [[Debbie Reynolds]] was brought on as a guest star in the season 6 episode \"There Goes the Bride: Part 2\" to test her chemistry with the other actresses as a possible replacement for Arthur, but it was decided that nobody could replicate the chemistry of the four original actresses. In any event, Arthur chose to commit to a seventh and final season.<ref name=\"Unauthorized\">{{cite book| title=Golden Girls Forever: An Unauthorized Look Behind the Lanai| first=Jim| last=Colucci| publisher=Harper Design| year=2016| pages=255\u201356}}</ref>\n\n===Exterior and interior sets===\nThe house's address was mentioned as being 6151 Richmond Street, Miami.<ref name=\"Terrace2011\">{{cite book| last=Terrace| first=Vincent| title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 Through 2010| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YX_daEhlnbsC&pg=PT2528| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2011| publisher=McFarland| isbn=978-0-7864-8641-0| page=2528}}</ref> The model used for exterior shots of the house from the third season through the end of the series was part of the backstage studio tour ride at Disney's Hollywood Studios. This fa\u00e7ade, along with the ''Empty Nest'' house, sustained hurricane damage leading to Disney's 2003 decision to bulldoze the houses of \"Residential Street\" and construct its \"Lights, Motors, Action!\" attraction. The fa\u00e7ade was based on a real house at 245 N. Saltair Avenue in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles, California]]. Producers used this residence for exterior shots during the first two seasons.<ref>{{Coord|34.066|-118.4474|display=inline|region:GB_scale:5000}}</ref>\n\nThe show's designer, Ed Stephenson, took inspiration from his time living in Florida to design a \"Florida look\" for ''The Golden Girls'' house set. The wooden accents, columns, and doors were painted to mimic [[Taxodium distichum|Bald cypress]] wood, popular in South Florida homes, with [[rattan]] furniture and tropical-printed upholstery chosen for the furniture.<ref>Colucci 2016 p. 317-318</ref>\n\nThe kitchen set seen on ''The Golden Girls'' was originally used on an earlier Witt/Thomas/Harris series, ''[[It Takes Two (American TV series)|It Takes Two]]'', which aired on ABC from 1982 to 1983. However, the exterior backdrop seen through the kitchen window changed from the view of Chicago [[high-rise]]s to palm trees and bushes for the Miami setting. Space was limited on the soundstage, so when the kitchen was off camera it was usually detached from the rest of the set and the space used for something else. The doorway from the living room, with the alcove and baker's shelf just inside, was designed to give the illusion that the actors were walking in and out of the kitchen.<ref>Colucci, 2016 pg. 324</ref>\n\n===Costumes===\nCostume designer Judy Evans created distinctive looks for each of the four actresses to suit their character's personalities and to reflect the Florida setting. According to Evans \"I wanted a sexy, soft, and flowing look for Rue, a tailored, pulled-together look for Bea, a down-home look for Betty, and comfort for Estelle.\"<ref>Colucci, 2016, p. 333</ref> Anna Wyckoff of the [[Costume Designers Guild]] wrote that \"Evans took the direction from the producers to create a vibrant look for the four mature leads, and ran with it...redefining what \u201cdressing your age\u201d looked like.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/articles-videos/articles-archive/costume-design-costars/| title=The Changing Face of Modern Television: When Costume Design Costars| first=Anna| last=Wyckoff| magazine=The Costume Designer| date=Spring 2012| access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Many of the character's outfits were designed by Evans and made specially, but there were between seven and ten costume changes per episode between the four actresses, which entailed a great deal of [[off the rack]] shopping.<ref name=\"Colucci, 2016 pg. 333\">Colucci, 2016 pg. 333</ref> Evans generally dressed the actresses in expensive pieces and high quality fabrics, despite the recurring theme that the four characters were struggling with money, because \"The main idea was to make them look good. We didn't want the show to be about four dowdy ladies.\"<ref name=\"Colucci, 2016 pg. 333\"/>\n\nBea Arthur had a preference for wearing loose fitting clothing, like slacks and long sweaters, along with sandals because she hated wearing shoes. She had established this signature look while playing [[Maude Findlay|Maude]], and Evans honored it in her designs for Dorothy.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://nypost.com/2002/01/28/bea-ing-stylishformer-golden-girl-bea-arthur-talks-about-comfort-clothes-going-barefoot-and-her-famous-maude-wardrobe/| title=Bea-ing Stylish: Former \u201cGolden Girl\u201d Bea Arthur Talks About Comfort Clothes, Going Barefoot and Her Famous \u201cMaude\u201d Wardrobe| first=Barbara| last=Hoffman| newspaper=New York Post| date=2002-01-28| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> Much of Arthur's wardrobe was custom-made because at the time it was difficult to find off-the-rack clothing that was flattering for a taller woman.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 333</ref> Rue McClanahan had a special clause written into her contract allowing her to keep her costumes, which were mostly custom-made using expensive fabrics.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 338</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/54393/7-must-have-items-rue-mcclanahans-estate-sale| title=7 Must-Have Items from Rue McClanahan's Estate Sale| first=Kara| last=Kovalchik| publisher=Mentalfloss.com| date=2014-01-14| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> Eventually McClanahan went on to create a clothing line for [[QVC]], called \"A Touch of Rue\", inspired by Blanche but made with affordable fabrics and practical designs.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 339</ref>\n\n===Format===\n''The Golden Girls'' was shot on videotape in front of a live studio audience.<ref name=\"Rosewarne2012\">{{cite book| last=Rosewarne| first=Lauren| title=Periods in Pop Culture: Menstruation in Film and Television| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m0Ti0d-T4DwC&pg=PA188| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2012| publisher=Lexington Books| isbn=978-0-7391-7000-7| page=188}}</ref> Many episodes of the series followed a similar format or theme. For example, one or more of the women would become involved in some sort of problem, often involving other family members, men, or an ethical dilemma. At some point, they would gather around the kitchen table and discuss the problem, sometimes late at night and often while eating [[cheesecake]], ice cream or some other dessert.<ref name=\"DeCaro2011\">{{cite book| last=DeCaro| first=Frank| title=The Dead Celebrity Cookbook: A Resurrection of Recipes from More Than 145 Stars of Stage and Screen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILvGSUX7olkC&pg=PA352| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2011| publisher=Health Communications Inc.| isbn=978-0-7573-1596-1| page=352}}</ref> One of the other girls then told a story from her own life, which somehow related to the problem (though Rose occasionally regaled a nonsense story that had nothing to do with the situation, and Sophia told outrageous made-up stories). Some episodes featured flashbacks to previous episodes, flashbacks to events not shown in previous episodes, or to events that occurred before the series began.<ref name=\"Huryk2007\">{{cite book| last=Huryk| first=Harry| title=The Golden Girls - The Ultimate Viewing Guide| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t_jTuiubE0AC&pg=PA13| accessdate=August 8, 2013| date=July 1, 2007| publisher=Lulu.com| isbn=978-1-4116-8528-4|page=13}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} Though the writing was mostly comical, dramatic moments and sentimental endings were included in several episodes. One of the actresses on the show, Bea Arthur, actually hated cheesecake.<ref>{{cite news |title=30 Things You Never Knew About 'The Golden Girls' |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/golden-girls-turns-30-facts-series/story?id=33545250 |work=ABC News |date=September 15, 2015 |access-date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nDuring the NBC upfronts, the preview screening of the show got a standing ovation. The show promptly received a full order of 12 episodes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/03/the-golden-girls-creators-on-finding-new-fans.html |title=The Golden Girls Creators On Finding a New Generation of Fans |last=Hunt |first=Stacey Wilson |work=Vulture |access-date=March 3, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n===Ratings===\nAn instant ratings hit, ''The Golden Girls'' became an NBC staple on Saturday nights.<ref name=\"tops\">{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Tops Ratings| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1985-09-17/news/mn-20345_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=September 17, 1985| agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The show was the anchor of NBC's Saturday line-up, and almost always won its time slot, as ABC and CBS struggled to find shows to compete against it, the most notable being ABC's [[Lucille Ball]] sitcom ''[[Life With Lucy]]'' in the beginning of the 1986\u201387 season. ''The Golden Girls'' was part of a series of Brandon Tartikoff shows that put an end to NBC's ratings slump, along with ''[[The Cosby Show]]'', ''[[227 (TV series)|227]]'', ''[[Night Court]]'', ''[[Miami Vice]]'', and ''[[L.A. Law]].''\n\nThe show dealt with many controversial issues, such as [[coming out]] and [[same-sex marriage]],<ref name=\"closets\">{{cite news| title=Gays and Closets--a TV Controversy| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-04-21/entertainment/ca-650_1_golden-girls-closets-weinstein| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=April 21, 1991}}</ref> [[elder care]] and [[homelessness]], [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[discrimination against people with HIV/AIDS]], US immigration policy, [[death]] and [[assisted suicide]].<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite news| title='The Golden Girls' And Gay Marriage: Classic Sitcom Showed Support 20 Years Before Obama| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/10/the-golden-girls-and-gay-marriage_n_1506091.html| date=May 10, 2012| work=[[The Huffington Post]]| accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWriter and producer [[Linda Bloodworth-Thomason]] created a sitcom with this kind of image as a \"four women\" show, which became ''[[Designing Women]]'' on CBS. ''Designing Women'' began competing against ''The Golden Girls'' in the same time slot, however ''The Golden Girls'' always got the higher rating, resulting in CBS pushing ''Designing Women'' to Mondays.\n\nAt the request of [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]], who was reputedly a big fan, the cast of ''The Golden Girls'' performed several skits as their characters in front of her and other members of the Royal Family at the 1988 [[Royal Variety Performance]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-cDonM4VXD8| title=Golden Girls Reunion| publisher=Lifetime Television| year=2003| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nNBC Timeslots\n* Seasons 1-6: Saturday at 9:00 PM\n* Season 7: Saturday at 8:00 PM\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by The Golden Girls}}\n[[File:The Golden Girls Disney Legends.jpg|thumb|''The Golden Girls'' [[Disney Legends]] plaque at [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Walt Disney Studios]]]]\nDuring its original run, ''The Golden Girls'' received 68 Emmy nominations, 11 Emmy awards, four Golden Globe Awards, and two [[Viewers for Quality Television]] awards. All the lead actresses won [[Emmy Award]]s for their performances on the show. ''The Golden Girls'' is one of three live action shows, along with ''[[All in the Family]]'' and ''[[Will & Grace]]'' where all the principal actors have won at least one Emmy Award.\n\nAs a tribute to the success of ''The Golden Girls'', all four actresses were later named [[Disney Legends]].<ref name=\"disney\">{{cite web| title=Legends| url=http://disney.go.com/disneyinsider/history/legends/find-legends| website=Walt Disney Company| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n\n===Syndication===\nBeginning July 3, 1989, NBC added daytime reruns of the show, replacing long-running ''Wheel of Fortune'' (it moved to CBS) on the NBC schedule at 11:00&nbsp;a.m.(EST). It ran for a little over a year until September 1990. At this time, syndicated reruns began airing, distributed by [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television#Buena Vista Television|Buena Vista Television]] (now [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]), the syndication arm of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], whose [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]] division produced the series.\n\nIn March 1997, the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] cable network acquired the exclusive rights to repeat the episodes of ''The Golden Girls'' in the US for over a decade, until March 1, 2009. Many episodes were edited to allow more commercials and for content.\n\nBoth the [[Hallmark Channel]] and [[WE tv]] picked up the reruns in March 2009. As of February 2013, We TV's rights expired and [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] networks' [[TV Land]], home to Betty White's last series ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'', purchased them,<ref name=\"tvland\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tvland.com/shows/the-golden-girls |title=The Golden Girls |publisher=[[TV Land]] |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> as did  [[Logo TV]].<ref name=logo>{{cite web| date=March 6, 2013 |url=http://www.logotv.com/video/misc/885521/preview-the-golden-girls-arrive-on-logo-april-13th.jhtml |title=Preview 2: The Golden Girls Arrive on Logo April 13th |publisher=Logotv.com |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> In 2020, [[CMT (American TV channel)|CMT]] purchased the rights to the series.\n\nIn Australia, the show airs daily on [[Fox Classics]]. As of 2019, every episode is available for streaming on [[Stan (company)|Stan]].\n\nIn Canada, [[Corus Entertainment|Corus Entertainment's]] digital specialty channel, [[DejaView]], aired reruns of ''The Golden Girls'' until 2017.\n\nIn Southeast Asia, [[Rewind Networks]] began airing reruns of ''The Golden Girls'' on its HD channel, [[Hits (TV channel)|HITS]], in 2013.\n\nIn New Zealand, the series was shown on [[TVNZ]] and is replayed on public holidays and it is shown on [[Jones!]].\n\nIn the UK, the series was shown on [[Channel 4]] and [[Disney Channel (UK and Ireland)|Disney Channel]].\n\nEvery episode of ''The Golden Girls'' was made available to stream on [[Hulu]] on February 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hulu.com/the-golden-girls|title=The Golden Girls|website=Hulu|access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n[[Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] has released all seven seasons of ''The Golden Girls'' on DVD in [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] and [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] with the first four being released in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]. On November 9, 2010, the studio released a complete series box set titled ''The Golden Girls: 25th Anniversary Complete Collection''.<ref name=tvshows>{{cite press release| url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Golden-Girls-Complete-Collection/14375| title=The Golden Girls \u2013 25th Anniversary Complete Collection| publisher=Walt Disney Studios| date=September 7, 2010| accessdate=January 2, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115072440/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Golden-Girls-Complete-Collection/14375| archivedate=November 15, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The 21-disc collection features all 180 episodes of the series as well as all special features contained on the previously released season sets; it is encased in special collectible packaging, a replica of Sophia's purse. On November 15, 2005, [[Warner Home Video]] released ''The Golden Girls: A Lifetime Intimate Portrait Series'' on DVD which contains a separate biography of Arthur, White, McClanahan and Getty, revealing each woman's background, rise to stardom and private life, which originally aired on [[Lifetime Television|Lifetime]] network between June 2000 and January 2003.<ref name=\"portrait\">{{cite AV media| url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000AYEL4M| title=''The Golden Girls'': A Lifetime Intimate Portrait Series| accessdate=June 9, 2011| publisher=Warner Home Video| date=November 15, 2005| medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\n'''Australian Region 4 DVD Releases:'''\n\n* Season 1 | 17 August 2005<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Night Season |journal=The Night Season |doi=10.5040/9780571284313.00000006 |year=2004 |isbn=978-0571284313}}</ref>\n* Season 2 | 21 September 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-2/851970/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 2 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 3 | 1 October 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sanity.com.au/products/2001693/Golden_Girls_The_-_Season_03 |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 03 |website=Sanity |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 4 | 5 December 2007<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-4/205314/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 4 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 5 | 2 April 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-5/222922/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 5 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 6 | 3 December 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-6/237247/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 6 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 7 | 18 March 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-7/247317/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 7 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* The Complete Series | 7 November 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-1-7/340415/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 1-7 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-offs==\nUpon the success of ''The Golden Girls'' creator Susan Harris later devised ''[[Empty Nest]]'' as a spin-off from ''The Golden Girls'' with some character crossovers. ''[[Nurses (TV series)|Nurses]]'' was later spun-off from ''Empty Nest'', and the shows occasionally had special episodes in which characters from one show made appearances in the others.<ref name=\"Dubrow\">{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Creator Adds Shows| work=Los Angeles Times| date=September 10, 1991| first=Rick| last=DuBrow| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-09-10/entertainment/ca-2286_1_golden-girls| accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===''The Golden Palace''===\n{{Main|The Golden Palace}}\nAfter the original series ended, White, McClanahan, and Getty reprised their characters in the CBS series ''The Golden Palace'', which ran from September 1992 to May 1993, and also starred [[Cheech Marin]] and [[Don Cheadle]] (Bea Arthur guest-starred in a double episode, reprising her role as Dorothy).<ref>{{cite news| title=TV Weekend; 3 of the Golden Girls in a New Home| work=The New York Times| date=September 25, 1992| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/25/news/tv-weekend-3-of-the-golden-girls-in-a-new-home.html?scp=1&sq=The%20Golden%20Palace&st=cse| accessdate=August 19, 2010 |first=John J. |last=O'Connor}}</ref> The show never approached the popularity or acclaim of the original, and ranked 57th in the annual ratings. Reportedly, a second season was approved before being canceled the day before the network announced its 1993-94 schedule.\n\nLifetime, which held the rights to ''The Golden Girls'' at the time, aired reruns of ''The Golden Palace'' in the summer of 2005, and again in December of that year. This was the first time since 1993 that ''The Golden Palace'' was seen on American television. Until April 2006, Lifetime played the series as a virtual season eight, airing the series in between the conclusion of the final season and the syndicated roll-over to season one.\n\n===''Empty Nest''===\n{{Main|Empty Nest}}\n[[File:EstelleGetty2.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Estelle Getty]] at the 41st annual [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 1989]]\nCapitalizing on the popularity of ''The Golden Girls'', creator Susan Harris decided to develop a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]], centering on the [[empty nest syndrome]]. The initial pilot was aired as the 1987 ''Golden Girls'' episode \"[[The Golden Girls (season 2)#Episodes|Empty Nests]]\" and starred [[Paul Dooley]] and [[Rita Moreno]] as George and Renee Corliss, a married couple living next to the ''Golden Girls'' characters, who face empty nest syndrome after their teenage daughter moves out.<ref>{{cite web| title=''The Golden Girls'' Has Been A Delight From Its Inception| work=Los Angeles Times| date=June 7, 1987| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-07/news/tv-777_1_los-angeles-golden-girls-etta-morris| accessdate=June 19, 2011| first=Etta| last=Morris}}</ref> When that idea was not well received, Harris retooled the series as a vehicle for [[Richard Mulligan]], and the following year ''[[Empty Nest]]'' debuted, starring Mulligan as pediatrician Harry Weston, a widower whose two adult daughters moved back home. Characters from both shows made occasional [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] guest appearances on the other show, with the four girls guesting on ''Empty Nest'' and Mulligan, [[Dinah Manoff]], [[Kristy McNichol]], [[David Leisure]], and [[Park Overall]] appearing on ''The Golden Girls'' in their ''Empty Nest'' roles.<ref>{{cite web| first=Howard| last=Rosenberg| title=''Empty Nest'' Looks Like Good Place to Nestle Down| work=Los Angeles Times| date=October 8, 1988| url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-10-08/entertainment/ca-3135_1_empty-nest| accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> After the end of ''The Golden Palace'', Getty joined the cast of ''Empty Nest'', making frequent appearances as Sophia in the show's final two seasons.\n\nMulligan and Manoff were alumni from one of Susan Harris' earlier shows, ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''.\n\n===''Nurses''===\n{{Main|Nurses (TV series)}}\n''Empty Nest'' launched its own spin-off in 1991 set in Miami in the same hospital where Dr. Weston worked. The series starred [[Stephanie Hodge]] and a set of other young female and male nurses. As one of the few times in television history where three shows from the same producer, set in the same city, aired back-to-back-to-back on the same network, the three shows occasionally took advantage of their unique circumstance to create storylines carrying through all three series, such as \"[[Hurricane Saturday]]\". Starring actress Hodge left after two seasons, [[David Rasche]] joining the cast at the start of the second season and [[Loni Anderson]] being added as the new hospital administrator in the third.\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Stage===\n''The Golden Girls: Live!'' was an [[off-Broadway]] show that opened in the summer of 2003 in New York City at Rose's Turn theater in the West Village, and ran until November of that year.<ref name=stage>{{cite web| title='Golden Girls: Live!' Sent to Shady Pines| date=December 8, 2003| last=Jacobs| first=Leonard| url=http://www.backstage.com/news/golden-girls-live-sent-to-shady-pines/| publisher=backstage.com| accessdate=January 2, 2014}}</ref> The production ended because the producers failed to secure the [[Copyright|rights]] and received a [[cease and desist]] order by the creators of the original television show. Featuring an all-male cast in [[Drag queen|drag]], ''The Golden Girls: Live!'' consisted of two back-to-back episodes of the sitcom: \"Break-In\" (season one, episode eight) and \"Isn't It Romantic?\" (season two, episode five).\n\nThe cast of The Golden Girls, Sophia, Dorothy, Blanche and Rose, have been even further immortalised in two puppet parody shows ''Thank You For Being A Friend''<ref>https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/city-east/thank-you-for-being-a-friend-brings-the-golden-girls-to-the-stage-as-puppets/news-story/715a4b5a3535352470bd7c530d07683b</ref> and ''That Golden Girls Show: A Puppet Parody'', both created by Australian screenwriter, [[Thomas Duncan-Watt]] and producer, [[Jonathan Rockefeller]]<ref>http://www.theaterjones.com/ntx/reviews/20191117091441/2019-11-17/Eisemann-Center-for-the-Performing-Arts/The-Golden-Girls-Show-A-Puppet-Parody</ref>.\n\n===International versions===\n* Chile: ''{{interlanguage link|Los a\u00f1os dorados|es|Los a\u00f1os dorados (Chile)|vertical-align=sup}}'': In 2015 a Chilean remake called ''Los A\u00f1os Dorados'' (''The Golden Years'') was produced by UCVTV in agreement with Disney, starring famous Chilean actresses Gloria M\u00fcnchmeyer, Carmen Barros, Ana Reeves, and Consuelo Holzapfel, who live their retirement in the city of [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar]]. It was a success for the channel, so there are plans to do the second season in 2016. \n*Israel:  ''[[Bnot HaZahav]]'', which ran from 2011 to 2016.\n* Greece: ''Chrysa Koritsia'': In 2008, Greek broadcaster [[ET1 (Greece)|ET1]] premiered a Greek remake entitled ''Chrysa Koritsia'' ({{Lang-el|X\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ac \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03c4\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1}}, ''Gold[en] Girls''), which features the four women in Greece.<ref name=\"Advocate\">{{cite news| title=Golden Girls Hits Spain| author=Jeffrey Gerson| work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]| publisher=Advocate.com| date=July 29, 2010| url=http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2010/07/29/Gracias_Por_Ser_Una_Amiga_Golden_Girls_Hits_Spain/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801033740/http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2010/07/29/Gracias_Por_Ser_Una_Amiga_Golden_Girls_Hits_Spain/| archivedate=August 1, 2010| accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref> Each of the characters has been hellenized to suit the culture and modern setting. Names were only slightly changed, but more for cultural reasons, as Sophia (whose first name was unchanged, as it is Greek), Bela (Blanche), Dora (Dorothy), Fifi (Rose), and Panos (Stan). The series began airing in mid-January, and features many similar plots to the original. ET1 aired a rerun of the show in the summer of 2008 and managed to take a place in the top-10 ratings chart, presented by AGB Nielsen Media Research. The Greek edition features Mirka Papakonstantinou as Dora, Dina Konsta as Sofia, Eleni Gerasimidou as Fifi, and Ivonni Maltezou as Bela.\n* Netherlands: ''{{interlanguage link|Golden Girls|nl|Golden Girls (Nederland)|vertical-align=sup}}:'' A Dutch remake for the [[RTL 4]] network stars [[Loes Luca]] as Barbara (Blanche), [[Beppie Melissen]] as Els (Dorothy), [[Cecile Heuer]] as Milly (Rose), and [[Pleuni Touw]] as Toos (Sophia). The show premiered in fall 2012, using essentially the same plots as the U.S. version, along with a Dutch-language version of the original theme song, \"[[Thank You for Being a Friend]]\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Golden Girls Intro (Dutch)| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OPYq7bmpldw| publisher=YouTube| date=October 11, 2012| accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref>\n* Philippines: ''50 Carats, O Di Ba?'' A Philippine version of ''The Golden Girls'' (spin-off) aired during the early 1990s by [[IBC 13]] starred [[Nida Blanca]], [[Charito Solis]], and [[Gloria Romero (actress)|Gloria Romero]].<ref name=\"francisco\">{{cite news| title=A rivalry that never was| url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/140171/rivalry-never-was| date=November 15, 2001| last=Francisco| first=Butch| newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]| accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n* Russia: ''Bolshie Devochki'': A Russian remake was broadcast in 2006, entitled ''Bolshie Devochki'' ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0438}}), which in English can literally be translated to: ''Big Girls''. The series featured renowned Russian actresses Galina Petrova as Irina (Dorothy), Olga Ostroumova as Nadejda (Blanche), Valentina Telechkina as Margarita (Rose), and Elena Millioti as Sofya (Sophia). However, the concept never caught on with the Russian viewers and the show was canceled after only 32 episodes.<ref name=\"Bolshie\">{{cite web |title=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0438 |url=http://www.amedia.ru/girls/ |publisher=amedia.ru |date= |accessdate=June 24, 2011 |language=Russian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511142327/http://www.amedia.ru/girls/ |archivedate=May 11, 2011 |trans-title=Big Girls}}</ref>\n* Spain: ''{{interlanguage link|Juntas, pero no revueltas|es|Juntas, pero no revueltas|vertical-align=sup}}''/''{{interlanguage link|Las chicas de oro|es|Las chicas de oro (Espa\u00f1a)|vertical-align=sup}}'': In 1996, [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]] launched a Spanish remake entitled ''Juntas pero no revueltas'' (''Together, but not mixed'') with [[Mercedes Sampietro]] as Julia (Dorothy), [[M\u00f3nica Randall]] as Nuri (Blanche), [[Kiti Manver]] as Rosa (Rose), and [[Amparo Bar\u00f3]] as Benigna (Sophia). Low ratings made it disappear after one season.<ref name=\"TVE\">{{cite web| title=TVE comienza a rodar 'Juntas, pero no revueltas', su versi\u00f3n de 'Las chicas de oro'| url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/Pantallas/MANVER/_KITI_/ACTRIZ/ESPANA/TELEVISION_ESPANOLA_/RTVE/TVE/comienza/rodar/Juntas/revueltas/version/chicas/oro/elpepirtv/19950609elpepirtv_3/Tes| date=June 9, 1995| work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]| publisher=elpais.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011|language=es}}</ref> In 2010, another remake with the title ''Las chicas de oro'' (''The Golden Girls'') was announced, again on [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]], this time produced by Jos\u00e9 Luis Moreno and with [[Concha Velasco]] as Doroti (Dorothy), [[Carmen Maura]] as Rosa (Rose), [[Lola Herrera]] as Blanca (Blanche), and Alicia Hermida as Sof\u00eda (Sophia).<ref name=\"vertele\">{{cite web| title=TVE presenta el remake: 'Volvemos a la sitcom pero con valor seguro'| date=July 27, 2010| publisher=vertele.com| url=http://www.vertele.com/noticias/27930/lograr-reparto-asi-historico| accessdate=June 24, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129083629/http://www.vertele.com/noticias/27930/lograr-reparto-asi-historico| archivedate=November 29, 2010| language=es}}</ref> The series premiered on September 13, 2010 with success.<ref name=\"de oro\">{{cite web| title=\"Las Chicas de Oro\" relucen en su estreno con 4 millones| date=September 14, 2010| url=http://www.vertele.com/noticias/28445/chicas-oro-relucen-estreno-millones| publisher=vertele.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118103844/http://www.vertele.com/noticias/28445/chicas-oro-relucen-estreno-millones| archivedate=November 18, 2010| language=es}}</ref> However, after only 26 episodes, the series was eventually discontinued after the end of the first season after receiving generally bad reviews and following dropping ratings.<ref name=\"de oro2\">{{cite web| title='Las Chicas de Oro' espa\u00f1olas ni son renovadas ni lo merec\u00edan| date=December 14, 2010| url=http://www.vayatele.com/tve-1/las-chicas-de-oro-espanolas-ni-son-renovadas-ni-lo-merecian| publisher=vertele.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n* Portugal: ''Queridas e Maduras'': In July 1995, [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] premiered ''Queridas e Maduras'' (in English, ''Dear Mature Girls'') a Portuguese version of the American sitcom. The show featured renowned Portuguese actresses [[Catarina Avelar]] as ''Edite'' (Dorothy), [[Am\u00e9lia Videira]] as ''In\u00eas'' (Rose), [[Lia Gama]] as ''Salom\u00e9'' (Blanche) and the veteran actress [[Lu\u00edsa Barbosa]] as ''Aparecida'' (Sophia). The Portuguese version got two seasons, the first in 1995 and the second in 1996, adapting episode plots from the first two seasons of the original series.\n* Turkey: ''{{interlanguage link|Altin Kizlar|tr|Altin Kizlar|vertical-align=sup}}''. In 2009, broadcaster [[ATV (Turkey)|ATV]] ''{{interlanguage link|Actual Television|tr|Akt\u00fcel Televizyon|vertical-align=sup}}'' premiered ''Altin Kizlar'' (literally translated to English as \"Girls of Gold\"). It was produced by Play Prod\u00fcksiyon. Rather than residing in Miami, the women shared a condo in residential part of [[Beyo\u011flu]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bal\u0131ksirt\u0131 |first1=\u015eeng\u00fcl |url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/yazarlar/gunaydin/baliksirti/2009/05/08/altin_kizlarin_setine_gizli_kamera_koymak_gerek |accessdate=16 September 2018 |ref=altinkizlar-sabah |location=Istanbul, Turkey |language=tr|title=Altin Kizlar'in Setine Gizli Kamera Koymak Gerek}}</ref> As in other foreign adaptations, it featured well-known local actresses. The key roles were filled by [[Fatma Girik]] as ''Saf\u0131ye'' (the 'Sophia' character), [[H\u00fclya Ko\u00e7yi\u011fit]] as ''\u0130smet'' ('Dorothy'), [[Nevra Serezli]] as ''G\u00f6n\u00fcl'' ('Blanche') and [[T\u00fcrkan \u015eoray]] as ''Inci'' ('Rose').<ref>{{Citation|title=Altin kizlar|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5986310/|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> The show lasted only one episode, consisting of story lines from two of the original American series: \"[https://www.thetvdb.com/series/the-golden-girls/episodes/41323 The Engagement]\" (Season 1, Episode 1) and \"[https://www.thetvdb.com/series/the-golden-girls/episodes/41327 The Triangle]\" (Season 1, Episode 5). \n* United Kingdom: ''[[The Brighton Belles|Brighton Belles]]'': In 1993, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] premiered ''Brighton Belles'', a British version of the American sitcom.<ref>{{cite news| title= Heard the one about the US sense of humour?| publisher=Independent.co.uk| work=The Independent| date=August 30, 2000| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/heard-the-one-about-the-us-sense-of-humour-696765.html| accessdate=September 9, 2010| location=London| first=Brian| last=Viner}}</ref> The show, starring [[Sheila Hancock]], [[Wendy Craig]], [[Sheila Gish]], and [[Jean Boht]] was nearly identical to ''Girls'' except for character name changes and actor portrayals. The 10-episode series was canceled after six weeks due to low ratings, with the final four episodes airing more than a year later.\n\n==Restaurant==\nIn 2017 a ''Golden Girls''-themed eatery Rue La Rue Cafe owned by Rue McLanahan's close friend Michael La Rue, who inherited many of the star's personal belongings and in turn decorated the restaurant with them, opened in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] section of the [[New York City]] borough of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=AM>{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' cafe Rue La Rue has soft opening in Washington Heights| first=Jillian| last=Jorgensen| url=http://www.amny.com/eat-and-drink/golden-girls-cafe-rue-la-rue-has-soft-opening-in-washington-heights-1.13075453| date=February 8, 2017| newspaper=[[AM New York]]| accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> The eatery closed in November 2017 after less than a year of operation.<ref name=WNBC>{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Cafe in Manhattan Closes After Less Than a Year| url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Golden-Girls-Cafe-in-Manhattan-Closes-After-Less-Than-a-Year-458880873.html| date=November 20, 2017| work=[[WNBC]] News| accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{cite book |title = Golden Girls Forever: An Unauthorized Look Behind the Lanai |last = Colucci|first = Jim |year = 2016 |publisher = Harper Collins |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-06-242290-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=The Golden Girls|id=0088526}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-golden-girls|The Golden Girls}}\n* {{epguides|id=GoldenGirls}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070701180551/http://thegoldengirls.wetpaint.com/ @ccess ''The Golden Girls'' Wiki]\n* [http://www.museum.tv/eotv/goldengirls.htm Encyclopedia of Television]\n* {{EmmyTVLegends title|golden-girls-the|The Golden Girls}}\n   \n{{Golden Girls}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Golden Girls|Awards for ''The Golden Girls'']]\n|list =\n{{EmmyAward ComedySeries 1976-2000}}\n{{GoldenGlobeTVComedy}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite New TV Comedy}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden Girls, The}}\n[[Category:The Golden Girls| ]]\n[[Category:1985 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1992 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1990s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Series Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Miami]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series winners]]\n[[Category:Television series about suburbia]]\n[[Category:Television series about old age]]\n[[Category:Works about old age]]\n[[Category:American television shows]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the 1995 Hong Kong film|The Golden Girls (film)|other uses|Golden Girl (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American sitcom (1985 - 1992)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = The Golden Girls\n| image          = Golden Girls title.svg\n| genre          = [[Sitcom]]\n| creator        = [[Susan Harris]]\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n*[[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]]\n*[[Betty White]]\n*[[Rue McClanahan]]\n*[[Estelle Getty]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Andrew Gold]]\n| opentheme      = \"[[Thank You for Being a Friend]]\" written by Andrew Gold sung by Cynthia Fee\n| endtheme       = \"Thank You for Being a Friend\" Instrumental\n| composer       = [[George Tipton]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| num_seasons    = 7\n| num_episodes   = 180\n| list_episodes  = List of The Golden Girls episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plain list|\n*[[Susan Harris]]\n*[[Paul Junger Witt]]\n*[[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]]\n}}\n| camera         = [[Videotape]], [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime        = 22\u201324 minutes\n| company        = {{Plain list|\n*[[Witt/Thomas Productions|Witt/Thomas/Harris Productions]]\n*[[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]<ref>https://thewaltdisneycompany.com</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]] (current)\n| network        = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Aspect ratio|4:3]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| audio_format   = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired    = {{Start date|1985|9|14}}\n| last_aired     = {{End date|1992|5|9}}\n| followed_by    = ''[[The Golden Palace]]''\n| related        = {{Plain list|\n*''[[Empty Nest]]''\n*''[[Nurses (American TV series)|Nurses]]''\n}}\n| website        =\n}}\n\n'''''The Golden Girls''''' is an American [[sitcom]] television series created by [[Susan Harris]] that originally aired on [[NBC]] from September 14, 1985, to May 9, 1992, with a total of 180 half-hour episodes spanning seven seasons. The show stars [[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]], [[Betty White]], [[Rue McClanahan]], and [[Estelle Getty]] as four older women who share friendship, and a home in [[Miami, Florida]]. It was produced by [[Witt/Thomas Productions|Witt/Thomas/Harris Productions]], in association with [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]], and [[Paul Junger Witt]]. [[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]] and Harris served as the original executive producers.\n\n''The Golden Girls'' received critical acclaim throughout most of its run and won several awards including the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]] twice. It also won three [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Awards for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news| title='L.A. Law' and 'Golden Girls' Win Series Emmys| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/21/arts/la-law-and-golden-girls-win-series-emmys.html| accessdate=November 8, 2013| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=September 21, 1987| agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Each of the four stars received an [[Emmy Award]], making it one of only three sitcoms in the award's history to achieve this. The series also ranked among the Nielsen ratings Top 10 for six of its seven seasons.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Galician| first1=Mary-Lou| last2=Merskin| first2=Debra L.| title=Critical Thinking About Sex, Love, and Romance In the Mass Media: Media Literacy Applications| year=2007| publisher=Psychology Press| isbn=978-0-8058-5615-6| page=109}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[TV Guide]]'' ranked ''The Golden Girls'' number 54 on its list of the 60 Best Series of All Time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/tv-guide-magazine-60-best-series-1074962/|title=TV Guide Magazine's 60 Best Series of All Time|work=TV Guide}}</ref> In 2014, the [[Writers Guild of America]] placed the sitcom at number 69 in their list of the \"101 Best Written TV Series of All Time\".<ref name=best101>{{cite web| title='101 Best Written TV Series Of All Time' From WGA/TV Guide: Complete List| url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/06/wgas-101-best-written-tv-series-of-all-time-complete-list/| date=June 2, 2013| website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe show had an [[ensemble cast]] and the plot revolves around four older single women (three widows and one divorc\u00e9e) sharing a house in Miami. The owner of the house is a widow named [[Blanche Devereaux]] (McClanahan), who was joined by fellow widow [[Rose Nylund]] (White) and divorc\u00e9e [[Dorothy Zbornak]] (Arthur), after they both responded to an ad on the bulletin board of a local grocery store a year before the start of the series. In the pilot episode, the three were joined by Dorothy's 80-year-old mother, [[Sophia Petrillo]] (Getty), after the [[retirement home]] where she had been living burned down.<ref>{{cite news| last=Bosman| first=Julie| title=The Grandchildren of 'The Golden Girls'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/08/business/media/08adco.html| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=The New York Times| date=November 8, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Du Brow| first=Rick| title='Golden Girl' Getty Will Miss Her TV 'Daughter'| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-28/entertainment/ca-840_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=April 28, 1992}}</ref>\n\n===Pilot===\nThe first episode featured a cook/butler named Coco (played by [[Charles Levin (actor)|Charles Levin]]), but the role was dropped before the second episode. The writers observed that in many of the proposed scripts, the main interaction between the women occurred in the kitchen while preparing and eating food. They decided that a separate cook would distract from their friendship. In addition, the character of Sophia had originally been planned as an occasional guest star, but Getty had tested so positively with preview audiences that the producers decided to make her a regular character.<ref>{{cite web| last=Kovalchik |first=Kara |title=7 Things You Might Not Know About The Golden Girls From Mental Floss |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/19134/7-things-you-might-not-know-about-golden-girls/ |accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Finale===\nAfter six consecutive seasons in the top 10, and the seventh season at number 30, ''The Golden Girls'' came to an end when Bea Arthur chose to leave the series. In the hour-long [[series finale]], which aired in May 1992, Dorothy meets and marries Blanche's uncle Lucas ([[Leslie Nielsen]]) and moves to Hollingsworth Manor in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Sophia was to join her, but in the end, she stays behind with the other women in Miami. This led into the spin-off series, ''[[The Golden Palace]]''.\n\nThe series finale of The Golden Girls was watched by 27.2 million viewers. As of 2016, it was the 17th-most watched television finale.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morin|first1=Natalie|title=These Are the Most-Watched TV Series Finales of All Time|url=http://tv-shows.prettyfamous.com/stories/21670/tv-series-episode-finales-popular-mash-cheers-friends#80-The-Golden-Girls-One-Flew-Out-of-the-Cuckoo-s-Nest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026121844/http://tv-shows.prettyfamous.com/stories/21670/tv-series-episode-finales-popular-mash-cheers-friends#80-The-Golden-Girls-One-Flew-Out-of-the-Cuckoo-s-Nest|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 26, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of The Golden Girls episodes}}\n{{:List of The Golden Girls episodes}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Main===\n[[File:Golden Girls cast miami song.png|thumb|Main characters in the final scene from the season two episode \"Big Daddy's Little Lady\" (''from left''): Estelle Getty as Sophia, Rue McClanahan as Blanche, Betty White as Rose, and Beatrice Arthur as Dorothy]]\n\n* [[Bea Arthur|Beatrice Arthur]] as [[Dorothy Zbornak]] (n\u00e9e Petrillo), a substitute teacher. Born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], to Sicilian immigrants Sophia and Salvadore Petrillo, Dorothy became pregnant while still in [[high school]], resulting in a marriage to Stanley Zbornak ([[Herb Edelman]]) [[shotgun wedding|to legitimize the baby]]. Stan and Dorothy eventually moved to Miami, but divorced after 38 years when Stan left her for a young flight attendant. The marriage produced two children; Kate, in her early 20s, and Michael, who was inconsistently aged between his mid-20s and late 30s (Michael was purportedly the cause of the shotgun wedding). In the series' final episode, Dorothy marries Blanche's uncle, Lucas Hollingsworth, and relocates to Atlanta. Arthur also played Dorothy's grandmother, Sophia's mother, in a flashback episode to when they lived in Brooklyn in the 1950s when Dorothy was a young adult (even though two episodes -- \"My Father, my Brother\" and \"The Days and Nights of Sophia Petrillo\" stated that Sophia's mother died when Dorothy was younger). In season one episode seven, Dorothy is stated to be 55.\n* [[Betty White]] as [[Rose Nylund]] (n\u00e9e Lindstr\u00f6m), a [[Norwegian American]] from the small farming town of [[St. Olaf, Minnesota]]. Often slightly naive and known for her humorously peculiar stories of life growing up in her hometown, Rose was happily married to Charlie Nylund, with whom she had five children; daughters Kirsten, Bridget, Gunilla; and sons Adam and Charlie, Jr. Upon Charlie's death, she moved to Miami. She eventually finds work at a grief counseling center, but later switches careers and becomes assistant to consumer reporter Enrique Mas at a local TV station. In later seasons, Rose became romantically involved with college professor Miles Webber. During season six, Webber was placed into the [[United States Federal Witness Protection Program|Witness Protection Program]], but returned later in the season. Their relationship continued throughout the series and shortly into the sequel series, ''The Golden Palace''.\n* [[Rue McClanahan]] as [[Blanche Devereaux]] (n\u00e9e Hollingsworth), a [[Southern belle]] employed at an art museum. Born into a wealthy family, Blanche grew up as the apple of her father's eye on a [[plantations in the American South|plantation]] outside of Atlanta, Georgia, prior to her relocation to Miami, where she lived with her husband, George, until his death. Their marriage produced six children; daughters Janet and Rebecca; and sons Doug, Biff, Skippy, and Matthew. A widow, Blanche was portrayed as man-hungry and clearly had the most male admirers and stories detailing various sexual encounters over the course of the series.\n* [[Estelle Getty]] as [[Sophia Petrillo]]<!-- If adding maiden name, please cite an episode or reliable source for verifiability -->, Dorothy's mother. Born in [[Sicily]], Sophia moved to New York after fleeing an [[arranged marriage]] to Guido Spirelli. She married Salvadore \"Sal\" Petrillo, with whom she had three children: Dorothy, Gloria, and Phil, a cross-dresser who later dies of a heart attack (episode \"[[Ebbtide's Revenge]]\"). Initially a resident of the Shady Pines retirement home after having a stroke prior to the start of the series, she moved in with Blanche, Rose, and Dorothy following a fire at the institution. During the series' run, Sophia married Max Weinstock, but they soon separated. Throughout the series, she held a few part-time jobs, mostly involving food, including as a fast-food worker and an entrepreneur of spaghetti sauce and homemade sandwiches.\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Herb Edelman]] as Stanley Zbornak, Dorothy's cheating, freeloading ex-husband who left her to marry a young flight attendant, who later left him. Stan married another woman in season 4, and they divorced off-screen in season 5. Stanley worked as an unsuccessful novelty salesman until he became a successful entrepreneur by inventing a baked potato opener that made him wealthy.\n* [[Harold Gould]] as Miles Webber (or Nicholas Carbone/Samuel Plankmaker) is Rose's professor boyfriend from season 5 onwards. In season 6, Miles reveals he is in the witness protection program and was a bookkeeper for a mobster. Gould also guest-starred once in the first season as Arnie Peterson, Rose's first serious boyfriend after her husband Charlie's death.\n* [[Sid Melton]] as Salvadore Petrillo, Sophia's late husband, who is usually seen in dreams or flashback sequences. Melton also appears as Don the Fool, a waiter at a medieval restaurant in season six.\n* Shawn Schepps and Debra Engle, as Blanche's daughter, Rebecca Devereaux. Initially an overweight former model in an emotionally abusive relationship, she later slimmed down and had a baby girl named Aurora by [[artificial insemination]].\n* [[Monte Markham]] and [[Sheree North]] as Blanche's siblings Clayton Hollingsworth and Virginia Hollingsworth. Virginia and Blanche were estranged for a long time, until they reconciled in season 1. They became estranged in season 5 after their father's funeral. Clayton is a closeted gay man who had troubled coming out to Blanche, who eventually accepted his orientation when Clayton and his new boyfriend got married.\n* [[Bill Dana]] and [[Nancy Walker]] as Sophia's siblings Angelo and Angela. Dana appears in seven episodes (seasons 3-7), while he also played Sophia's father in a season-four episode. Walker starred in two episodes in season 2.\n* [[Doris Belack]] and [[Dena Dietrich]] as Gloria Petrillo, Dorothy's younger sister who is married to a wealthy man in California. In a two-part episode, she has lost all of her money and becomes romantically involved with Stan, but she eventually comes to think of him as a \"yutz\" and breaks up with him.\n* [[Scott Jacoby (actor)|Scott Jacoby]] as Dorothy's traveling musician son Michael Zbornak.\n* [[Lynnie Greene]] (credited as Lynn Greene) as a younger Dorothy in flashbacks.\n* [[Lisa Jane Persky]] and [[Deena Freeman]], as Dorothy's daughter, Kate Zbornak who is in interior decorator in New York and married to Dennis who is a successful foot doctor.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Creation===\n{|class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; margin-right:2em; font-size:95%; color:black; width:35em; max-width:50%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|\"I was running all over the house grabbing anybody who would listen. I kept reading scenes to them and saying, 'God, this is brilliant [...] There's nothing trendy about this show. There are no tricks. It's a classic.\"\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\" |\u2014NBC executive [[Warren Littlefield]] about reading the pilot script<ref name=\"ew-2\">{{cite news| first=Nicholas| last=Fonseca| title=Golden Girls: A 20th Anniversary Oral History| date=April 24, 2009| url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1100651_2,00.html| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]| accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\nIdeas for a comedy series about older women emerged during the filming of a television special at [[NBC]]'s Warner Bros. Studios in [[Burbank, California]], in August 1984.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> Produced to introduce the network's [[1984\u201385 United States network television schedule|1984\u201385 season schedule]], two actresses appearing on NBC shows, [[Selma Diamond]] of ''[[Night Court]]'' and [[Doris Roberts]] of ''[[Remington Steele]]'', appeared in a skit promoting the upcoming show ''[[Miami Vice]]'' as ''Miami Nice'', a parody about old people living in Miami.<ref name=\"Schwartz\">{{cite journal| last=Schwartz| first=Tony| title=The Real Mr. T| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7gBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=September 30, 1985| journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]| page=42| issn=0028-7369}}</ref> NBC senior vice president [[Warren Littlefield]] was among the executive producers in the audience who were amused by their performance, and he envisioned a series based on the geriatric humor the two were portraying.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/>\n\nShortly afterward, he met with producers Paul Junger Witt and [[Tony Thomas (producer)|Tony Thomas]], who were pitching a show about a female lawyer. Though Littlefield nixed their idea, he asked if they would be interested in delivering a [[television pilot|pilot script]] for ''Miami Nice'' instead. Their regular writer declined, so Witt asked his wife, [[Susan Harris]],<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> who had been planning to retire after the conclusion of their ABC series ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''.<ref name=\"Fitzharris\">{{cite web| last=Fitzharris| first=Dustin |title=Catching Up with the Golden Girls' Susan Harris| url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/television/2010/10/03/catching-golden-girls-susan-harris| work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=October 4, 2010}}</ref> She found the concept interesting, as \"it was a demographic that had never been addressed,\" and she soon began work on it.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> Though her vision of a sitcom about women in their 60s differed from NBC's request for a comedy about women around 40 years old,<ref name=\"Prague\">{{cite web| first=Jacke| last=Prague| date=April 8, 2010| title=Crackle's Creator Conversation: Soap's Susan Harris| url=http://www.crackle.com/blog/crackles-creator-conversation-soaps-susan-harris/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227145150/http://www.crackle.com/blog/crackles-creator-conversation-soaps-susan-harris/| archivedate=December 27, 2010| work=Crackle| publisher=Crackle.com| accessdate=June 9, 2011}}</ref> Littlefield was impressed when he received her pilot script and subsequently approved production of it.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/> ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' director [[Jay Sandrich]], who had previously worked with Harris, Witt, and Thomas on ''Soap'', agreed to direct.<ref name=\"Cronin\">{{cite web| last=Cronin| first=Brian| title=TV Legends Revealed #35| url=http://legendsrevealed.com/entertainment/2011/01/14/tv-legends-revealed-35/| publisher=Legends Revealed| accessdate=January 14, 2010| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119085507/http://legendsrevealed.com/entertainment/2011/01/14/tv-legends-revealed-35/| archivedate=January 19, 2011| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe pilot included a gay houseboy, Coco ([[Charles Levin (actor)|Charles Levin]]), who lived with the girls. Levin had been suggested by then-NBC president [[Brandon Tartikoff]] based on  Levin's groundbreaking portrayal of a recurring gay character, Eddie Gregg, on NBC's Emmy-winning drama ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''. After the pilot, the character of Coco was eliminated from the series.<ref name=\"Colucci\">{{cite book| last=Colucci| first=Jim| title=The Q Guide to the Golden Girls| year=2006| publisher=Alyson Books| pages=8, 43\u201355}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloom\">{{cite book |last1=Bloom |first1=Ken |last2=Vlastnik |first2=Frank |last3=Lithgow |first3=John |title=Sitcoms: The 101 Greatest TV Comedies of All Time |year=2007 |publisher=Black Dog Publishing |isbn=978-1-57912-752-7 |page=137}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Rue McClanahan book signing.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Rue McClanahan]] in 2007]]\n\nThe part of [[Sophia Petrillo]] was the first of the four roles to be cast. Estelle Getty auditioned and won the role of the feisty mother of character [[Dorothy Zbornak]]. This was due, in part, to the rave reviews she garnered in her Off-Broadway role reprisal for the 1984 Los Angeles run of ''[[Torch Song Trilogy]]''. Afterwards, Getty had returned to New York but gained permission from her manager to return to California in early 1985. Getty figured it would be her last chance to find television or film work. She would return home to New York if she was unsuccessful.\n\nCasting director Judith Weiner had seen ''Torch Song Trilogy'' and thought Getty was terrific in it. She was also impressed by Getty's audition for the role of the mother of Steven Keaton (played by actor [[Michael Gross (actor)|Michael Gross]]) for a guest episode of ''[[Family Ties]]''. Although Getty was impressive, the show's producers went with another actress. Getty came to Weiner's mind soon after when it became time to begin casting of ''The Golden Girls.''<ref>Colucci, Jim. ''Golden Girls Forever''. HarperCollins Publishers Inc, 2016.</ref>\n\nGetty, who went through a three-hour transformation to become Sophia, wore heavy make-up, thick glasses, and a white wig to look the part.<ref name=\"Kinosian\">{{cite book| last=Kinosian| first=Janet| title=Making Up Is Hard to Do| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=52AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA157| accessdate=November 8, 2013| date=February 1, 1988| work=[[Orange Coast (magazine)|Orange Coast]]| page=157| issn=0279-0483}}</ref> The character of Sophia was thought by the creators to enhance the idea that three retirement-aged women could be young. Disney's [[Michael Eisner]] explains, \"Estelle Getty made our three women into girls. And that was, to me, what made it seem like it could be a contemporary, young show.\"<ref name=\"legend\">{{cite web| title=The Golden Girls| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/shows/golden-girls-the| publisher=Archive of American Television| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> As surprising as it might sound, Estelle Getty continuously battled her stage fright. During an interview in 1988, Getty commented on her phobia and expressed how working with major stars, such as Arthur and White, made her even more nervous. At times, she even froze on camera while filming.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 20 Fun Facts About 'The Golden Girls'|url = http://mentalfloss.com/article/56215/20-fun-facts-about-golden-girls|website = [[Mental Floss]]|access-date = February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHired to film the pilot, director Jay Sandrich also became instrumental in helping to cast the roles of Blanche Devereaux and Rose Nylund. Both Rue McClanahan and Betty White came into consideration as the series ''[[Mama's Family]]'', in which the two co-starred, had been canceled by NBC. Originally, producers wanted to cast McClanahan as Rose and White as Blanche. The thinking for this was based on roles they previously played; White portrayed man-hungry [[Sue Ann Nivens]] on ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'', while McClanahan co-starred as sweet but scatter-brained [[Vivian Harmon]] in ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]''. Eager not to be [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]], they took the suggestion of Sandrich and switched roles last-minute.<ref name=\"ew-2\"/><ref name=\"Bloom\"/>\n\nIn the pilot script, Blanche was described as \"more Southern than [[Blanche DuBois]]\", so McClanahan was perplexed when she was asked by director Sandrich during the filming of the pilot not to use the strong [[Southern American English|southern accent]] she had developed, but to use her natural Oklahoma accent instead.<ref name=\"emmytv\">{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y_DGIgDOg6c| title=Rue McClanahan on Blanche's accent on \"The Golden Girls\"- EMMYTVLEGENDS.org| author=emmytvlegends.org| publisher=YouTube.com| date=June 11, 2010| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref> Once the show was picked up for a first season, the new director [[Paul Bogart]] felt exactly the opposite, insisting that McClanahan use a Southern accent. McClanahan deliberately exaggerated her accent, stating \"I played Blanche the way I felt Blanche. She thought an accentuated Southern accent...would be sexy and strong and attractive to men. She wanted to be a southern heroine, like [[Vivien Leigh]]. In fact, that's who I think she thought she was.\"<ref>{{cite book| title=Golden Girls Forever| first=Jim| last=Colucci| publisher=Harper Collins| year=2016| p=34}}</ref>\n\nThough Harris had created the character of Dorothy with a \"Bea Arthur type\" in mind, Littlefield and the producers initially envisioned actress [[Elaine Stritch]] for the part.<ref name=\"Bloom\"/> Stritch's audition flopped, however, and under the impression that Arthur did not want to participate, Harris asked McClanahan if she could persuade Arthur, with whom she worked previously on the CBS sitcom ''Maude'', to take the role. Arthur flipped upon reading the script, but felt hesitant about McClanahan's approach, as she did not \"want to play (their ''Maude'' characters) Maude and Vivian meet Sue Ann Nivens.\" She reconsidered, however, after hearing that McClanahan and White had switched roles.\n\nBea Arthur and Betty White worked well together in shared mutual respect but they did not pursue a personal friendship with one another outside of ''The Golden Girls'' set. Arthur's son, Matthew Saks, later spoke of tension between the two actresses, stating that his mother \"unknowingly carried the attitude that it was fun to have somebody to be angry at...It was almost like Betty became her nemesis, someone she could always roll her eyes about at work.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.closerweekly.com/posts/bea-arthur-feud-betty-white-golden-girls-138841/?display=listicle| title=Betty White and Bea Arthur's Friends Open Up About Their On-Set Feud| publisher=closerweekly.com}}</ref> Both actresses had dramatically different training and acting backgrounds; Saks commented on White's habit of [[breaking the fourth wall]] to engage and joke with the studio audience during breaks between filming, which Bea Arthur found unprofessional.<ref name=\"Michelle Darrisaw\">{{cite article|  url=https://www.southernliving.com/culture/betty-white-bea-arthur-golden-girls-feud| title=Say It Isn't So, Girls! Details on Betty White and Bea Arthur's Off-Screen Feud| author=Michelle Darrisaw| publisher=Southern Living| date=|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> In 2011 White stated that she believed it was her \"positive attitude\" and perky demeanor which got on Arthur's nerves.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web| title=CNN Official Interview: Betty White: Bea Arthur was not fond of me| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i-wTJ2hQCK8| publisher=CNN| date=May 4, 2011| accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Writing and taping===\nThe show was the second television series to be produced by the Walt Disney Company under the [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]] label, and was subsequently distributed by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista International, Inc.]] (which holds as the ownership stake in [[Disney Channel (Southeast Asia)|Disney Channel Southeast Asia]], now [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group]]).<ref name=\"studios\">{{cite web| title=ABC Studios| url=http://tviv.org/ABC_Studios| publisher=The TV IV| date=August 30, 2007| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCreator Susan Harris went on to contribute another four episodes to the first season, but became less involved with the sitcom throughout its run; she continued reading all scripts, though, and remained familiar with most of the storylines. Kathy Speer and Terry Grossman were the first head writers of the series and wrote for the show's first four seasons. As head writers, Speer and Grossman, along with Mort Nathan and Barry Fanaro, who won an Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing the first season, gave general ideas to lower staff writers, and personally wrote a handful of scripts each season.<ref name=\"Mills\">{{cite news| last=Mills| first=Nancy| title='Golden Girls' Polishes Its Scripts: Daily Revisions Geared to Sharpen Story and Hone Those Laugh Lines| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-10-30/entertainment/ca-11702_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=October 30, 1987}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Marc Sotkin, previously a writer on ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' and a producer on fellow Witt/Thomas series ''[[It's a Living (1980 TV series)|It's a Living]]'', assumed head-writing responsibilities, and guided the show (to varying degrees) during what were its final three seasons. Richard Vaczy and Tracy Gamble, previously writers on ''[[227 (TV series)|227]]'' and ''[[My Two Dads]]'', also assumed the roles of producers and head writers. Beginning in 1990, [[Marc Cherry]] served as writer and producer, years before creating ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'', which ran on ABC from 2004 to 2012.<ref name=\"Mills\"/> [[Mitchell Hurwitz]] also served as writer for the show in its last two seasons. Hurwitz later created ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and later for Netflix.\n\nCherry commented on [[read-through]]s of the scripts that \"generally, if the joke was a good one, the women found a way to make it work the very first time they read it. You have a lot of table reads where the actors will mess it up because they don't understand what the characters are doing, or they misinterpret. But the women were so uniformly brilliant at nailing it the first time...we basically knew that if the women didn't get it right the first time, the joke needed to be replaced.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/02/marc-cherry-remembers-writing-for-golden-girls.html| title=Marc Cherry Shares His Memories of Writing for Golden Girls| first=Josef| last=Adalian| journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]| date=February 28, 2013| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEstelle Getty's [[stage fright]], which affected her from the beginning of the show, grew worse as the show went on, to the point that she would forget her lines more and more. Beginning in Season 5, she would have to read her lines off cue cards held off-camera or from props.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/flashback/golden-girls-werent-so-chummy-off-the-screen-stars-son-reveals/news-story/6f1a33f4d0f9713751c5efdd5b371141| title=Golden Girls weren't so chummy off the screen, star\u2019s son reveals| first=Stephanie| last=Nolasco| publisher=Fox News| via=news.com.au| date=November 9, 2017| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref> Rue McClanahan, who shared a dressing room with Getty, described the severity of Getty's stage fright: \"She'd panic. She would start getting under a dark cloud the day before tape day...You could see a big difference in her that day. She'd be walking around like [[Pig-Pen]] under a black cloud. By tape day, she was unreachable. She was just as uptight as a human being could get. When your brain is frozen like that, you can't remember lines.\"<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SaDIbjIXnlM| title=Rue McClanahan Interview - Part 4 of 5 - EMMYTVLEGENDS.org| author=Emmytvlegends.org| publisher=YouTube.com| date=September 9, 2009| access-date=September 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring season six there was some uncertainty over whether Bea Arthur would commit to future seasons, or leave the show once her contract expired to pursue other projects.<ref name=\"Unauthorized\"/><ref name=\"Lifetime\">{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E6lZupLt8HU| title=Bea Arthur 2002 Intimate Portrait (HD)| publisher=YouTube.com| date=September 17, 2016| access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> Arthur had expressed weariness with doing the show, and had also grown frustrated with the disparaging jokes made about her physical appearance which were often in the script.<ref name=\"Michelle Darrisaw\"/> [[Debbie Reynolds]] was brought on as a guest star in the season 6 episode \"There Goes the Bride: Part 2\" to test her chemistry with the other actresses as a possible replacement for Arthur, but it was decided that nobody could replicate the chemistry of the four original actresses. In any event, Arthur chose to commit to a seventh and final season.<ref name=\"Unauthorized\">{{cite book| title=Golden Girls Forever: An Unauthorized Look Behind the Lanai| first=Jim| last=Colucci| publisher=Harper Design| year=2016| pages=255\u201356}}</ref>\n\n===Exterior and interior sets===\nThe house's address was mentioned as being 6151 Richmond Street, Miami.<ref name=\"Terrace2011\">{{cite book| last=Terrace| first=Vincent| title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 Through 2010| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YX_daEhlnbsC&pg=PT2528| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2011| publisher=McFarland| isbn=978-0-7864-8641-0| page=2528}}</ref> The model used for exterior shots of the house from the third season through the end of the series was part of the backstage studio tour ride at Disney's Hollywood Studios. This fa\u00e7ade, along with the ''Empty Nest'' house, sustained hurricane damage leading to Disney's 2003 decision to bulldoze the houses of \"Residential Street\" and construct its \"Lights, Motors, Action!\" attraction. The fa\u00e7ade was based on a real house at 245 N. Saltair Avenue in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles, California]]. Producers used this residence for exterior shots during the first two seasons.<ref>{{Coord|34.066|-118.4474|display=inline|region:GB_scale:5000}}</ref>\n\nThe show's designer, Ed Stephenson, took inspiration from his time living in Florida to design a \"Florida look\" for ''The Golden Girls'' house set. The wooden accents, columns, and doors were painted to mimic [[Taxodium distichum|Bald cypress]] wood, popular in South Florida homes, with [[rattan]] furniture and tropical-printed upholstery chosen for the furniture.<ref>Colucci 2016 p. 317-318</ref>\n\nThe kitchen set seen on ''The Golden Girls'' was originally used on an earlier Witt/Thomas/Harris series, ''[[It Takes Two (American TV series)|It Takes Two]]'', which aired on ABC from 1982 to 1983. However, the exterior backdrop seen through the kitchen window changed from the view of Chicago [[high-rise]]s to palm trees and bushes for the Miami setting. Space was limited on the soundstage, so when the kitchen was off camera it was usually detached from the rest of the set and the space used for something else. The doorway from the living room, with the alcove and baker's shelf just inside, was designed to give the illusion that the actors were walking in and out of the kitchen.<ref>Colucci, 2016 pg. 324</ref>\n\n===Costumes===\nCostume designer Judy Evans created distinctive looks for each of the four actresses to suit their character's personalities and to reflect the Florida setting. According to Evans \"I wanted a sexy, soft, and flowing look for Rue, a tailored, pulled-together look for Bea, a down-home look for Betty, and comfort for Estelle.\"<ref>Colucci, 2016, p. 333</ref> Anna Wyckoff of the [[Costume Designers Guild]] wrote that \"Evans took the direction from the producers to create a vibrant look for the four mature leads, and ran with it...redefining what \u201cdressing your age\u201d looked like.\"<ref>{{cite article| url=https://costumedesignersguild.com/articles-videos/articles-archive/costume-design-costars/| title=The Changing Face of Modern Television: When Costume Design Costars| first=Anna| last=Wyckoff| magazine=The Costume Designer| date=Spring 2012| access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Many of the character's outfits were designed by Evans and made specially, but there were between seven and ten costume changes per episode between the four actresses, which entailed a great deal of [[off the rack]] shopping.<ref name=\"Colucci, 2016 pg. 333\">Colucci, 2016 pg. 333</ref> Evans generally dressed the actresses in expensive pieces and high quality fabrics, despite the recurring theme that the four characters were struggling with money, because \"The main idea was to make them look good. We didn't want the show to be about four dowdy ladies.\"<ref name=\"Colucci, 2016 pg. 333\"/>\n\nBea Arthur had a preference for wearing loose fitting clothing, like slacks and long sweaters, along with sandals because she hated wearing shoes. She had established this signature look while playing [[Maude Findlay|Maude]], and Evans honored it in her designs for Dorothy.<ref>{{cite article| url=https://nypost.com/2002/01/28/bea-ing-stylishformer-golden-girl-bea-arthur-talks-about-comfort-clothes-going-barefoot-and-her-famous-maude-wardrobe/| title=Bea-ing Stylish: Former \u201cGolden Girl\u201d Bea Arthur Talks About Comfort Clothes, Going Barefoot and Her Famous \u201cMaude\u201d Wardrobe| first=Barbara| last=Hoffman| newspaper=New York Post| date=2002-01-28| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> Much of Arthur's wardrobe was custom-made because at the time it was difficult to find off-the-rack clothing that was flattering for a taller woman.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 333</ref> Rue McClanahan had a special clause written into her contract allowing her to keep her costumes, which were mostly custom-made using expensive fabrics.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 338</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/54393/7-must-have-items-rue-mcclanahans-estate-sale| title=7 Must-Have Items from Rue McClanahan's Estate Sale| first=Kara| last=Kovalchik| publisher=Mentalfloss.com| date=2014-01-14| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> Eventually McClanahan went on to create a clothing line for [[QVC]], called \"A Touch of Rue\", inspired by Blanche but made with affordable fabrics and practical designs.<ref>Colucci, 2016, 339</ref>\n\n===Format===\n''The Golden Girls'' was shot on videotape in front of a live studio audience.<ref name=\"Rosewarne2012\">{{cite book| last=Rosewarne| first=Lauren| title=Periods in Pop Culture: Menstruation in Film and Television| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m0Ti0d-T4DwC&pg=PA188| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2012| publisher=Lexington Books| isbn=978-0-7391-7000-7| page=188}}</ref> Many episodes of the series followed a similar format or theme. For example, one or more of the women would become involved in some sort of problem, often involving other family members, men, or an ethical dilemma. At some point, they would gather around the kitchen table and discuss the problem, sometimes late at night and often while eating [[cheesecake]], ice cream or some other dessert.<ref name=\"DeCaro2011\">{{cite book| last=DeCaro| first=Frank| title=The Dead Celebrity Cookbook: A Resurrection of Recipes from More Than 145 Stars of Stage and Screen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILvGSUX7olkC&pg=PA352| accessdate=August 8, 2013| year=2011| publisher=Health Communications Inc.| isbn=978-0-7573-1596-1| page=352}}</ref> One of the other girls then told a story from her own life, which somehow related to the problem (though Rose occasionally regaled a nonsense story that had nothing to do with the situation, and Sophia told outrageous made-up stories). Some episodes featured flashbacks to previous episodes, flashbacks to events not shown in previous episodes, or to events that occurred before the series began.<ref name=\"Huryk2007\">{{cite book| last=Huryk| first=Harry| title=The Golden Girls - The Ultimate Viewing Guide| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t_jTuiubE0AC&pg=PA13| accessdate=August 8, 2013| date=July 1, 2007| publisher=Lulu.com| isbn=978-1-4116-8528-4|page=13}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} Though the writing was mostly comical, dramatic moments and sentimental endings were included in several episodes. One of the actresses on the show, Bea Arthur, actually hated cheesecake.<ref>{{cite news |title=30 Things You Never Knew About 'The Golden Girls' |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/golden-girls-turns-30-facts-series/story?id=33545250 |work=ABC News |date=September 15, 2015 |access-date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nDuring the NBC upfronts, the preview screening of the show got a standing ovation. The show promptly received a full order of 12 episodes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/03/the-golden-girls-creators-on-finding-new-fans.html |title=The Golden Girls Creators On Finding a New Generation of Fans |last=Hunt |first=Stacey Wilson |work=Vulture |access-date=March 3, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n===Ratings===\nAn instant ratings hit, ''The Golden Girls'' became an NBC staple on Saturday nights.<ref name=\"tops\">{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Tops Ratings| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1985-09-17/news/mn-20345_1_golden-girls| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=September 17, 1985| agency=Associated Press}}</ref> The show was the anchor of NBC's Saturday line-up, and almost always won its time slot, as ABC and CBS struggled to find shows to compete against it, the most notable being ABC's [[Lucille Ball]] sitcom ''[[Life With Lucy]]'' in the beginning of the 1986\u201387 season. ''The Golden Girls'' was part of a series of Brandon Tartikoff shows that put an end to NBC's ratings slump, along with ''[[The Cosby Show]]'', ''[[227 (TV series)|227]]'', ''[[Night Court]]'', ''[[Miami Vice]]'', and ''[[L.A. Law]].''\n\nThe show dealt with many controversial issues, such as [[coming out]] and [[same-sex marriage]],<ref name=\"closets\">{{cite news| title=Gays and Closets--a TV Controversy| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-04-21/entertainment/ca-650_1_golden-girls-closets-weinstein| accessdate=November 8, 2013| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=April 21, 1991}}</ref> [[elder care]] and [[homelessness]], [[HIV/AIDS]] and [[discrimination against people with HIV/AIDS]], US immigration policy, [[death]] and [[assisted suicide]].<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite news| title='The Golden Girls' And Gay Marriage: Classic Sitcom Showed Support 20 Years Before Obama| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/10/the-golden-girls-and-gay-marriage_n_1506091.html| date=May 10, 2012| work=[[The Huffington Post]]| accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWriter and producer [[Linda Bloodworth-Thomason]] created a sitcom with this kind of image as a \"four women\" show, which became ''[[Designing Women]]'' on CBS. ''Designing Women'' began competing against ''The Golden Girls'' in the same time slot, however ''The Golden Girls'' always got the higher rating, resulting in CBS pushing ''Designing Women'' to Mondays.\n\nAt the request of [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]], who was reputedly a big fan, the cast of ''The Golden Girls'' performed several skits as their characters in front of her and other members of the Royal Family at the 1988 [[Royal Variety Performance]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-cDonM4VXD8| title=Golden Girls Reunion| publisher=Lifetime Television| year=2003| access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nNBC Timeslots\n* Seasons 1-6: Saturday at 9:00 PM\n* Season 7: Saturday at 8:00 PM\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by The Golden Girls}}\n[[File:The Golden Girls Disney Legends.jpg|thumb|''The Golden Girls'' [[Disney Legends]] plaque at [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Walt Disney Studios]]]]\nDuring its original run, ''The Golden Girls'' received 68 Emmy nominations, 11 Emmy awards, four Golden Globe Awards, and two [[Viewers for Quality Television]] awards. All the lead actresses won [[Emmy Award]]s for their performances on the show. ''The Golden Girls'' is one of three live action shows, along with ''[[All in the Family]]'' and ''[[Will & Grace]]'' where all the principal actors have won at least one Emmy Award.\n\nAs a tribute to the success of ''The Golden Girls'', all four actresses were later named [[Disney Legends]].<ref name=\"disney\">{{cite web| title=Legends| url=http://disney.go.com/disneyinsider/history/legends/find-legends| website=Walt Disney Company| accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n\n===Syndication===\nBeginning July 3, 1989, NBC added daytime reruns of the show, replacing long-running ''Wheel of Fortune'' (it moved to CBS) on the NBC schedule at 11:00&nbsp;a.m.(EST). It ran for a little over a year until September 1990. At this time, syndicated reruns began airing, distributed by [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television#Buena Vista Television|Buena Vista Television]] (now [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]), the syndication arm of [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], whose [[ABC Studios#Touchstone Television|Touchstone Television]] division produced the series.\n\nIn March 1997, the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] cable network acquired the exclusive rights to repeat the episodes of ''The Golden Girls'' in the US for over a decade, until March 1, 2009. Many episodes were edited to allow more commercials and for content.\n\nBoth the [[Hallmark Channel]] and [[WE tv]] picked up the reruns in March 2009. As of February 2013, We TV's rights expired and [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] networks' [[TV Land]], home to Betty White's last series ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'', purchased them,<ref name=\"tvland\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tvland.com/shows/the-golden-girls |title=The Golden Girls |publisher=[[TV Land]] |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> as did  [[Logo TV]].<ref name=logo>{{cite web| date=March 6, 2013 |url=http://www.logotv.com/video/misc/885521/preview-the-golden-girls-arrive-on-logo-april-13th.jhtml |title=Preview 2: The Golden Girls Arrive on Logo April 13th |publisher=Logotv.com |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> In 2020, [[CMT]] purchased the rights to the series.\n\nIn Australia, the show airs daily on [[Fox Classics]]. As of 2019, every episode is available for streaming on [[Stan (company)|Stan]].\n\nIn Canada, [[Corus Entertainment|Corus Entertainment's]] digital specialty channel, [[DejaView]], aired reruns of ''The Golden Girls'' until 2017.\n\nIn Southeast Asia, [[Rewind Networks]] began airing reruns of ''The Golden Girls'' on its HD channel, [[Hits (TV channel)|HITS]], in 2013.\n\nIn New Zealand, the series was shown on [[TVNZ]] and is replayed on public holidays and it is shown on [[Jones!]].\n\nIn the UK, the series was shown on [[Channel 4]] and [[Disney Channel (UK and Ireland)|Disney Channel]].\n\nEvery episode of ''The Golden Girls'' was made available to stream on [[Hulu]] on February 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hulu.com/the-golden-girls|title=The Golden Girls|website=Hulu|access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n[[Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] has released all seven seasons of ''The Golden Girls'' on DVD in [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] and [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] with the first four being released in [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]. On November 9, 2010, the studio released a complete series box set titled ''The Golden Girls: 25th Anniversary Complete Collection''.<ref name=tvshows>{{cite press release| url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Golden-Girls-Complete-Collection/14375| title=The Golden Girls \u2013 25th Anniversary Complete Collection| publisher=Walt Disney Studios| date=September 7, 2010| accessdate=January 2, 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115072440/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Golden-Girls-Complete-Collection/14375| archivedate=November 15, 2013| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The 21-disc collection features all 180 episodes of the series as well as all special features contained on the previously released season sets; it is encased in special collectible packaging, a replica of Sophia's purse. On November 15, 2005, [[Warner Home Video]] released ''The Golden Girls: A Lifetime Intimate Portrait Series'' on DVD which contains a separate biography of Arthur, White, McClanahan and Getty, revealing each woman's background, rise to stardom and private life, which originally aired on [[Lifetime Television|Lifetime]] network between June 2000 and January 2003.<ref name=\"portrait\">{{cite AV media| url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000AYEL4M| title=''The Golden Girls'': A Lifetime Intimate Portrait Series| accessdate=June 9, 2011| publisher=Warner Home Video| date=November 15, 2005| medium=DVD}}</ref>\n\n'''Australian Region 4 DVD Releases:'''\n\n* Season 1 | 17 August 2005<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Night Season |journal=The Night Season |doi=10.5040/9780571284313.00000006 |year=2004 |isbn=978-0571284313}}</ref>\n* Season 2 | 21 September 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-2/851970/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 2 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 3 | 1 October 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sanity.com.au/products/2001693/Golden_Girls_The_-_Season_03 |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 03 |website=Sanity |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 4 | 5 December 2007<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-4/205314/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 4 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 5 | 2 April 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-5/222922/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 5 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 6 | 3 December 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-6/237247/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 6 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* Season 7 | 18 March 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-7/247317/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 7 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n* The Complete Series | 7 November 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/golden-girls-the-season-1-7/340415/ |title=Golden Girls, The - Season 1-7 |website=www.jbhifi.com.au |language=en-AU |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-offs==\nUpon the success of ''The Golden Girls'' creator Susan Harris later devised ''[[Empty Nest]]'' as a spin-off from ''The Golden Girls'' with some character crossovers. ''[[Nurses (TV series)|Nurses]]'' was later spun-off from ''Empty Nest'', and the shows occasionally had special episodes in which characters from one show made appearances in the others.<ref name=\"Dubrow\">{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Creator Adds Shows| work=Los Angeles Times| date=September 10, 1991| first=Rick| last=DuBrow| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-09-10/entertainment/ca-2286_1_golden-girls| accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===''The Golden Palace''===\n{{Main|The Golden Palace}}\nAfter the original series ended, White, McClanahan, and Getty reprised their characters in the CBS series ''The Golden Palace'', which ran from September 1992 to May 1993, and also starred [[Cheech Marin]] and [[Don Cheadle]] (Bea Arthur guest-starred in a double episode, reprising her role as Dorothy).<ref>{{cite news| title=TV Weekend; 3 of the Golden Girls in a New Home| work=The New York Times| date=September 25, 1992| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/25/news/tv-weekend-3-of-the-golden-girls-in-a-new-home.html?scp=1&sq=The%20Golden%20Palace&st=cse| accessdate=August 19, 2010 |first=John J. |last=O'Connor}}</ref> The show never approached the popularity or acclaim of the original, and ranked 57th in the annual ratings. Reportedly, a second season was approved before being canceled the day before the network announced its 1993-94 schedule.\n\nLifetime, which held the rights to ''The Golden Girls'' at the time, aired reruns of ''The Golden Palace'' in the summer of 2005, and again in December of that year. This was the first time since 1993 that ''The Golden Palace'' was seen on American television. Until April 2006, Lifetime played the series as a virtual season eight, airing the series in between the conclusion of the final season and the syndicated roll-over to season one.\n\n===''Empty Nest''===\n{{Main|Empty Nest}}\n[[File:EstelleGetty2.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Estelle Getty]] at the 41st annual [[Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 1989]]\nCapitalizing on the popularity of ''The Golden Girls'', creator Susan Harris decided to develop a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]], centering on the [[empty nest syndrome]]. The initial pilot was aired as the 1987 ''Golden Girls'' episode \"[[The Golden Girls (season 2)#Episodes|Empty Nests]]\" and starred [[Paul Dooley]] and [[Rita Moreno]] as George and Renee Corliss, a married couple living next to the ''Golden Girls'' characters, who face empty nest syndrome after their teenage daughter moves out.<ref>{{cite web| title=''The Golden Girls'' Has Been A Delight From Its Inception| work=Los Angeles Times| date=June 7, 1987| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-06-07/news/tv-777_1_los-angeles-golden-girls-etta-morris| accessdate=June 19, 2011| first=Etta| last=Morris}}</ref> When that idea was not well received, Harris retooled the series as a vehicle for [[Richard Mulligan]], and the following year ''[[Empty Nest]]'' debuted, starring Mulligan as pediatrician Harry Weston, a widower whose two adult daughters moved back home. Characters from both shows made occasional [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] guest appearances on the other show, with the four girls guesting on ''Empty Nest'' and Mulligan, [[Dinah Manoff]], [[Kristy McNichol]], [[David Leisure]], and [[Park Overall]] appearing on ''The Golden Girls'' in their ''Empty Nest'' roles.<ref>{{cite web| first=Howard| last=Rosenberg| title=''Empty Nest'' Looks Like Good Place to Nestle Down| work=Los Angeles Times| date=October 8, 1988| url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-10-08/entertainment/ca-3135_1_empty-nest| accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> After the end of ''The Golden Palace'', Getty joined the cast of ''Empty Nest'', making frequent appearances as Sophia in the show's final two seasons.\n\nMulligan and Manoff were alumni from one of Susan Harris' earlier shows, ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''.\n\n===''Nurses''===\n{{Main|Nurses (TV series)}}\n''Empty Nest'' launched its own spin-off in 1991 set in Miami in the same hospital where Dr. Weston worked. The series starred [[Stephanie Hodge]] and a set of other young female and male nurses. As one of the few times in television history where three shows from the same producer, set in the same city, aired back-to-back-to-back on the same network, the three shows occasionally took advantage of their unique circumstance to create storylines carrying through all three series, such as \"[[Hurricane Saturday]]\". Starring actress Hodge left after two seasons, [[David Rasche]] joining the cast at the start of the second season and [[Loni Anderson]] being added as the new hospital administrator in the third.\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Stage===\n''The Golden Girls: Live!'' was an [[off-Broadway]] show that opened in the summer of 2003 in New York City at Rose's Turn theater in the West Village, and ran until November of that year.<ref name=stage>{{cite web| title='Golden Girls: Live!' Sent to Shady Pines| date=December 8, 2003| last=Jacobs| first=Leonard| url=http://www.backstage.com/news/golden-girls-live-sent-to-shady-pines/| publisher=backstage.com| accessdate=January 2, 2014}}</ref> The production ended because the producers failed to secure the [[Copyright|rights]] and received a [[cease and desist]] order by the creators of the original television show. Featuring an all-male cast in [[Drag queen|drag]], ''The Golden Girls: Live!'' consisted of two back-to-back episodes of the sitcom: \"Break-In\" (season one, episode eight) and \"Isn't It Romantic?\" (season two, episode five).\n\nThe cast of The Golden Girls, Sophia, Dorothy, Blanche and Rose, have been even further immortalised in two puppet parody shows ''Thank You For Being A Friend''<ref>https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/city-east/thank-you-for-being-a-friend-brings-the-golden-girls-to-the-stage-as-puppets/news-story/715a4b5a3535352470bd7c530d07683b</ref> and ''That Golden Girls Show: A Puppet Parody'', both created by Australian screenwriter, [[Thomas Duncan-Watt]] and producer, [[Jonathan Rockefeller]]<ref>http://www.theaterjones.com/ntx/reviews/20191117091441/2019-11-17/Eisemann-Center-for-the-Performing-Arts/The-Golden-Girls-Show-A-Puppet-Parody</ref>.\n\n===International versions===\n* Chile: ''{{interlanguage link|Los a\u00f1os dorados|es|Los a\u00f1os dorados (Chile)|vertical-align=sup}}'': In 2015 a Chilean remake called ''Los A\u00f1os Dorados'' (''The Golden Years'') was produced by UCVTV in agreement with Disney, starring famous Chilean actresses Gloria M\u00fcnchmeyer, Carmen Barros, Ana Reeves, and Consuelo Holzapfel, who live their retirement in the city of [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar]]. It was a success for the channel, so there are plans to do the second season in 2016. \n*Israel:  ''[[Bnot HaZahav]]'', which ran from 2011 to 2016.\n* Greece: ''Chrysa Koritsia'': In 2008, Greek broadcaster [[ET1 (Greece)|ET1]] premiered a Greek remake entitled ''Chrysa Koritsia'' ({{Lang-el|X\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ac \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03c4\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1}}, ''Gold[en] Girls''), which features the four women in Greece.<ref name=\"Advocate\">{{cite news| title=Golden Girls Hits Spain| author=Jeffrey Gerson| work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]| publisher=Advocate.com| date=July 29, 2010| url=http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2010/07/29/Gracias_Por_Ser_Una_Amiga_Golden_Girls_Hits_Spain/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801033740/http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2010/07/29/Gracias_Por_Ser_Una_Amiga_Golden_Girls_Hits_Spain/| archivedate=August 1, 2010| accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref> Each of the characters has been hellenized to suit the culture and modern setting. Names were only slightly changed, but more for cultural reasons, as Sophia (whose first name was unchanged, as it is Greek), Bela (Blanche), Dora (Dorothy), Fifi (Rose), and Panos (Stan). The series began airing in mid-January, and features many similar plots to the original. ET1 aired a rerun of the show in the summer of 2008 and managed to take a place in the top-10 ratings chart, presented by AGB Nielsen Media Research. The Greek edition features Mirka Papakonstantinou as Dora, Dina Konsta as Sofia, Eleni Gerasimidou as Fifi, and Ivonni Maltezou as Bela.\n* Netherlands: ''{{interlanguage link|Golden Girls|nl|Golden Girls (Nederland)|vertical-align=sup}}:'' A Dutch remake for the [[RTL 4]] network stars [[Loes Luca]] as Barbara (Blanche), [[Beppie Melissen]] as Els (Dorothy), [[Cecile Heuer]] as Milly (Rose), and [[Pleuni Touw]] as Toos (Sophia). The show premiered in fall 2012, using essentially the same plots as the U.S. version, along with a Dutch-language version of the original theme song, \"[[Thank You for Being a Friend]]\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Golden Girls Intro (Dutch)| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OPYq7bmpldw| publisher=YouTube| date=October 11, 2012| accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref>\n* Philippines: ''50 Carats, O Di Ba?'' A Philippine version of ''The Golden Girls'' (spin-off) aired during the early 1990s by [[IBC 13]] starred [[Nida Blanca]], [[Charito Solis]], and [[Gloria Romero (actress)|Gloria Romero]].<ref name=\"francisco\">{{cite news| title=A rivalry that never was| url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/140171/rivalry-never-was| date=November 15, 2001| last=Francisco| first=Butch| newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]| accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>\n* Russia: ''Bolshie Devochki'': A Russian remake was broadcast in 2006, entitled ''Bolshie Devochki'' ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0438}}), which in English can literally be translated to: ''Big Girls''. The series featured renowned Russian actresses Galina Petrova as Irina (Dorothy), Olga Ostroumova as Nadejda (Blanche), Valentina Telechkina as Margarita (Rose), and Elena Millioti as Sofya (Sophia). However, the concept never caught on with the Russian viewers and the show was canceled after only 32 episodes.<ref name=\"Bolshie\">{{cite web |title=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0438 |url=http://www.amedia.ru/girls/ |publisher=amedia.ru |date= |accessdate=June 24, 2011 |language=Russian |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511142327/http://www.amedia.ru/girls/ |archivedate=May 11, 2011 |trans-title=Big Girls}}</ref>\n* Spain: ''{{interlanguage link|Juntas, pero no revueltas|es|Juntas, pero no revueltas|vertical-align=sup}}''/''{{interlanguage link|Las chicas de oro|es|Las chicas de oro (Espa\u00f1a)|vertical-align=sup}}'': In 1996, [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]] launched a Spanish remake entitled ''Juntas pero no revueltas'' (''Together, but not mixed'') with [[Mercedes Sampietro]] as Julia (Dorothy), [[M\u00f3nica Randall]] as Nuri (Blanche), [[Kiti Manver]] as Rosa (Rose), and [[Amparo Bar\u00f3]] as Benigna (Sophia). Low ratings made it disappear after one season.<ref name=\"TVE\">{{cite web| title=TVE comienza a rodar 'Juntas, pero no revueltas', su versi\u00f3n de 'Las chicas de oro'| url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/Pantallas/MANVER/_KITI_/ACTRIZ/ESPANA/TELEVISION_ESPANOLA_/RTVE/TVE/comienza/rodar/Juntas/revueltas/version/chicas/oro/elpepirtv/19950609elpepirtv_3/Tes| date=June 9, 1995| work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]| publisher=elpais.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011|language=es}}</ref> In 2010, another remake with the title ''Las chicas de oro'' (''The Golden Girls'') was announced, again on [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]], this time produced by Jos\u00e9 Luis Moreno and with [[Concha Velasco]] as Doroti (Dorothy), [[Carmen Maura]] as Rosa (Rose), [[Lola Herrera]] as Blanca (Blanche), and Alicia Hermida as Sof\u00eda (Sophia).<ref name=\"vertele\">{{cite web| title=TVE presenta el remake: 'Volvemos a la sitcom pero con valor seguro'| date=July 27, 2010| publisher=vertele.com| url=http://www.vertele.com/noticias/27930/lograr-reparto-asi-historico| accessdate=June 24, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129083629/http://www.vertele.com/noticias/27930/lograr-reparto-asi-historico| archivedate=November 29, 2010| language=es}}</ref> The series premiered on September 13, 2010 with success.<ref name=\"de oro\">{{cite web| title=\"Las Chicas de Oro\" relucen en su estreno con 4 millones| date=September 14, 2010| url=http://www.vertele.com/noticias/28445/chicas-oro-relucen-estreno-millones| publisher=vertele.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118103844/http://www.vertele.com/noticias/28445/chicas-oro-relucen-estreno-millones| archivedate=November 18, 2010| language=es}}</ref> However, after only 26 episodes, the series was eventually discontinued after the end of the first season after receiving generally bad reviews and following dropping ratings.<ref name=\"de oro2\">{{cite web| title='Las Chicas de Oro' espa\u00f1olas ni son renovadas ni lo merec\u00edan| date=December 14, 2010| url=http://www.vayatele.com/tve-1/las-chicas-de-oro-espanolas-ni-son-renovadas-ni-lo-merecian| publisher=vertele.com| accessdate=June 24, 2011|language=es}}</ref>\n* Portugal: ''Queridas e Maduras'': In July 1995, [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]] premiered ''Queridas e Maduras'' (in English, ''Dear Mature Girls'') a Portuguese version of the American sitcom. The show featured renowned Portuguese actresses [[Catarina Avelar]] as ''Edite'' (Dorothy), [[Am\u00e9lia Videira]] as ''In\u00eas'' (Rose), [[Lia Gama]] as ''Salom\u00e9'' (Blanche) and the veteran actress [[Lu\u00edsa Barbosa]] as ''Aparecida'' (Sophia). The Portuguese version got two seasons, the first in 1995 and the second in 1996, adapting episode plots from the first two seasons of the original series.\n* Turkey: ''{{interlanguage link|Altin Kizlar|tr|Altin Kizlar|vertical-align=sup}}''. In 2009, broadcaster [[ATV (Turkey)|ATV]] ''{{interlanguage link|Actual Television|tr|Akt\u00fcel Televizyon|vertical-align=sup}}'' premiered ''Altin Kizlar'' (literally translated to English as \"Girls of Gold\"). It was produced by Play Prod\u00fcksiyon. Rather than residing in Miami, the women shared a condo in residential part of [[Beyo\u011flu]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bal\u0131ksirt\u0131 |first1=\u015eeng\u00fcl |url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/yazarlar/gunaydin/baliksirti/2009/05/08/altin_kizlarin_setine_gizli_kamera_koymak_gerek |accessdate=16 September 2018 |ref=altinkizlar-sabah |location=Istanbul, Turkey |language=tr|title=Altin Kizlar'in Setine Gizli Kamera Koymak Gerek}}</ref> As in other foreign adaptations, it featured well-known local actresses. The key roles were filled by [[Fatma Girik]] as ''Saf\u0131ye'' (the 'Sophia' character), [[H\u00fclya Ko\u00e7yi\u011fit]] as ''\u0130smet'' ('Dorothy'), [[Nevra Serezli]] as ''G\u00f6n\u00fcl'' ('Blanche') and [[T\u00fcrkan \u015eoray]] as ''Inci'' ('Rose').<ref>{{Citation|title=Altin kizlar|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5986310/|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> The show lasted only one episode, consisting of story lines from two of the original American series: \"[https://www.thetvdb.com/series/the-golden-girls/episodes/41323 The Engagement]\" (Season 1, Episode 1) and \"[https://www.thetvdb.com/series/the-golden-girls/episodes/41327 The Triangle]\" (Season 1, Episode 5). \n* United Kingdom: ''[[The Brighton Belles|Brighton Belles]]'': In 1993, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] premiered ''Brighton Belles'', a British version of the American sitcom.<ref>{{cite news| title= Heard the one about the US sense of humour?| publisher=Independent.co.uk| work=The Independent| date=August 30, 2000| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/heard-the-one-about-the-us-sense-of-humour-696765.html| accessdate=September 9, 2010| location=London| first=Brian| last=Viner}}</ref> The show, starring [[Sheila Hancock]], [[Wendy Craig]], [[Sheila Gish]], and [[Jean Boht]] was nearly identical to ''Girls'' except for character name changes and actor portrayals. The 10-episode series was canceled after six weeks due to low ratings, with the final four episodes airing more than a year later.\n\n==Restaurant==\nIn 2017 a ''Golden Girls''-themed eatery Rue La Rue Cafe owned by Rue McLanahan's close friend Michael La Rue, who inherited many of the star's personal belongings and in turn decorated the restaurant with them, opened in the [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] section of the [[New York City]] borough of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=AM>{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' cafe Rue La Rue has soft opening in Washington Heights| first=Jillian| last=Jorgensen| url=http://www.amny.com/eat-and-drink/golden-girls-cafe-rue-la-rue-has-soft-opening-in-washington-heights-1.13075453| date=February 8, 2017| newspaper=[[AM New York]]| accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref> The eatery closed in November 2017 after less than a year of operation.<ref name=WNBC>{{cite news| title='Golden Girls' Cafe in Manhattan Closes After Less Than a Year| url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Golden-Girls-Cafe-in-Manhattan-Closes-After-Less-Than-a-Year-458880873.html| date=November 20, 2017| work=[[WNBC]] News| accessdate=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{cite book |title = Golden Girls Forever: An Unauthorized Look Behind the Lanai |last = Colucci|first = Jim |year = 2016 |publisher = Harper Collins |location = New York |isbn = 978-0-06-242290-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=The Golden Girls|id=0088526}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-golden-girls|The Golden Girls}}\n* {{epguides|id=GoldenGirls}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070701180551/http://thegoldengirls.wetpaint.com/ @ccess ''The Golden Girls'' Wiki]\n* [http://www.museum.tv/eotv/goldengirls.htm Encyclopedia of Television]\n* {{EmmyTVLegends title|golden-girls-the|The Golden Girls}}\n   \n{{Golden Girls}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by The Golden Girls|Awards for ''The Golden Girls'']]\n|list =\n{{EmmyAward ComedySeries 1976-2000}}\n{{GoldenGlobeTVComedy}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite New TV Comedy}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden Girls, The}}\n[[Category:The Golden Girls| ]]\n[[Category:1985 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1992 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:1990s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Series Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by ABC Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Miami]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series winners]]\n[[Category:Television series about suburbia]]\n[[Category:Television series about old age]]\n[[Category:Works about old age]]\n[[Category:American television shows]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCMT(link changed toCMT (American TV channel)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Golden_Girls"}
{"title_page": "Leader of the Labour Party (UK)", "text_new": "{{short description|Elected Head of the Labour Party in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Leader of the Labour Party\n|body            = \n|member_of       = [[National Executive Committee]]\n| image               = Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg\n|incumbent      = Sir [[Keir Starmer]]\n|incumbentsince  = 4 April 2020\n|status          = \n|residence       = \n|appointer       = \n|termlength      = \n|formation       = 17 January 1906\n|inaugural       = [[Keir Hardie]]\n|precursor       = Chair of the [[Parliamentary Labour Party|PLP]]\n|website         = \n}}\nThe '''Leader of the Labour Party''' is the head of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] of the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==History==\nThe post of Leader of the Labour Party was officially created in 1922. Before this, between when Labour MPs were first elected in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] and the general election in [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]], when substantial gains were made, the post was known as [[Parliamentary Labour Party|Chairman of the Parliamentary Labour Party]].<ref name=\"A History Of The British Labour Party\">Thorpe, Andrew. (2001) ''A History Of The British Labour Party'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|0-333-92908-X}}</ref> In 1970, the positions of leader of the Labour Party and Chairman of the Parliamentary Labour Party were separated.\n\nIn 1921, [[John Robert Clynes|J. R. Clynes]] became the first leader of the Labour Party to have been born in [[England]]; prior to this, all party leaders had been born in [[Scotland]]. In [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]], [[Ramsay MacDonald]] became the first ever [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]], leading a minority administration which lasted nine months. [[Clement Attlee]] would become the first Labour leader to lead a majority government in [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]. The first to be born in [[Wales]] was [[Neil Kinnock]], who was elected in [[1983 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|1983]]. The most electorally successful leaders of the Labour Party to date are: [[Tony Blair]], who won three consecutive electoral victories in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] (both landslide victories), and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]], and [[Harold Wilson]], who won three general elections out of five contested, in [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964]], [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966]] and [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974]].\n\n==Selection==\nUnlike other British political party leaders, the Labour leader does not have the power to dismiss or appoint their deputy. Both the leader and deputy leader are elected by an [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] system. From 1980 to 2014 an electoral college was used, with a third of the votes allocated to the Party's [[List of Labour Party (UK) MPs|MPs]] and [[List of members of the European Parliament 2009\u20132014|MEPs]], a third to individual members of the Labour Party, and a third to individual members of all affiliated organisations, including [[Socialist society (Labour Party)|socialist societies]] and [[Affiliated trade union|trade unions]]. The [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2015 leadership election]] used a \"one member, one vote\" system, in which the votes of party members and members of affiliated organisations are counted equally. MPs and MEPs votes are not counted separately, although a candidate needs to receive the support of 10% of Labour MPs in order to appear on the ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/labour-proposals-all-but-guarantee-leftwing-corbyn-successor/ar-AAzdqmI|title=Labour proposals 'all-but guarantee leftwing Corbyn successor'|website=www.msn.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref>\n\n==Role==\nWhen the Labour Party is in [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]], as it currently is, the leader of the Labour Party usually acts as the [[Leader of Her Majesty's Loyal Opposition|Leader of the Opposition]], and chairs the [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|shadow cabinet]]. Concordantly, when the Party is in [[Her Majesty's Government|government]], the leader would usually become the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister of the United Kingdom]], [[First Lord of the Treasury]] and [[Minister for the Civil Service]], as well as appointing the [[Cabinet (UK)|cabinet]].\n\n==Leaders of the Labour Party (1906\u2013present)==\n{{qnote|the right-hand column does not allocate height proportional to time in office.}}\nA list of leaders (including acting leaders) since 1906.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leaders of the Labour Party|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/lableader.html|website=election.demon.co.uk|publisher=United Kingdom Election Results|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Leader<br /><small>(birth\u2013death)</small>\n! Portrait\n! Constituency\n! Took office\n! |Left office\n! colspan=\"2\"|Prime Minister {{small|(term)}}\n|-\n| [[Keir Hardie]]<br /><small>(1856\u20131915)</small>\n| [[File:Jameskeirhardie.jpg|60px]]\n| [[Merthyr Tydfil (UK Parliament constituency)|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| 17 February 1906\n| 22 January 1908\n| style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}; border-top:solid 0 gray; border-bottom:solid 0 gray\" |\n! rowspan=2 style=\"font-weight:normal\"|[[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Campbell-Bannerman]] <small>{{nowrap|1905\u20131908}}</small>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Arthur Henderson]]<br /><small>(1863\u20131935)</small><br />(1st time)\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[File:arthurhenderson.jpg|60px]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Barnard Castle (UK Parliament constituency)|Barnard Castle]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|22 January 1908\n| rowspan=\"2\"|14 Febr