{"title_page": "Lombrette River", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Lombrette (disambiguation){{!}}Lombrette}}\n{{short description|River in Charlevoix and La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality, Quebec, Canada}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Lombrette River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = \n| image_caption      = \n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = [[Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name4  = [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = [[Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] and [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|26,2|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Unidentified lake\n| source1_location   = [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.00564|-70.65484|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = 677 m\n| mouth              = [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.18471|-70.73960|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = 37 m\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   =(Upward from the mouth) Five unidentified streams, unidentified stream (via a lake), two unidentified streams, discharge from three lakes, discharge from a small lake.\n| tributaries_right  =(Upward from the mouth) Six unidentified streams, [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]], three unidentified streams, McLean Creek.\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\nThe '''Lombrette river''' is a tributary of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]] flowing on the north bank of the [[Saint Lawrence River]], in the administrative region of the [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in [[Canada]]. This river flows consecutively through the regional county municipalities (MRC) of:\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]: in the municipality of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]];\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]: in the municipality of [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]].\n\nThis small valley is mainly served by the [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]] which normally runs along the north shore of the St. Lawrence River; however, it distances itself from the river in this area of Charlevoix. Forestry is the main economic activity in this valley; second-hand tourist activities.\n\nThe surface of the Lombrette River is generally frozen from the beginning of December until the end of March; however, safe traffic on the ice is generally from mid-December to mid-March. The water level of the river varies with the seasons and the precipitation; the spring flood occurs in March or April.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Lombrette river has its source in [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] at the mouth of an unidentified lake (altitude of {{convert|677|m}}) which is located between [[mountain at Liguori]] (summit located at {{convert|3.8|km}} to the north), Salvation Mountain (summit located at {{convert|3.3|km}} to the southeast) and [[McLean Mountain]] (summit located at {{convert|4.4|km}} in the South). This small lake is located at:\n* {{convert|5.3|km}} east of the west bank of the [[St. Lawrence River]];\n* {{convert|7.5|km}} south-west of the village center of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]];\n* {{convert|6.7|km}} east of a curve of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]].\n\nFrom this source, the course of the Lombrette river descends with a drop of {{convert|640|m}} over {{convert|26.2|km}} parallel to the edge of the Laurentian plateau away from 4 to 5&nbsp;km, depending on the following segments:\n\n'''Upper course of the Lombrette river''' (segment of {{convert|16.8|km}})\n\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} to the south, by forming a hook towards the east and down the mountain, to the outlet (coming from the northeast) of a stream;\n* {{convert|2,3|km}} south down the mountain and passing on the west side of Salvation Mountain, to McLean stream (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|1.3|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, until the mouth of a small lake which receives a stream (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|6.8|km}} to the south in a valley between the McLeau Mountain (west side) and another mountain (East side), collecting a stream (coming from the west) and forming many small snakes in places, up to a stream (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|3.0|km}} to the southwest by forming two S passing from the south side of a small hamlet, to [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]];\n* {{convert|1,6|km}} to the south, forming numerous small streamers, until the confluence of the [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]] (coming from the north);\n\n'''Lower course of the Lombrette river''' (segment of {{convert|9.4|km}})\n\n* {{convert|7.0|km}} southwards passing west of the hamlet Domaine-Armand-Cr\u00e9peault west of the village of Saint-Tite-des-Caps, while winding in places, until the outlet of the black stream (coming from the northeast);\n* {{convert|2.4|km}} south-west in agricultural area, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/en/index.html Atlas of Canada - Department of Natural Resources Canada - Lombrette River - Distance and altitude measurements based on the application of site measurements.]</ref>\n\nThe Lombrette river flows on the east bank of the Sainte-Anne river, in [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]. This confluence is located {{convert|6.7|km}} west of the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]] and {{convert|2.6|km}} southwest of the center of the village of Saint-Tite-des-Caps.\n\nFrom the confluence of the Lombrette river, the current flows over {{convert|14,0|km}} generally south along the course of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], to the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence river]].<ref name=Atlas/>\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe map of the province of Quebec drawn up in 1870 by Eug\u00e8ne Tach\u00e9 indicates this watercourse in the form \"R. The Ombrette\u201d. This toponym would evoke the nickname of Pierre Simard, dit Lombrette, master mason who arrived in New France in 1654 and died between 1681 and 1686, and especially of his son, No\u00ebl Simard, dit Lombrette (1637-1715) laborer. The latter obtained, in particular a concession at Cape Maillard in the vicinity of the Lombrette River. The nickname Lombrette, joined to the name of Pierre Simard or Cimar in the census of 1666\u20131667, still remains enigmatic. If it is not the name of a farm or a place known as the country of origin of Pierre Simard in the surroundings of Angoul\u00eame, if need be, the ombrette can be the diminutive of shade, a bony fish that is distinguished from salmon, trout and char by its small mouth. The graphic form L'Ombrette, adopted in 1949, was modified for that of Lombrette in 1974, by the Geographic Commission. The name \"Rivi\u00e8re McLean\" was also used in memory of John McLean, landowner at Saint-Tite-des-Caps.<ref>Source: Names and places of Quebec, work of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec, published in 1994 and 1996 in the form of a printed illustrated dictionary, and in that of a CD-ROM produced by the company Micro-Intel, in 1997, from this dictionary.</ref>\n\nThe toponym \"rivi\u00e8re Lombrette\" was formalized on August 29, 1972 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=36411 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: Rivi\u00e8re Lombrette]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[Capitale-Nationale]], an administrative region\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]], a municipality\n* [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]], a municipality\n* [[Rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]]\n* [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lombrette, river}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n[[Category:La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|River in Charlevoix and La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality, Quebec, Canada}}\n{{Other uses|Lombrette (disambiguation){{!}}Lombrette}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Lombrette River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = \n| image_caption      = \n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = [[Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name4  = [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = [[Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] and [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|26,2|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Unidentified lake\n| source1_location   = [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.00564|-70.65484|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = 677 m\n| mouth              = [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.18471|-70.73960|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = 37 m\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   =(Upward from the mouth) Five unidentified streams, unidentified stream (via a lake), two unidentified streams, discharge from three lakes, discharge from a small lake.\n| tributaries_right  =(Upward from the mouth) Six unidentified streams, [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]], three unidentified streams, McLean Creek.\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\nThe '''Lombrette river''' is a tributary of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]] flowing on the north bank of the [[Saint Lawrence River]], in the administrative region of the [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in [[Canada]]. This river flows consecutively through the regional county municipalities (MRC) of:\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]: in the municipality of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]];\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]: in the municipality of [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]].\n\nThis small valley is mainly served by the [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]] which normally runs along the north shore of the St. Lawrence River; however, it distances itself from the river in this area of Charlevoix. Forestry is the main economic activity in this valley; second-hand tourist activities.\n\nThe surface of the Lombrette River is generally frozen from the beginning of December until the end of March; however, safe traffic on the ice is generally from mid-December to mid-March. The water level of the river varies with the seasons and the precipitation; the spring flood occurs in March or April.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Lombrette river has its source in [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] at the mouth of an unidentified lake (altitude of {{convert|677|m}}) which is located between [[mountain at Liguori]] (summit located at {{convert|3.8|km}} to the north), Salvation Mountain (summit located at {{convert|3.3|km}} to the southeast) and [[McLean Mountain]] (summit located at {{convert|4.4|km}} in the South). This small lake is located at:\n* {{convert|5.3|km}} east of the west bank of the [[St. Lawrence River]];\n* {{convert|7.5|km}} south-west of the village center of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]];\n* {{convert|6.7|km}} east of a curve of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]].\n\nFrom this source, the course of the Lombrette river descends with a drop of {{convert|640|m}} over {{convert|26.2|km}} parallel to the edge of the Laurentian plateau away from 4 to 5 km, depending on the following segments:\n\n'''Upper course of the Lombrette river''' (segment of {{convert|16.8|km}})\n\n* {{convert|1.8|km}} to the south, by forming a hook towards the east and down the mountain, to the outlet (coming from the northeast) of a stream;\n* {{convert|2,3|km}} south down the mountain and passing on the west side of Salvation Mountain, to McLean stream (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|1.3|km}} towards the south-east in a deep valley, until the mouth of a small lake which receives a stream (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|6.8|km}} to the south in a valley between the McLeau Mountain (west side) and another mountain (East side), collecting a stream (coming from the west) and forming many small snakes in places, up to a stream (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|3.0|km}} to the southwest by forming two S passing from the south side of a small hamlet, to [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]];\n* {{convert|1,6|km}} to the south, forming numerous small streamers, until the confluence of the [[rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]] (coming from the north);\n\n'''Lower course of the Lombrette river''' (segment of {{convert|9.4|km}})\n\n* {{convert|7.0|km}} southwards passing west of the hamlet Domaine-Armand-Cr\u00e9peault west of the village of Saint-Tite-des-Caps, while winding in places, until the outlet of the black stream (coming from the northeast);\n* {{convert|2.4|km}} south-west in agricultural area, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/en/index.html Atlas of Canada - Department of Natural Resources Canada - Lombrette River - Distance and altitude measurements based on the application of site measurements.]</ref>\n\nThe Lombrette river flows on the east bank of the Sainte-Anne river, in [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]. This confluence is located {{convert|6.7|km}} west of the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]] and {{convert|2.6|km}} southwest of the center of the village of Saint-Tite-des-Caps.\n\nFrom the confluence of the Lombrette river, the current flows over {{convert|14,0|km}} generally south along the course of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], to the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence river]].<ref name=Atlas/>\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe map of the province of Quebec drawn up in 1870 by Eug\u00e8ne Tach\u00e9 indicates this watercourse in the form \"R. The Ombrette\u201d. This toponym would evoke the nickname of Pierre Simard, dit Lombrette, master mason who arrived in New France in 1654 and died between 1681 and 1686, and especially of his son, No\u00ebl Simard, dit Lombrette (1637-1715) laborer. The latter obtained, in particular a concession at Cape Maillard in the vicinity of the Lombrette River. The nickname Lombrette, joined to the name of Pierre Simard or Cimar in the census of 1666-1667, still remains enigmatic. If it is not the name of a farm or a place known as the country of origin of Pierre Simard in the surroundings of Angoul\u00eame, if need be, the ombrette can be the diminutive of shade, a bony fish that is distinguished from salmon, trout and char by its small mouth. The graphic form L'Ombrette, adopted in 1949, was modified for that of Lombrette in 1974, by the Geographic Commission. The name \"Rivi\u00e8re McLean\" was also used in memory of John McLean, landowner at Saint-Tite-des-Caps.<ref>Source: Names and places of Quebec, work of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec, published in 1994 and 1996 in the form of a printed illustrated dictionary, and in that of a CD-ROM produced by the company Micro-Intel, in 1997, from this dictionary.</ref>\n\nThe toponym \"rivi\u00e8re Lombrette\" was formalized on August 29, 1972 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=36411 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: Rivi\u00e8re Lombrette]</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[Capitale-Nationale]], an administrative region\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]], a municipality\n* [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]], a municipality\n* [[Rivi\u00e8re des Chenaux]]\n* [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lombrette, river}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n[[Category:La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1666-1667 \u2192 1666\u20131667", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lombrette_River"}
{"title_page": "Angela Rayner", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Angela Rayner\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image               = Official portrait of Angela Rayner MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Rayner in 2019\n| office              = [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader              = [[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start          = 4 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]] <br> [[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1         = 1 July 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Pat Glass]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Shadow Minister for Women and Equalities]]\n| leader2             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2         = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2           = 6 October 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Kate Green]]\n| successor2          = [[Sarah Champion]]\n| office3             = [[Official Opposition frontbench#Social services|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n| leader3             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3         = 11 January 2016\n| term_end3           = 1 July 2016\n| predecessor3        = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n| successor3          = [[Alex Cunningham]]\n| office4             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n| term_start4         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4           = \n| predecessor4        = [[David Heyes]]\n| successor4          = \n| majority4           = 4,263 (11.1%)\n| birth_name          = Angela Bowen\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|3|28}}\n| birth_place         = [[Stockport]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Mark Rayner|2010}}\n| children            = 3\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Angela Rayner''' (''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Bowen'''; born 28 March 1980) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]<nowiki/> since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]<ref name=\"2015 result\">{{cite news |title=Ashton-under-Lyne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511133428/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |archivedate=11 May 2015  }}</ref> and [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] since 2020.\n\nShe has served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] since 2016. As Shadow Education Secretary, Rayner has proposed the creation of a [[National Education Service]] (NES), modelled on the [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|title=Labour to outline plans for National Education Service and 'cradle to grave' learning|date=26 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205404/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nRayner left secondary school aged 16 whilst pregnant and without any qualifications. She later trained as a [[care worker]], eventually becoming a [[union representative|trade union representative]] within [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]], during which time she joined the Labour Party. Shortly after her election to the [[House of Commons]] in 2015, she was described in the media as being part of the Labour Party's [[soft left]]. \n\nIn January 2016, Corbyn appointed Rayner as a [[Shadow Cabinet|Junior Shadow Minister]] for Pensions, and later for Women and Equalities, in June. She has since been considered by some as a possible future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Leader]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |title=Labour's Angela Rayner: 'I'm proper working-class and Jeremy Kyle' |last=Moss |first=Stephen |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728232408/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |archivedate=28 July 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|title=The irresistible rise of Angela Rayner|website=www.newstatesman.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926230219/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|title=Corbyn says 2 Labour MPs tipped to replace him could 'absolutely' be leaders|first=Todd|last=Fitzgerald|date=10 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151705/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> However, Rayner opted to not run for the Labour leadership in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], choosing to support her flat-mate [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and instead successfully [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|stand for Deputy Leader]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner was born on 28 March 1980 in [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\">'RAYNER, Angela', ''[[Who's Who 2017]]'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016; online edn., November 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U283864 accessed 5 Oct 2017]</ref> She attended [[Stockport Academy|Avondale School]] in Stockport, leaving the school aged 16 after becoming pregnant, and did not obtain any qualifications.<ref name=\"oldham\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |title=Not bad for a ginger kid! |publisher=[[Oldham Chronicle]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819045552/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |archivedate=19 August 2016  }}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ Teen mum turned Labour MP: Why Angela Rayner should have the Tories running scared] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930081709/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ |date=30 September 2016 }}, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 29 September 2016</ref> She later studied part-time at [[Stockport College]], learning [[British Sign Language]], and qualifying as a [[Social care|social care worker]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\" />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter leaving college, Rayner worked for [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]] as a care worker for a number of years. During this time, she was also elected as a trade union representative for [[UNISON|Unison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |title=Joining a trade union |publisher=[[GOV.UK]] |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917171227/https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref> She was later elected as [[convenor]] of [[UNISON|Unison]] [[North West England|North West]], becoming the union's most senior official in the region.<ref name=\"schoolsweek\" /><ref name=\"Fitzgerald\">{{cite news|last=Fitzgearld|first=Todd|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|title=Commons vow by new Ashton MP Angela Rayner who was told she'd amount to nothing|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=13 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181523/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' featured a lengthy profile of Rayner in 2012, as part of an article on a trade union officer's working life.<ref>{{cite news|title=A working life: the Union Official|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216161110/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Angela Rayner, 2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|Rayner speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\nIn 2014, Rayner was selected to become Labour's candidate for the seat of [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], after the retirement of [[David Heyes]]. She won the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], increasing both the Labour majority and its share of the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Labour candidate: We need real people with life experience to bring common sense to Parliament|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=8 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915003947/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> She delivered her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 3 June 2015. In the 2017 general election held on Thursday 8 June 2017, Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat, increasing both the Labour majority and vote share. Rayner held her Ashton-under-Lyne seat a third time after winning the constituency in the general election held on Thursday 12 December 2019.\n\nRayner nominated [[Andy Burnham]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]], but the following year became one of just 18 MPs to back the incumbent [[Jeremy Corbyn]] against challenger [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 leadership election]].<ref name=\"KeepCorbyn\">{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|title=Corbyn addresses crowd of up to 10,000 on eve of confidence vote|publisher=[[LabourList]]|last=Pine|first=Sarah|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701080636/http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2016, after a series of resignations from the [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|Shadow Cabinet]], Corbyn appointed Rayner to the position of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]].<ref name=\"schoolsweek\">{{cite web |url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |title=Exclusive: Angela Rayner becomes third shadow education secretary in a week |publisher=Schools Week |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090147/http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]] Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat being returned as Member of Parliament for the third time in 5 years. She was elected as deputy leader on 4 April 2020, replacing [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]].\n\n==Political views==\nIn a 2017 interview discussing her political beliefs, Rayner highlighted her [[pragmatism]], described herself as being part of the \"[[soft left]]\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"auto\"/> As shadow education secretary, Rayner has championed the policy of a \u2019National Education Service\u2019, which would be modelled along similar lines to the UK [[National Health Service]], as well as promoting an increase in funding to early years education. She has previously written that decreasing teachers' salaries would lead to shortages in those joining the profession.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 England's schools face 'severe' teacher shortage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 |date=30 August 2018 }} ''[[BBC News]]''. 20 August 2018''</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, she married Mark Rayner, a Unison official.<ref name=\"WW 2017\" /> She has three sons: Ryan, who was born when she was aged 16; Jimmy; and Charlie.<ref name=\"oldham\" /> Charlie was born prematurely at 23 weeks and Rayner says that the care he received demonstrated the importance of the NHS to her.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unions blast Education Secretary over controversial reforms|url=http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|publisher=Equal Times|date=30 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065658/http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Rayner lives in her constituency of [[Ashton-under-Lyne]] with her family. She became a grandmother in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|title=Grangela: Labour's Angela Rayner is grandmother at 37|date=22 November 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|archivedate=22 November 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Evan Davis]] of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] in 2018, Rayner said that her mother had been unable to read or write; a repeat of part of a tribute she made to her mother in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |title=Labour MP Angela Rayner's tribute to her 'inspirational' mother |work=inews.co.uk |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925025945/https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Rayner revealed that she had fitted [[panic button]]s at her home after rape and death threats were sent to her a few weeks earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Angela Rayner has panic buttons fitted after online threats |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |accessdate=4 March 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304212645/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |archive-date=4 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, she confirmed she had been suffering symptoms of [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] and was self-isolating following medical advice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/|title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating|work=ITV News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.angelarayner.com/}}\n*[https://twitter.com/AngelaRayner?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Twitter]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=angela-rayner/4356 |publicwhip=Angela_Rayner |theywork=angela_rayner}}\n* [http://unisonactive.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/proud-loud-and-unison-angie-rayners.html ''UNISON blog'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Heyes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pat Glass]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Angela}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Stockport]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Women trade unionists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Angela Rayner\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image               = Official portrait of Angela Rayner MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Rayner in 2019\n| office              = [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader              = [[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start          = 4 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]] <br> [[Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1         = 1 July 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Pat Glass]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Shadow Minister for Women and Equalities]]\n| leader2             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2         = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2           = 6 October 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Kate Green]]\n| successor2          = [[Sarah Champion]]\n| office3             = [[Official Opposition frontbench#Social services|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n| leader3             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3         = 11 January 2016\n| term_end3           = 1 July 2016\n| predecessor3        = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n| successor3          = [[Alex Cunningham]]\n| office4             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n| term_start4         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4           = \n| predecessor4        = [[David Heyes]]\n| successor4          = \n| majority4           = 4,263 (11.1%)\n| birth_name          = Angela Bowen\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|3|28}}\n| birth_place         = [[Stockport]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Mark Rayner|2010}}\n| children            = 3\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Angela Rayner''' (''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Bowen'''; born 28 March 1980) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]<nowiki/> since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]<ref name=\"2015 result\">{{cite news |title=Ashton-under-Lyne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511133428/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |archivedate=11 May 2015  }}</ref> and [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] since 2020.\n\nShe has served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] since 2016. As Shadow Education Secretary, Rayner has proposed the creation of a [[National Education Service]] (NES), modelled on the [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|title=Labour to outline plans for National Education Service and 'cradle to grave' learning|date=26 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205404/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nRayner left secondary school aged 16 whilst pregnant and without any qualifications. She later trained as a [[care worker]], eventually becoming a [[union representative|trade union representative]] within [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]], during which time she joined the Labour Party. Shortly after her election to the [[House of Commons]] in 2015, she was described in the media as being part of the Labour Party's [[soft left]]. \n\nIn January 2016, Corbyn appointed Rayner as a [[Shadow Cabinet|Junior Shadow Minister]] for Pensions, and later for Women and Equalities, in June. She has since been considered by some as a possible future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Leader]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |title=Labour's Angela Rayner: 'I'm proper working-class and Jeremy Kyle' |last=Moss |first=Stephen |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728232408/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |archivedate=28 July 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|title=The irresistible rise of Angela Rayner|website=www.newstatesman.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926230219/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|title=Corbyn says 2 Labour MPs tipped to replace him could 'absolutely' be leaders|first=Todd|last=Fitzgerald|date=10 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151705/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> However, Rayner opted to not run for the Labour leadership in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], choosing to support her flat-mate [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and instead successfully [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|stand for Deputy Leader]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner was born on 28 March 1980 in [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\">'RAYNER, Angela', ''[[Who's Who 2017]]'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016; online edn., November 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U283864 accessed 5 Oct 2017]</ref> She attended [[Stockport Academy|Avondale School]] in Stockport, leaving the school aged 16 after becoming pregnant, and did not obtain any qualifications.<ref name=\"oldham\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |title=Not bad for a ginger kid! |publisher=[[Oldham Chronicle]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819045552/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |archivedate=19 August 2016  }}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ Teen mum turned Labour MP: Why Angela Rayner should have the Tories running scared] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930081709/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ |date=30 September 2016 }}, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 29 September 2016</ref> She later studied part-time at [[Stockport College]], learning [[British Sign Language]], and qualifying as a [[Social care|social care worker]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\" />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter leaving college, Rayner worked for [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]] as a care worker for a number of years. During this time, she was also elected as a trade union representative for [[UNISON|Unison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |title=Joining a trade union |publisher=[[GOV.UK]] |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917171227/https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref> She was later elected as [[convenor]] of [[UNISON|Unison]] [[North West England|North West]], becoming the union's most senior official in the region.<ref name=\"schoolsweek\" /><ref name=\"Fitzgerald\">{{cite news|last=Fitzgearld|first=Todd|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|title=Commons vow by new Ashton MP Angela Rayner who was told she'd amount to nothing|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=13 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181523/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' featured a lengthy profile of Rayner in 2012, as part of an article on a trade union officer's working life.<ref>{{cite news|title=A working life: the Union Official|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216161110/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Angela Rayner, 2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|Rayner speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\nIn 2014, Rayner was selected to become Labour's candidate for the seat of [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], after the retirement of [[David Heyes]]. She won the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], increasing both the Labour majority and its share of the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Labour candidate: We need real people with life experience to bring common sense to Parliament|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=8 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915003947/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> She delivered her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 3 June 2015. In the 2017 general election held on Thursday 8 June 2017, Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat, increasing both the Labour majority and vote share. Rayner held her Ashton-under-Lyne seat a third time after winning the constituency in the general election held on Thursday 12 December 2019.\n\nRayner nominated [[Andy Burnham]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]], but the following year became one of just 18 MPs to back the incumbent [[Jeremy Corbyn]] against challenger [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 leadership election]].<ref name=\"KeepCorbyn\">{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|title=Corbyn addresses crowd of up to 10,000 on eve of confidence vote|publisher=[[LabourList]]|last=Pine|first=Sarah|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701080636/http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2016, after a series of resignations from the [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|Shadow Cabinet]], Corbyn appointed Rayner to the position of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]].<ref name=\"schoolsweek\">{{cite web |url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |title=Exclusive: Angela Rayner becomes third shadow education secretary in a week |publisher=Schools Week |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090147/http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]] Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat being returned as Member of Parliament for the third time in 5 years. She was elected to deputy leader on 4 April 2020 replacing [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]].\n\n==Political views==\nIn a 2017 interview discussing her political beliefs, Rayner highlighted her [[pragmatism]], described herself as being part of the \"[[soft left]]\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"auto\"/> As shadow education secretary, Rayner has championed the policy of a \u2019National Education Service\u2019, which would be modelled along similar lines to the UK [[National Health Service]], as well as promoting an increase in funding to early years education. She has previously written that decreasing teachers' salaries would lead to shortages in those joining the profession.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 England's schools face 'severe' teacher shortage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 |date=30 August 2018 }} ''[[BBC News]]''. 20 August 2018''</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, she married Mark Rayner, a Unison official.<ref name=\"WW 2017\" /> She has three sons: Ryan, who was born when she was aged 16; Jimmy; and Charlie.<ref name=\"oldham\" /> Charlie was born prematurely at 23 weeks and Rayner says that the care he received demonstrated the importance of the NHS to her.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unions blast Education Secretary over controversial reforms|url=http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|publisher=Equal Times|date=30 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065658/http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Rayner lives in her constituency of [[Ashton-under-Lyne]] with her family. She became a grandmother in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|title=Grangela: Labour's Angela Rayner is grandmother at 37|date=22 November 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|archivedate=22 November 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Evan Davis]] of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] in 2018, Rayner said that her mother had been unable to read or write; a repeat of part of a tribute she made to her mother in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |title=Labour MP Angela Rayner's tribute to her 'inspirational' mother |work=inews.co.uk |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925025945/https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Rayner revealed that she had fitted [[panic button]]s at her home after rape and death threats were sent to her a few weeks earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Angela Rayner has panic buttons fitted after online threats |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |accessdate=4 March 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304212645/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |archive-date=4 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, she confirmed she had been suffering symptoms of [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] and was self-isolating following medical advice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/|title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating|work=ITV News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.angelarayner.com/}}\n*[https://twitter.com/AngelaRayner?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Twitter]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=angela-rayner/4356 |publicwhip=Angela_Rayner |theywork=angela_rayner}}\n* [http://unisonactive.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/proud-loud-and-unison-angie-rayners.html ''UNISON blog'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Heyes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pat Glass]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Angela}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\