{"title_page": "Fort Worth Public Library", "text_new": "{{coord|32.7541|-97.3348|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=title}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Fort Worth Public Library\n| image = [[File:Fort Worth Central library entrance.png|300px]]\n| library_logo =\n| location = Fort Worth, Texas\n| established = 1901\n| num_branches = 16\n| collection_size = 2.065 million\n| annual_circulation = 4 million\n| pop_served = 686,850\n| budget =  $16,994,721\n| director = Manya Shorr\n| num_employees = 207\n| website = [http://www.fortworthgov.org/Library/]\n}}\n'''Fort Worth Public Library''' is the public library system that serves the city of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], [[Texas]]. The Fort Worth Public Libraries consist of 16 branches including the central library and two regional libraries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/branches/|title=Locations and Hours|website=Fort Worth Library|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn April 1892, 20 women formed the idea for the city's first library while meeting at the home of [[Jennie Scott Scheuber]]. Under the Fort Worth Public Library Association, this association received its state charter and with the financial support from [[Andrew Carnegie]] they brought the Fort Worth Public Library into existence.<ref name=\"History of Fort Worth Public Library\">[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=5610]</ref> Carnegie donated building funds for the construction of more than 2,000 libraries in the [[United States]] and from 1886 to 1919 he donated $56 million.<ref>Richard Rubin. ''Foundations of Library and Information Science''. Neal-Schuman Publishers, 2004.</ref> Carnegie suggested to the founding women that they ask the local gentlemen for \"the price of a good cigar\" to help raise the necessary local supporting funds. When the City Council approved spending $4,000 per year to run the library, Carnegie contributed $50,000 for the building.<ref>[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=5610].</ref> The Carnegie Public Library of Fort Worth opened on October 17, 1901, at Ninth and Throckmorton streets.\n\n==Central Library==\n\nFort Worth's Central Library expansion officially opened October 22, 1999. On March 28, 2000 the [[Fort Worth Tornado]] caused over a million dollars in damage to the new Central Library.<ref name=\"History of Fort Worth Public Library\" />\n\nCentral Library has a spacious Learning Commons for patrons to enjoy a book, magazine, or use a computer. The Central Library also offers its users free Internet access at the computer lab or with WiFi.<ref>[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=4144]</ref> Computer classes are available to promote [[information literacy]]. The Genealogy, Local History and Archives unit is housed within the Central Library; the Archives are also the official municipal archives of the City of Fort Worth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/genealogy/|title=Genealogy, History, Archives|website=Fort Worth Library|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>  [[Image:Fort Worth Library Computer Lab.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Fort Worth Central Library Computer Lab]]\n\n==Regional Libraries==\n* East Regional - opened ({{start date and age|1996}})\n* Southwest Regional - - opened ({{start date and age|1987}})\n\n==Branches==\n* Butler Outreach Library Division (BOLD) - opened ({{start date and age|1997}})\n* Cavile Outreach Opportunity Library (COOL) - - opened ({{start date and age|1994}})Diamond Hill/Jarvis - opened ({{start date and age|1989}})\n* East Berry - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Meadowbrook - opened ({{start date and age|1961}})\n* Northside - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Ridglea - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Riverside \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|1961}})\n* Seminary South - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Ella Mae Shamblee -opened ({{start date and age|2008}})\n* Summerglen \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|November 2000}})\n* Wedgwood - opened ({{start date and age|1962}})\n* Northwest \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|2010}})\n\n==Partner library systems==\nPartner systems, which accept the MetroPAC cards accepted by the Fort Worth system, include:<ref name=\"Locations\">\"[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/branches/ Locations and Hours].\" ''Fort Worth Library''. Retrieved on January 27, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Benbrook, Texas|Benbrook Public Library]]\n* [[Burleson, Texas|Burleson Public Library]]\n* [[Haltom City, Texas|Haltom City Public Library]]\n* [[Keller, Texas|Keller Public Library]]\n* [[Richland Hills, Texas|Richland Hills Public Library]]\n* [[Watauga, Texas|Watauga Public Library]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fortworthgov.org/Library/ Fort Worth Public Library]\n{{Fort Worth, Texas}}\n{{Texas public libraries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Culture of Fort Worth, Texas]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Fort Worth, Texas|Library]]\n[[Category:Education in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Texas]]\n[[Category:Government of Fort Worth, Texas|Library]]\n[[Category:David M. Schwarz buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|32.7541|-97.3348|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=title}}\n{{Infobox library\n| library_name = Fort Worth Public Library\n| image = [[File:Fort Worth Central library entrance.png|300px]]\n| library_logo =\n| location = Fort Worth, Texas\n| established = 1901\n| num_branches = 16\n| collection_size = 2.065 million\n| annual_circulation = 4 million\n| pop_served = 686,850\n| budget =  $16,994,721\n| director = Manya Shorr\n| num_employees = 207\n| website = [http://www.fortworthgov.org/Library/]\n}}\n'''Fort Worth Public Library''' is the public library system that serves the city of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], [[Texas]]. The Fort Worth Public Libraries consist of 16 branches including the central library and two regional libraries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/branches/|title=Locations and Hours|website=Fort Worth Library|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn April 1892, 20 women formed the idea for the city's first library while meeting at the home of [[Jennie Scott Scheuber]]. Under the Fort Worth Public Library Association, this association received its state charter and with the financial support from [[Andrew Carnegie]] they brought the Fort Worth Public Library into existence.<ref name=\"History of Fort Worth Public Library\">[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=5610]</ref> Carnegie donated building funds for the construction of more than 2,000 libraries in the [[United States]] and from 1886 to 1919 he donated $56 million.<ref>Richard Rubin. ''Foundations of Library and Information Science''. Neal-Schuman Publishers, 2004.</ref> Carnegie suggested to the founding women that they ask the local gentlemen for \"the price of a good cigar\" to help raise the necessary local supporting funds. When the City Council approved spending $4,000 per year to run the library, Carnegie contributed $50,000 for the building.<ref>[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=5610].</ref> The Carnegie Public Library of Fort Worth opened on October 17, 1901, at Ninth and Throckmorton streets.\n\n==Central Library==\n\nFort Worth's Central Library expansion officially opened October 22, 1999. On March 28, 2000 the [[Fort Worth Tornado]] caused over a million dollars in damage to the new Central Library.<ref name=\"History of Fort Worth Public Library\" />\n\nCentral Library has a spacious Learning Commons for patrons to enjoy a book, magazine, or use a computer. The Central Library also offers its users free Internet access at the computer lab or with WiFi.<ref>[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/info/default.aspx?id=4144]</ref> Computer classes are available to promote [[information literacy]]. The Genealogy, Local History and Archives unit is housed within the Central Library; the Archives are also the official municipal archives of the City of Fort Worth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/genealogy/|title=Genealogy, History, Archives|website=Fort Worth Library|language=en|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>  [[Image:Fort Worth Library Computer Lab.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Fort Worth Central Library Computer Lab]]\n\n==Regional Libraries==\n* East Regional - opened ({{start date and age|1996}})\n* Southwest Regional - - opened ({{start date and age|1987}})\n\n==Branches==\n* Butler Outreach Library Division (BOLD) - opened ({{start date and age|1997}})\n* Cavile Outreach Opportunity Library (COOL) - - opened ({{start date and age|1994}})Diamond Hill/Jarvis - opened ({{start date and age|1989}})\n* East Berry - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Meadowbrook - opened ({{start date and age|1961}})\n* Northside - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Ridglea - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Riverside \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|1961}})\n* Seminary South - opened ({{start date and age|1967}})\n* Ella Mae Shamblee -opened ({{start date and age|2008}})\n* Summerglen \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|November 2000}})\n* Wedgwood - opened ({{start date and age|1962}})\n* Northwest \u2013 opened ({{start date and age|2010}})\n\n==Partner library systems==\nPartner systems, which accept the MetroPAC cards accepted by the Fort Worth system, include:<ref name=\"Locations\">\"[http://www.fortworthgov.org/library/branches/ Locations and Hours].\" ''Fort Worth Library''. Retrieved on January 27, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Benbrook, Texas|Benbrook Public Library]]\n* [[Burleson, Texas|Burleson Public Library]]\n* [[Haltom City, Texas|Haltom City Public Library]]\n* [[Keller, Texas|Keller Public Library]]\n* [[Richland Hills, Texas|Richland Hills Public Library]]\n* [[Watauga, Texas|Watauga Public Library]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fortworthgov.org/Library/ Fort Worth Public Library]\n{{Fort Worth, Texas}}\n{{Texas public libraries}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Culture of Fort Worth, Texas]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Fort Worth, Texas|Library]]\n[[Category:Education in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Texas]]\n[[Category:Government of Fort Worth, Texas|Library]]\n", "name_user": "Herrikez", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Worth_Public_Library"}
{"title_page": "The Cave (2019 Syrian film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 Syrian documentary film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Cave\n| image          = The Cave 2019 Syrian poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Feras Fayyad]]\n| producer       = Sigrid Dyekj\u00e6r<br />Kirstine Barfod\n| writer         = Alisar Hasan<br />Feras Fayyad\n| starring       = [[Amani Ballour]]\n| music          = [[Matthew Herbert]]\n| cinematography = Muhammed Khair Al Shami<br />Ammar Sulaiman<br>Mohammad Eyad\n| editing        = Denniz G\u00f6l Bertelsen<br />Per K. Kirkegaard\n| studio         = Danish Documentary Production<br />Hecat Studio\n| distributor    = [[National Geographic Documentary Films]] (United States)\n| released       = {{film date|2019|09|05|[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Denmark<br />Syria\n| language       = Arabic<br />English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $191,703<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=thecave2019.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Cave-The-(Syria)#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Cave''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0647\u0641}}) is a 2019 Syrian-Danish [[Documentary film|documentary]] film directed by [[Feras Fayyad]] and written by Fayyad and Alisar Hasan.<ref name=lang>Brent Lang, [https://variety.com/2019/film/news/the-cave-feras-fayyad-syria-amani-ballor-1203325081/ \"With \u2018The Cave,\u2019 \u2018Last Men in Aleppo\u2019 Director Feras Fayyad Returns to Syria to Find a Hero\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', September 6, 2019.</ref> A companion piece to his earlier film ''[[Last Men in Aleppo]]'',<ref>Caryn James, [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/cave-review-1234314 \"'The Cave': Film Review | TIFF 2019\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', September 5, 2019.</ref> the film profiles [[Amani Ballour]], a female doctor in [[Ghouta]] who is operating a makeshift hospital nicknamed \"the Cave\" during the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>Tomris Laffley, [https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-cave-review-1203325088/ \"Toronto Film Review: \u2018The Cave\u2019\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', September 5, 2019.</ref> The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] (TIFF) on September 5, 2019.\n\nIn an interview, Fayyad said his purpose in making the film was to create documentary evidence that could be used to seek justice for innocent victims of the civil war. \"The film should put people in an uncomfortable position to look through the terrible reality around us,\" he said.<ref>{{cite web|website=CBC.ca|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-oct-28-2019-1.5337771/in-a-bunker-hospital-in-syria-a-director-made-it-his-mission-to-document-the-plight-of-innocent-civilians-1.5337808|title=In a bunker hospital in Syria, a director made it 'his mission' to document the plight of innocent civilians|author=Mac Cameron|accessdate=November 1, 2019|date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Reception and nominations==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series holds an approval rating of 97% with an average rating of 8.34/10, based on 61 reviews. The site's consensus states that \"A hard-hitting documentary with imagery as powerful as its message, ''The Cave'' poses heartbreakingly urgent questions -- and leaves them for the viewer to answer.\" <ref>{{Citation|title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_cave_2019|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award: Documentaries|People's Choice Award for Documentaries]].<ref>Jessica Wong, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/tiff19-awards-1.5284085 \"TIFF 2019: Jojo Rabbit captures TIFF People's Choice Award\"]. [[CBC News]], September 15, 2019.</ref>\n\n''The Cave'' won the Most Valuable Documentary Award of Year 2020 at the 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala.<ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n\n''The Cave'' was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[92nd Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"oscars2020\">{{cite news|title=Oscars 2020 nominations: Full list of nominees including Joker, Little Women and Jojo Rabbit|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2020/01/13/oscars-nominations-2020-can-expect-todays-announcement/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.nationalgeographic.com/films/the-cave/}}\n*{{IMDb title|7178226}}\n\n{{TIFF People's Choice Documentaries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cave, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Danish documentary films]]\n[[Category:Danish films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about women in war]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about health care]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Society films]]\n[[Category:Syrian documentary films]]\n[[Category:Syrian films]]\n\n\n{{Syria-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 Syrian documentary film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Cave\n| image          = The Cave 2019 Syrian poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Feras Fayyad]]\n| producer       = Sigrid Dyekj\u00e6r<br />Kirstine Barfod\n| writer         = Alisar Hasan<br />Feras Fayyad\n| starring       = Amani Ballour\n| music          = [[Matthew Herbert]]\n| cinematography = Muhammed Khair Al Shami<br />Ammar Sulaiman<br>Mohammad Eyad\n| editing        = Denniz G\u00f6l Bertelsen<br />Per K. Kirkegaard\n| studio         = Danish Documentary Production<br />Hecat Studio\n| distributor    = [[National Geographic Documentary Films]] (United States)\n| released       = {{film date|2019|09|05|[[2019 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = Denmark<br />Syria\n| language       = Arabic<br />English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $191,703<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=thecave2019.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb|IMDb.com, Inc.]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Cave-The-(Syria)#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Cave''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0647\u0641}}) is a 2019 Syrian-Danish [[Documentary film|documentary]] film directed by [[Feras Fayyad]] and written by Fayyad and Alisar Hasan.<ref name=lang>Brent Lang, [https://variety.com/2019/film/news/the-cave-feras-fayyad-syria-amani-ballor-1203325081/ \"With \u2018The Cave,\u2019 \u2018Last Men in Aleppo\u2019 Director Feras Fayyad Returns to Syria to Find a Hero\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', September 6, 2019.</ref> A companion piece to his earlier film ''[[Last Men in Aleppo]]'',<ref>Caryn James, [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/cave-review-1234314 \"'The Cave': Film Review | TIFF 2019\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', September 5, 2019.</ref> the film profiles Amani Ballour, a female doctor in [[Ghouta]] who is operating a makeshift hospital nicknamed \"the Cave\" during the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref>Tomris Laffley, [https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-cave-review-1203325088/ \"Toronto Film Review: \u2018The Cave\u2019\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', September 5, 2019.</ref> The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] (TIFF) on September 5, 2019.\n\nIn an interview, Fayyad said his purpose in making the film was to create documentary evidence that could be used to seek justice for innocent victims of the civil war. \"The film should put people in an uncomfortable position to look through the terrible reality around us,\" he said.<ref>{{cite web|website=CBC.ca|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/thecurrent/the-current-for-oct-28-2019-1.5337771/in-a-bunker-hospital-in-syria-a-director-made-it-his-mission-to-document-the-plight-of-innocent-civilians-1.5337808|title=In a bunker hospital in Syria, a director made it 'his mission' to document the plight of innocent civilians|author=Mac Cameron|accessdate=November 1, 2019|date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Reception and nominations==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series holds an approval rating of 97% with an average rating of 8.34/10, based on 61 reviews. The site's consensus states that \"A hard-hitting documentary with imagery as powerful as its message, ''The Cave'' poses heartbreakingly urgent questions -- and leaves them for the viewer to answer.\" <ref>{{Citation|title=The Cave (2019)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_cave_2019|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award: Documentaries|People's Choice Award for Documentaries]].<ref>Jessica Wong, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/tiff19-awards-1.5284085 \"TIFF 2019: Jojo Rabbit captures TIFF People's Choice Award\"]. [[CBC News]], September 15, 2019.</ref>\n\n''The Cave'' won the Most Valuable Documentary Award of Year 2020 at the 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala.<ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n\n''The Cave'' was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[92nd Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"oscars2020\">{{cite news|title=Oscars 2020 nominations: Full list of nominees including Joker, Little Women and Jojo Rabbit|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2020/01/13/oscars-nominations-2020-can-expect-todays-announcement/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.nationalgeographic.com/films/the-cave/}}\n*{{IMDb title|7178226}}\n\n{{TIFF People's Choice Documentaries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cave, The}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Danish documentary films]]\n[[Category:Danish films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about women in war]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about health care]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Society films]]\n[[Category:Syrian documentary films]]\n[[Category:Syrian films]]\n\n\n{{Syria-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bahnmoeller", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Cave_(2019_Syrian_film)"}
{"title_page": "SSC Tuatara", "text_new": "{{short description|High performance sports car produced by SSC North America}}\n{{about|the [[sports car]]|the experimental music band|Tuatara (band)|the animal|Tuatara}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = SSC Tuatara\n| image = 2019 SSC Tuatara at Pebble Beach Press Conference.jpg\n| caption = \n| manufacturer = [[SSC North America]]\n| designer = Jerod Shelby<br>\n[[Jason Castriota]]\n| production = 2020- <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://driving.ca/auto-news/news/its-coming-the-1750-horsepower-ssc-tuatara-finally-enters-production|date=July 4, 2019|title=It's coming! The 1,750-horsepower SSC Tuatara finally enters production|publisher=Driving|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| assembly = [[Richland, Washington]], United States\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout| Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| engine = {{ubl\n|'''Concept:'''\n|{{cvt|423.6|cuin|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[twin-turbocharged]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|'''Production version:'''\n|{{cvt|5.9|L|cuin|1|abbr=on}} twin-turbocharged V8\n}}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n|'''Concept options:'''\n|7-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n|7-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic]]\n|'''Production version:'''\n|7-speed semi-automatic\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|105.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|182.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|81.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|42.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|2750|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[SSC Aero|SSC Ultimate Aero]]\n| chassis = Carbon Fiber Monocoque\n| powerout = 1,750 HP on E85<br>1,350 HP on 91 Octane\n}}\n\nThe '''SSC Tuatara''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|u|\u0259|t|\u0251\u02d0|r|\u0259}} is an upcoming [[United States of America|America]]n [[sports car]] to be produced by automobile manufacturer [[SSC North America]] (formerly '''S'''helby '''S'''uper'''C'''ars Inc.). The car is the successor to the [[SSC Aero]] and is the result of a design collaboration between [[Jason Castriota]] and SSC. Initially it was to be powered by a 6.9-liter twin-turbocharged V8 engine but eventually the capacity of the engine was reduced to 5.9-liters in order to allow the engine to have a higher redline of 8,800 rpm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara|date=July 6, 2019|title=Tuatara,SSC NorthAmerica|publisher=SSC NorthAmerica|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> SSC has stated that the power output would be at {{convert|1350|hp|kW PS|abbr=on|0}}  or {{convert|1750|hp|kW PS|abbr=on|0}} on E85 fuel, along with the top speed goal of {{convert|300|mph|kph|1|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/pebble-beach-2018/new-ssc-tuatara-aiming-300mph-top-speed|date=September 4, 2018|title=New SSC Tuatara is aiming for a 311mph top speed | publisher=Top Gear|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:SSC Tuatara by J.Smith831 - 003.jpg|thumb|SSC Tuatara concept]]\nSSC began working on the development of the successor of the [[SSC Aero|SSC Ultimate Aero]] in 2011. The new car, named the Tuatara was previewed in concept form at the 2011 [[Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance]] but due to certain reasons never came to the production stage. In August 2018, 7 years after the debut of the concept, the production version of the Tuatara was shown to the general public. Designed by ex-[[Pininfarina]] designer [[Jason Castriota]], the car takes inspiration from the aerospace industry.\n\nThe Tuatara is named after the [[Tuatara|reptile]], found only in [[New Zealand]], known for having the fastest molecular evolution of any living animal.\n\nBoasting the lowest [[drag coefficient]] in its class at 0.279 and having a [[Carbon fiber reinforced polymer|carbon-fiber]] body construction with aluminum crumple zones, SSC aims to set new benchmarks in the production car speed records by beating its competitors outright.\n\nThe interior contains leather and [[Alcantara (material)|Alcantara]] upholstery and the functions of the car are controlled through a touch screen located on the center console. There is a configurable instrument panel behind the steering wheel displaying important information  about the car's status along with a 300 mph speedometer. The car uses a camera system instead of traditional side view mirrors.\n\nThe Tuatara will be produced at a purpose-built facility in West Richland, Washington and production will be limited to 100 cars.\n\nSSC has partnered with Nelson Racing Engines to build the engine, Linder Power Systems for engine sub-assembly fabrication and Automac for the production of the 7-speed semi-automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/news/tuatara-released|title=Press Release - The Tuatara Released|date=August 25, 2018|work=SSC North America|accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications and general data==\n===Engine===\n* '''Type''':  SSC-designed billet aluminium flat-plane crank V8 \n* '''Displacement''':  {{cvt|5.9|L|cuin cc|abbr=on}}\n* '''Compression Ratio''': 8.80:1\n* '''Horsepower''': {{convert|1350|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm (Engine is able to produce up to {{convert|1750|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 8,800 rpm on E85 flex fuel)\n* '''Torque''': {{convert|1280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm<ref name=\"gizmag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/ssc-teases-1700-hp/27276/|title=SSC completes engine testing on Tuatara supercar, teases 1,700 hp|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''Redline''': 8,800 rpm\n* '''Fuel Injection''': Electronic sequential port with dual injection per cylinder\n* '''Oil''': SAE 5W/30 Fully Synthetic (Racing)\n* '''Induction System''': Sequential, multi-port fuel injection, twin-turbochargers, dual-water to air intercoolers\n* '''Fuel''': Premium Unleaded - 91RON pump octane, E85 flex fuel\n* '''Weight''': {{cvt|428|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Transmission''':  7-Speed semi-automatic with robotised shifting mechanism\n* '''Clutch''': Triple-disc carbon ceramic, zicro'titanium clutch\n\n===General data===\n* '''Wheelbase''': {{convert|105.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Length''': {{convert|182.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Width''': {{convert|81.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Height''': {{convert|42.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Ground Clearance''': {{convert|4.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Layout''': Mid-engined (Aero Direct-Straightline position of engine)\n* '''Drivetrain''': Longitudinal adjustable optional electrological rear-wheel drive (RWD)\n* '''Body/Frame''': Carbon-fiber/Carbon-fiber/Aluminium crash structures\n* '''Coefficient of Drag (Cd)''': 0.279\n* '''Frontal Area''': 18.0 sq. ft.\n* '''Brakes (Front)''': 16.0 inch Vented and slotted carbon ceramic discs with 6-piston calipers\n* '''Brakes (Rear)''': 15.0 inch Vented and slotted carbon ceramic discs with 4-piston calipers\n* '''Wheels''': Single-piece carbon fiber (19x9-1/2\" Front, 20x13\" Rear)\n* '''Tires''': [[Michelin]] Pilot Ultra Sport PS2-F1 (245/35 (YR)20 Front, 345/35 (YR)20 Rear)\n* '''Steering''': Rack & Pinion, Variable electric assist tilt column\n* '''Turns - Lock to Lock''': 2.5\n* '''Turning Circle''': {{convert|41.6|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n* '''Suspension''' (F/R): Adjustable hydraulic system with unequal length upper and lower A-arms, coil-over springs, remote reservoir-adjustable [[Penske]] coil-over shocks, cab controlled air lift, anti-roll bars\n* '''Total Dry Weight''': {{convert|2750|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara|publisher=SSC North America |date= August 24, 2018|accessdate=August 26, 2018|title=The future of HyperCars is here}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|SSC Tuatara}}\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara.php}}\n* [https://www.foxnews.com/auto/say-hello-to-the-275-mph-tuatara Say Hello to the 275 MPH Tuatara]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722051214/http://www.thirdage.com/news/tuatara-supercar-will-hit-275-mph_07-20-2011 Tuatara will hit 275 MPH]\n* [http://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/article45873270.html West Richland car plant ready to get rolling]\n\n* [https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1118285_ssc-reveals-tuatara-hypercars-twin-turbo-v-8 SSC reveals Tuatara hypercar's twin-turbo V-8]\n\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|High performance sports car produced by SSC North America}}\n{{about|the [[sports car]]|the experimental music band|Tuatara (band)|the animal|Tuatara}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = SSC Tuatara\n| image = 2019 SSC Tuatara at Pebble Beach Press Conference.jpg\n| caption = \n| manufacturer = [[SSC North America]]\n| designer = Jerod Shelby<br>\n[[Jason Castriota]]\n| production = 2020- <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://driving.ca/auto-news/news/its-coming-the-1750-horsepower-ssc-tuatara-finally-enters-production|date=July 4, 2019|title=It's coming! The 1,750-horsepower SSC Tuatara finally enters production|publisher=Driving|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| assembly = [[Richland, Washington]], United States\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout| Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| engine = {{ubl\n|'''Concept:'''\n|{{cvt|423.6|cuin|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[twin-turbocharged]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|'''Production version:'''\n|{{cvt|5.9|L|cuin|1|abbr=on}} twin-turbocharged V8\n}}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n|'''Concept options:'''\n|7-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n|7-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic]]\n|'''Production version:'''\n|7-speed semi-automatic\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|105.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|182.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|81.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|42.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|2750|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[SSC Aero|SSC Ultimate Aero]]\n| chassis = Carbon Fiber Monocoque\n| powerout = 1,750 HP on E85<br>1,350 HP on 91 Octane\n}}\n\nThe '''SSC Tuatara''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|u|\u0259|t|\u0251\u02d0|r|\u0259}} is an upcoming [[United States of America|America]]n [[sports car]] to be produced by automobile manufacturer [[SSC North America]] (formerly '''S'''helby '''S'''uper'''C'''ars Inc.). The car is the successor to the [[SSC Aero]] and is the result of a design collaboration between [[Jason Castriota]] and SSC. Initially it was to be powered by a 6.9-liter twin-turbocharged V8 engine but eventually the capacity of the engine was reduced to 5.9-liters in order to allow the engine to have a higher redline of 8,800 rpm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara|date=July 6, 2019|title=Tuatara,SSC NorthAmerica|publisher=SSC NorthAmerica|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> SSC has stated that the power output would be at {{convert|1350|hp|kW PS|abbr=on|0}}  or {{convert|1750|hp|kW PS|abbr=on|0}} on E85 fuel, along with the top speed goal of {{convert|300|mph|kph|1|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/pebble-beach-2018/new-ssc-tuatara-aiming-300mph-top-speed|date=September 4, 2018|title=New SSC Tuatara is aiming for a 311mph top speed | publisher=Top Gear|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:SSC Tuatara by J.Smith831 - 003.jpg|thumb|SSC Tuatara concept]]\nSSC began working on the development of the successor of the [[SSC Aero|SSC Ultimate Aero]] in 2011. The new car, named the Tuatara was previewed in concept form at the 2011 [[Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance]] but due to certain reasons never came to the production stage. In August 2018, 7 years after the debut of the concept, the production version of the Tuatara was shown to the general public. Designed by ex-[[Pininfarina]] designer [[Jason Castriota]], the car takes inspiration from the aero space industry.\n\nThe Tuatara is named after the [[Tuatara|reptile]], found only in [[New Zealand]], known for having the fastest molecular evolution of any living animal.\n\nBoasting the lowest [[Drag coefficient|coefficient of drag]] in its class at 0.279 and having a [[Carbon fiber reinforced polymer|carbon-fiber]] body construction with aluminum crumple zones, SSC aims to set new benchmarks in the production car speed records by beating its competitors outright.\n\nThe interior contains leather and [[Alcantara_(material)|Alcantara]] upholstery and the functions of the car are controlled through a touch screen located on the center console. There is a configurable instrument panel behind the steering wheel displaying important information  about the car's status along with a 300 mph speedometer. The car uses a camera system instead of traditional side view mirrors.\n\nThe Tuatara will be produced at a purpose-built facility in West Richland, Washington and production will be limited to 100 cars.\n\nSSC has partnered with Nelson Racing Engines to build the engine, Linder Power Systems for engine sub-assembly fabrication and Automac for the production of the 7-speed semi-automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/news/tuatara-released|title=Press Release - The Tuatara Released|date=August 25, 2018|work=SSC North America|accessdate=August 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications and general data==\n===Engine===\n* '''Type''':  SSC-designed billet aluminium flat-plane crank V8 \n* '''Displacement''':  {{cvt|5.9|L|cuin cc|abbr=on}}\n* '''Compression Ratio''': 8.80:1\n* '''Horsepower''': {{convert|1350|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm (Engine is able to produce up to {{convert|1750|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 8,800 rpm on E85 flex fuel)\n* '''Torque''': {{convert|1280|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm<ref name=\"gizmag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/ssc-teases-1700-hp/27276/|title=SSC completes engine testing on Tuatara supercar, teases 1,700 hp|publisher=}}</ref>\n* '''Redline''': 8,800 rpm\n* '''Fuel Injection''': Electronic sequential port with dual injection per cylinder\n* '''Oil''': SAE 5W/30 Fully Synthetic (Racing)\n* '''Induction System''': Sequential, multi-port fuel injection, twin-turbochargers, dual-water to air intercoolers\n* '''Fuel''': Premium Unleaded - 91RON pump octane, E85 flex fuel\n* '''Weight''': {{cvt|428|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Transmission''':  7-Speed semi-automatic with robotised shifting mechanism\n* '''Clutch''': Triple-disc carbon ceramic, zicro'titanium clutch\n\n===General data===\n* '''Wheelbase''': {{convert|105.2|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Length''': {{convert|182.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Width''': {{convert|81.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Height''': {{convert|42.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Ground Clearance''': {{convert|4.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n* '''Layout''': Mid-engined (Aero Direct-Straightline position of engine)\n* '''Drivetrain''': Longitudinal adjustable optional electrological rear-wheel drive (RWD)\n* '''Body/Frame''': Carbon-fiber/Carbon-fiber/Aluminium crash structures\n* '''Coefficient of Drag (Cd)''': 0.279\n* '''Frontal Area''': 18.0 sq. ft.\n* '''Brakes (Front)''': 16.0 inch Vented and slotted carbon ceramic discs with 6-piston calipers\n* '''Brakes (Rear)''': 15.0 inch Vented and slotted carbon ceramic discs with 4-piston calipers\n* '''Wheels''': Single-piece carbon fiber (19x9-1/2\" Front, 20x13\" Rear)\n* '''Tires''': [[Michelin]] Pilot Ultra Sport PS2-F1 (245/35 (YR)20 Front, 345/35 (YR)20 Rear)\n* '''Steering''': Rack & Pinion, Variable electric assist tilt column\n* '''Turns - Lock to Lock''': 2.5\n* '''Turning Circle''': {{convert|41.6|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n* '''Suspension''' (F/R): Adjustable hydraulic system with unequal length upper and lower A-arms, coil-over springs, remote reservoir-adjustable [[Penske]] coil-over shocks, cab controlled air lift, anti-roll bars\n* '''Total Dry Weight''': {{convert|2750|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara|publisher=SSC North America |date= August 24, 2018|accessdate=August 26, 2018|title=The future of HyperCars is here}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|SSC Tuatara}}\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.sscnorthamerica.com/tuatara.php}}\n* [https://www.foxnews.com/auto/say-hello-to-the-275-mph-tuatara Say Hello to the 275 MPH Tuatara]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110722051214/http://www.thirdage.com/news/tuatara-supercar-will-hit-275-mph_07-20-2011 Tuatara will hit 275 MPH]\n* [http://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/article45873270.html West Richland car plant ready to get rolling]\n\n* [https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1118285_ssc-reveals-tuatara-hypercars-twin-turbo-v-8 SSC reveals Tuatara hypercar's twin-turbo V-8]\n\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "Da\u00df W\u00f6lf", "label": "safe", "comment": "reinstated correct parts of IP edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SSC_Tuatara"}
{"title_page": "Marieke Lucas Rijneveld", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2020}}{{notability|1=Biographies|date=April 2020}}}}\n{{short description|Dutch poet and writer}}\n[[File:Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2016).jpg|thumb|Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2016)]]\n'''Marieke Lucas Rijneveld''' (born April 1991, [[Nieuwendijk]], Netherlands) is a Dutch writer.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/life-culture/article/48140/1/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-interview-the-discomfort-of-evening|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld: the Dutch dairy farmer who wrote a bestseller|last1=Kinsella|first1=Ana|date=|website=Dazed|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebookerprizes.com/author/marieke-lucas-rijneveld|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld {{!}} The Booker Prizes|website=thebookerprizes.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> They use the pronouns they/them.<ref name=\"Flood\">{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/02/international-booker-prize-shortlist-led-by-28-year-olds-debut|title=International Booker prize shortlist led by 28-year-old\u2019s debut|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Their debut novel, translated into English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'' by Michele Hutchison, was nominated for the [[International Booker Prize]] in 2020, making them only the third Dutch author to be nominated for the prize, after [[Tommy Wieringa]] (longlisted in 2019) and [[Harry Mulisch]] (shortlisted in 2007).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebookerprizes.com/international-booker/news/interview-longlisted-author-marieke-lucas-rijneveld-and-translator-michele|title=Interview with longlisted author Marieke Lucas Rijneveld and translator Michele Hutchison {{!}} The Booker Prizes|website=thebookerprizes.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Marieke lucas rijneveld-1521366879.jpg|thumb|Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2018)]]\nRijneveld grew up in a religious family on a farm in [[North Brabant]] in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/books/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-the-discomfort-of-evening-interview-books-mental-health-author-2519930|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld: 'My stories all came back to the loss of my brother'|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> They have said that their debut novel, translated into English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'', is inspired partly by the death of their brother when the author was three.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''Kalfsvlies'', 2015 (English: ''Calf's caul,'' excerpts from which were translated into English by Sarah Timmer Harvey and shortlisted for [[Asymptote (magazine)|Asymptote]] magazine's 'Close Approximations' translation contest in 2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/special-feature/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-calfs-caul/|title=from Calf\u2019s Caul - Asymptote|website=www.asymptotejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/blog/2017/08/16/close-approximations-in-conversation-with-poetry-runner-up-sarah-timmer-harvey/|title=Close Approximations: In Conversation With Poetry Runner-up Sarah Timmer Harvey - Asymptote Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''Fantoommerrie'', 2019 (English: ''Phantom Mare'')\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''De avond is ongemak,'' published in English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'', translated by [[Michele Hutchison]] ([[Faber and Faber|Faber & Faber]]) <nowiki>ISBN 9780571349364</nowiki>.\n\n== Awards ==\n* ''Kalfsvlies'', awarded the [[C. Buddingh'-prijs|C. Buddingh\u2019 Prize]] for best Dutch-language poetry debut in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/poet/28881/Marieke-Lucas-Rijneveld|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (poet) - The Netherlands - Poetry International|website=www.poetryinternational.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''De avond is ongemak,'' awarded the ANV Debutantenprijs, the prize for best debut novel in Dutch, in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.letterenfonds.nl/en/entry/2435/winners-anv-debutantenprijs|title=news - Winners ANV Debutantenprijs - Letterenfonds|website=www.letterenfonds.nl|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''The Discomfort of Evening'', translated by Michele Hutchison, was nominated for the International Booker Prize in 2020.<ref name=\"Flood\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Self|first=John|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-discomfort-of-evening-by-marieke-lucas-rijneveld-trans-by-michele-hutchison-review-no-comfort-on-this-farm-br2hgsksq|title=The Discomfort of Evening by Marieke Lucas Rijneveld review \u2014 no comfort on this farm|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rijneveld, Marieke Lucas}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Dutch novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{notability|1=Biographies|date=April 2020}}}}\n{{short description|Dutch poet and writer}}\n[[File:Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2016).jpg|thumb|Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2016)]]\nMarieke Lucas Rijneveld (born April 1991, [[Nieuwendijk]], Netherlands) is a Dutch writer.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/life-culture/article/48140/1/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-interview-the-discomfort-of-evening|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld: the Dutch dairy farmer who wrote a bestseller|last1=Kinsella|first1=Ana|date=|website=Dazed|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebookerprizes.com/author/marieke-lucas-rijneveld|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld {{!}} The Booker Prizes|website=thebookerprizes.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> They use the pronouns they/them.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/02/international-booker-prize-shortlist-led-by-28-year-olds-debut|title=International Booker prize shortlist led by 28-year-old\u2019s debut|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Their debut novel, translated into English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'' by Michele Hutchison, was nominated for the [[International Booker Prize]] in 2020, making them only the third Dutch author to be nominated for the prize, after [[Tommy Wieringa]] (longlisted in 2019) and [[Harry Mulisch]] (shortlisted in 2007).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebookerprizes.com/international-booker/news/interview-longlisted-author-marieke-lucas-rijneveld-and-translator-michele|title=Interview with longlisted author Marieke Lucas Rijneveld and translator Michele Hutchison {{!}} The Booker Prizes|website=thebookerprizes.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Marieke lucas rijneveld-1521366879.jpg|thumb|Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (2018)]]\nRijneveld grew up in a religious family on a farm in [[North Brabant]] in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/books/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-the-discomfort-of-evening-interview-books-mental-health-author-2519930|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld: 'My stories all came back to the loss of my brother'|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> They have said that their debut novel, translated into English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'', is inspired partly by the death of their brother when the author was three.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Poetry ===\n* ''Kalfsvlies'', 2015 (English: ''Calf's caul,'' excerpts from which were translated into English by Sarah Timmer Harvey and shortlisted for [[Asymptote (magazine)|Asymptote]] magazine\u2019s 'Close Approximations' translation contest in 2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/special-feature/marieke-lucas-rijneveld-calfs-caul/|title=from Calf\u2019s Caul - Asymptote|website=www.asymptotejournal.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/blog/2017/08/16/close-approximations-in-conversation-with-poetry-runner-up-sarah-timmer-harvey/|title=Close Approximations: In Conversation With Poetry Runner-up Sarah Timmer Harvey - Asymptote Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''Fantoommerrie'', 2019 (English: ''Phantom Mare'')<br />\n\n=== Books ===\n* ''De avond is ongemak,'' published in English as ''The Discomfort of Evening'', translated by [[Michele Hutchison]] ([[Faber and Faber|Faber & Faber]]) <nowiki>ISBN 9780571349364</nowiki>.\n\n== Awards ==\n* ''Kalfsvlies'', awarded the [[C. Buddingh'-prijs|C. Buddingh\u2019 Prize]] for best Dutch-language poetry debut in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/poet/28881/Marieke-Lucas-Rijneveld|title=Marieke Lucas Rijneveld (poet) - The Netherlands - Poetry International|website=www.poetryinternational.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''De avond is ongemak,'' awarded the ANV Debutantenprijs, the prize for best debut novel in Dutch, in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.letterenfonds.nl/en/entry/2435/winners-anv-debutantenprijs|title=news - Winners ANV Debutantenprijs - Letterenfonds|website=www.letterenfonds.nl|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* ''The Discomfort of Evening'', translated by Michele Hutchison, was nominated for the International Booker Prize in 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Flood|first=Alison|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/02/international-booker-prize-shortlist-led-by-28-year-olds-debut|title=International Booker prize shortlist led by 28-year-old\u2019s debut|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Self|first=John|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-discomfort-of-evening-by-marieke-lucas-rijneveld-trans-by-michele-hutchison-review-no-comfort-on-this-farm-br2hgsksq|title=The Discomfort of Evening by Marieke Lucas Rijneveld review \u2014 no comfort on this farm|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rijneveld, Marieke Lucas}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Dutch novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marieke_Lucas_Rijneveld"}
{"title_page": "Saw (franchise)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Saw'' (franchise)}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''Saw''\n| image = Saw film logo.png\n| imagesize = 210\n| caption = Official franchise logo\n| creator = [[James Wan]]<br />[[Leigh Whannell]]\n| owner = [[Lions Gate Entertainment]]\n| origin = ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n| comics = * ''[[Saw: Rebirth]]'' (2005)\n| films = * ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Saw II]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Saw III]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Saw IV]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Saw V]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Saw VI]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw 3D]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'' (2020)\n| shorts = * ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n* ''Full Disclosure Report: Piecing Together Jigsaw'' (2005)\n* ''The Scott Tibbs Documentary'' (2006)\n| vgs = * ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'' (2010)\n| radio = \n| soundtracks = * ''[[Saw (soundtrack)|Saw]]''\n* ''[[Saw II (soundtrack)|Saw II]]''\n* ''[[Saw III (soundtrack)|Saw III]]''\n* ''[[Saw IV (soundtrack)|Saw IV]]'' \n* ''[[Saw V (soundtrack)|Saw V]]'' \n* ''[[Saw VI (soundtrack)|Saw VI]]'' \n* ''[[Saw 3D (Original Score Soundtrack)|Saw 3D]]'' \n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)#Music|Jigsaw]]''\n| music = * \"[[Hello Zepp]]\"\n| otherlabel1 = Theme park ride(s)\n| otherdata1 = * [[Saw \u2013 The Ride]]\n| otherlabel2 = Haunted attraction(s)\n| otherdata2 = * Game Over<ref name=\"gover\">{{Cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2009/oct/12/sprawling-21st-century-freak-show/|title=Fright Dome: Circus Circus fear factory teems with terrific human horrors - Las Vegas Sun Newspaper|first=Joe|last=Brown|date=October 12, 2009|website=lasvegassun.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw's Revenge<ref name=\"gover\" />\n* Saw: Game Over<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3172917/a-bd-walkthrough-of-saw-game-over-jigsaw-s-horror-nights-maze/|title=A BD Walkthrough of \u2018Saw: Game Over\u2019, Jigsaw\u2019s Horror Nights Maze!|first=Bloody Disgusting|last=Staff|date=August 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* Saw: Game On<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldofpopculture.com/vampyrecastle-of-the-undead-added-to-halloween-horror-nights-2010/|title='Vampyre:Castle of the Undead' Added to Halloween Horror Nights 2010!|first=Kristyn|last=Clarke|date=September 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* Saw Maze<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parkz.com.au/update/2010/10/28/254-Warner_Bros_Movie_World_Halloween_2010.html|title=The Parkz Update: Warner Bros. Movie World, Halloween 2010|website=Parkz}}</ref>\n* Saw: The Games of Jigsaw<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/08/14/universal-studios-saw-the-games-of-jigsaw-to-set-new-traps-for-guests-during-halloween-horror-nights/|title=Universal Studios\u2019 \u2018SAW: The Games of Jigsaw\u2019 to set new traps for guests during Halloween Horror Nights|date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* Saw: Alive<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thorpepark.com/fright-nights/saw-alive|title=SAW: Alive - Live Action Horror Maze &#124; Thorpe Park|website=www.thorpepark.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw: Survive the Trap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/09/27/saw-jigsaw-escape-room-new-york-comic-con/|title='Jigsaw'-themed escape room to trap 'Saw' fans at New York Comic Con|website=EW.com}}</ref>\n* Saw Escape Room<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://attractionsmagazine.com/saw-escape-room-opens-in-las-vegas/|title=Official 'Saw' escape room now open in Las Vegas|date=January 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| otherlabel3 = Fan Film(s) Universe\n| otherdata3 = * ''Saw: Heritage'' (2016)\n* ''Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage'' (2016)\n* ''Saw: Bloodlines'' (2020)\n* ''He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw'' (2020)\n}}\n\n'''''Saw''''' is an American [[horror film|horror]] [[media franchise|franchise]] created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]]. It consists of eight [[feature film]]s and additional media.\n\nIn 2003, Wan and Whannell made a [[Saw (2003 film)|short film]] to help [[Sales presentation|pitch]] a potential [[feature film]] concept. Their pitch was ultimately successful, and in 2004, [[Saw (2004 film)|the first installment]] of what would become the feature film franchise debuted at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]. The film was released theatrically that October, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. The sequels were directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], [[David Hackl]], and [[Kevin Greutert]], and were written by Wan, Whannell, Bousman, [[Patrick Melton]], and [[Marcus Dunstan]], and were released subsequently every October, on the Friday before [[Halloween]], between 2004 and 2010. Both of the creators remained with the franchise as [[executive producer]]s.\n\nOn July 22, 2010, producer [[Mark Burg]] confirmed that the seventh film, ''[[Saw 3D]]'', is the final installment of the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowles|first=Scott|date=July 22, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-22-saw22_ST_N.htm|title='Saw 3D' will be the final cut for horror franchise|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=July 22, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61r3dlvkb|archive-date=September 20, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, Lionsgate reportedly expressed interest in continuing the franchise with a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]].<ref name=\"Lionsgate Remaking Saw\">{{cite web|title=Lionsgate Remaking Saw?|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/58024/lionsgate-remaking-saw|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> In November 2013, it was reported that they were actively developing a sequel.<ref name=\"bloody-disgusting.com\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Lionsgate Is Actively Developing Next 'Saw'|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3262916/exclusive-lionsgate-is-actively-developing-next-saw/|publisher=Bloody Disgusting}}</ref> An eighth film, ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'', was eventually released in October 2017. In 2019, a ninth film was announced, ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'', with comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] attached to star, produce, and co-write.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/|title=\u2018SAW\u2019 Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct!|first=Brad|last=Miska|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise primarily revolves around [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]], also called the \"Jigsaw Killer\" or simply \"Jigsaw\". He was introduced briefly in ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' and developed in more detail in ''[[Saw II]]'' and the subsequent films. Rather than killing his [[List of Saw characters|victims]] outright, Jigsaw traps them in situations that he calls \"tests\" or \"games\" to test their will to live through physical or psychological torture and believes that if they survive, they will be \"rehabilitated\". Despite the fact that John was murdered in ''[[Saw III]]'', the films continue to focus on the posthumous influence of the Jigsaw Killer and his apprentices by exploring his character via [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]].\n\nThe franchise grossed more than {{US$|1 billion|long=no|link=yes}} from [[box office]] and retail sales by 2009,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lidz|first=Franz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html?_r=1&pagewanted=2&hpw|title=Limbs Pile Up, and Money, Too|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=October 21, 2009|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> and the films have collectively grossed over {{US$|976 million|long=no}} at the worldwide box office as of 2018. The film series as a whole has received mostly mixed to negative reviews by critics, but has been a financial success at the box office and is one of the highest-grossing horror film franchises of all time. While the films have been classified as [[Splatter film#Torture porn|torture porn]] by some critics,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sharrett|first=Christopher|title=The Problem of Saw: \"Torture Porn\" and the Conservatism of Contemporary Horror Films|magazine=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]|number=1|volume=35|date=December 2009|pages=32\u201337 |jstor= 41690851 |url=https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016013623/https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |archivedate= 2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442 | last=Nelson|first=Rob| title=Saw VI Movie Review | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] | date=October 23, 2009 | access-date=December 8, 2009| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nfI0IX | archive-date=January 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699|title=Saw VI \u2013 Film Review|last=Scheck|first=Frank|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 23, 2009|access-date=September 15, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQpk10a|archive-date=September 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> the creators of ''Saw'' disagree with that term.<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/|title=Saw creators Leigh Whannell and James Wan|last=Tobias|first=Scott|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=October 29, 2010|access-date=August 16, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/60zpLcBgr|archive-date=August 16, 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=100%\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Screenwriter(s) \n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" width=15%| Producer(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2004|10|29}}\n| [[James Wan]]\n| [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| James Wan and Leigh Whannell\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gregg Hoffman]], [[Oren Koules]] and [[Mark Burg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw II]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2005|10|28}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Leigh Whannell and Darren Lynn Bousman\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw III]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2006|10|27}}\n| Leigh Whannell\n| Leigh Whannell and James Wan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2007|10|26}}\n| [[Patrick Melton]] & [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan and [[Thomas Fenton]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw V]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2008|10|24}}\n| [[David Hackl]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2009|10|23}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Kevin Greutert]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2010|10|29}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2017|10|27}}\n| [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Josh Stolberg]] & Peter Goldfinger\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2020|5|15}}\n| Darren Lynn Bousman\n| Josh Stolberg & Peter Goldfinger\n| [[Chris Rock]]\n| Oren Koules and Mark Burg\n|}\n\n===Future===\n{{Main|Spiral (2020 film)}}\nIn May 2019, it was confirmed that a ninth film in the series was in production.  Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] will return to helm the film. Comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] will star in the film and will also be involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Rock stated \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/|title=Chris Rock To Reboot \u2018Saw\u2019 Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> ''Jigsaw'' writers Josh Stolberg and Pete Goldfinger are returning to write the screenplay. Stolberg later clarified that ninth installment will exist in the same continuity of the previous films, though it will not be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143993966049685504|title=The film is NOT a reboot. It is canon. All the films exist in the same universe. And who knows, maybe Saw X will tie all the stories together. You never know.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143028357610627073|title=I can say with pretty much certainly that our new film will NOT be called Jigsaw 2. But I don't make the decisions, so who knows. But it's NOT a sequel to Jigsaw. It's DEFINITELY in the timeline of ALL the films though.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe movie began filming in June 2019 and was scheduled to be released in theaters on May 15, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/112615/20190524/saw-9-release-date-spoilers-chris-rock-reboot-might-introduce-creepy-new-john-kramer.htm|title='Saw 9' Release Date, Spoilers: Chris Rock Reboot Might Introduce Creepy New John Kramer|first=Business|last=Times|date=May 24, 2019|website=Business Times|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/|title=New Saw Movie Set To Start Filming This Month|date=June 27, 2019|website=ScreenRant|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> but was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Short film===\n''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'', retrospectively referred to as ''Saw 0.5'', is a 2003 [[short film]] that served as a promotional tool in pitching the film's potential to [[Lionsgate]], included on the second disc of the uncut DVD release of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', released by itself, and on the ''Saw Trilogy'' DVD containing ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' Uncut Edition, ''[[Saw II]]'' Special Edition, and ''[[Saw III]]'' Director's Cut, packaged with a limited-edition 3D puppet head box version of [[Billy the Puppet]].\n\n==Cast and crew==\n===Cast===\n{{Details|List of Saw (franchise) cast members|List of Saw (franchise) characters|topic=the cast and characters}}\n\n{{Cast indicator|S|V|C|A}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=99%\n!rowspan=\"3\" width=\"14%\" | Character\n!colspan=\"9\" | Films\n|-\n! ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n! ''[[Saw II]]''\n! ''[[Saw III]]''\n! ''[[Saw IV]]''\n! ''[[Saw V]]''\n! ''[[Saw VI]]''\n! ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n! ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n! ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral:<br>{{small|From the<br>Book of Saw}}]]''\n|-\n|{{small|'''2004'''}}\n|{{small|'''2005'''}}\n|{{small|'''2006'''}}\n|{{small|'''2007'''}}\n|{{small|'''2008'''}}\n|{{small|'''2009'''}}\n|{{small|'''2010'''}}\n|{{small|'''2017'''}}\n|{{small|'''2020'''}}\n|-\n!