\" |$10.8 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw5BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw5.htm|title=Saw V (2008)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw VI]]''\n|{{start date|2009|10|23}}\n|$27,693,292\n|$40,540,337\n|$68,233,629\n|align=\"center\" |$11 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"Saw6BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw6.htm|title=Saw VI (2009)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Saw 3D]]''\n|{{Start date|2010|10|29}}\n|$45,710,178\n|$90,440,256\n|$136,150,434\n|align=\"center\"|$20 million\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=\"budget\">{{cite news| url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19116 | title=Kevin Greutert Talks to BD from the Set of 'Saw VII 3D' | work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] | publisher= The Collective | last= Miska|first= Brad | date=February 15, 2010 | access-date=February 16, 2010 | quote=At this point I view it as getting paid to go through a $17 million dollar one-man 3D film school program, so how's that for looking at the bright side of a dark situation?| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5namYxahq | archive-date=February 16, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n|{{start date|2017|10|27}}\n|$38,052,832\n|$64,900,056\n|$102,952,888\n|align=\"center\" |$10 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"JigsawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2017.htm|title=Jigsaw (2017)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\"|Total\n!$453,966,900\n!$522,305,866\n!$976,272,768\n!align=\"center\" |$77 million\n!\n|}\n\n===Critical and public response===\nOn [[IGN]]'s list of the top twenty-five film franchises of all time, the ''Saw'' series ranked as 25th.<ref>{{cite web|date=2006-11-20|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html|title=IGN: Top 25 Movie Franchises of All Time: #25|work=[[IGN]] |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061202074915/http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html |archive-date= 2006-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n! align=\"center\" | '''Film'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Rotten Tomatoes]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Metacritic]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[CinemaScore]]'''\n|-\n|-\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| 49% (184 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/|title=Saw|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 46 (32 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw/critic-reviews|title=Saw (2004): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| C+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web | title = CinemaScore | url = https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ | website = [[CinemaScore]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Saw II]]''\n| 37% (122 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/|title=Saw II|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 40 (28 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews|title=Saw II (2005): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw III]]''\n| 28% (92 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/|title=Saw III|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 48 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews|title=Saw III (2006): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| 20% (81 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| 36 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iv/critic-reviews|title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw V]]''\n| 13% (76 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_v/|title=Saw V|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20 (13 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-v/critic-reviews|title=Saw V (2008): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|C<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| 39% (72 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/|title=Saw VI|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n| 30 (12 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews|title=Saw VI (2009): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 24, 2009}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| 10% (79 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw3d/|title=Saw 3D|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n| 24 (17 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-3d/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Saw 3D (2010)|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B\u2013<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| 33% (87 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| 39 (18 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|website=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|}\n\n==Other media==\n{{main|List of Saw media}}\n\n===Video games===\n[[Japan]]ese video game company [[Konami]] currently owns the rights to the ''Saw'' interactive video game property. Konami stated in mid-2009 that they wanted to make ''Saw'' a series of video games to supplement the films. They also wish to make ''Saw'' their next big survival horror franchise next to their other property, ''[[Silent Hill]]''. They stated that because ''Saw'' focuses on visual intensity and ''Silent Hill'' focuses on psychological terror, both could exist in the video game industry without directly competing against each other.<ref name= \"Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?\">{{cite news|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/the_cut_scene/2009/04/silent-hill-say-hello-to-your-new-brother-jigsawkonami-has-confirmed-an-earlier-cut-scene-report-that-it-has-bought-the-pub.html|title=Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?|work=The Cut Scene|date=2009-04-02|access-date=2009-08-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first game in the series, ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'', set between the first and second film in the series, was initially released on October 6, 2009.<ref name=WanWhannell>{{Cite web|url=http://www.360-hq.com/article-2382-thread-1-0.html|title=Producer James Wan On Saw The Video Game &#124; 360-HQ.COM|website=www.360-hq.com|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118092768266523504 |title=A Start Up's Risky Niche: Movie-Based Videogames|date=2007-06-04|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2008-01-30|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/848/848533p1.html|title=Saw announced|access-date=2008-01-30}}</ref> with a sequel ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'', released on October 19, 2010, for the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, ten days before the release of the seventh film, ''Saw 3D''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/57520/Jigsaw_Returns.php|title=Jigsaw Returns!|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|date=April 9, 2010|access-date=April 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tapp]] and [[Amanda Young]] were released as part of the downloadable ''Saw Chapter'' for the video game ''[[Dead by Daylight]]''.<ref name= \"Dead by Daylight\">{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/01/22/dead-by-daylight-saw-dlc-confirmed-jigsaw-coming-tomorrow/|publisher=Comic Book|title=Dead By Daylight Confirms Saw DLC, Releasing Tomorrow|date=2018-01-22|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Comic books===\n''Saw: Rebirth'', a [[comic book]] prequel to the original film released to promote ''Saw II''. Its [[canon (fiction)|canonicity]] was later contradicted by events in ''Saw IV''. It is, however, the first canonical appearance of Jigsaw's wife, Jill, who was later introduced into the film series in ''Saw III'', and established still-canonical elements of Jigsaw's backstory (an engineer who is dying from brain cancer.)\n\n===Theme park attractions===\n* \"[[Saw: The Ride]]\" is a [[Gerstlauer Euro-Fighter]] roller coaster themed around the franchise, which opened on March 13, 2009, at [[Thorpe Park]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. It features an enclosed dark ride section with special effects, before cars travel outside and are pulled up a 100-foot vertical lift hill into a steep 100-degree drop.\n* [[Thorpe Park]] opened a temporary ''Saw'' attraction called \"Saw \u2014 Movie Bites\" for their 2009 Fright Nights event.\n* It was announced in October 2009 that Thorpe Park would also be adding a permanent, year-round [[live action]] horror [[maze]] themed around the ''Saw'' movies. It opened at the start of the 2010 season, and features six scenes representing one iconic trap from each movie to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hauntedattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=570&Itemid=2|title=Thorpe: SAW Alive exclusive details|work=Haunted Attractions|publisher=hauntedattractions.co.uk|access-date=2009-11-29}}</ref>\n* \"[[Halloween Horror Nights|Saw: Game Over]]\" was a 2009 maze made by [[Universal Parks & Resorts|Universal Studios]] for [[Halloween Horror Nights]], based on characters, traps and scenes from the films.<ref name= \"Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11469|publisher=Shock Till You Drop|title=Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!|date=2009-08-19|access-date=2009-11-12}}</ref> At the [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] rendition of Horror Nights it was titled ''Saw: Game Over'', while at the [[Universal Studios Florida]] rendition, it was simply titled ''Saw''.\n* \"Saw\", a themed haunted house, operated during the month of October at [http://www.frightdome.com Fright Dome], [[Circus Circus Las Vegas]]. It featured interactive, handcrafted replicas of the \"games\" set by [[Jigsaw Killer|Jigsaw]]. It was introduced in 2009 and partnered with [[Lionsgate]] and [[Twisted Pictures]].\n* In 2010, \"[[Halloween Fright Nights]]\" at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]] featured a maze created by [[Sudden Impact Entertainment]], featuring characters, traps and scenes from the films. The maze was simply titled \"Saw Maze\".\n* \"Saw Haunted Attraction\" was a maze at the Brea Plaza Shopping Center in 2008 created by Sinister Pointe Haunted Attractions.\n* \"SAWMANIA\" was a fan event in New York. Eventgoers were able to meet actors and directors, and view props used in the films.\n\n=== Fan Films Universe ===\nThe huge impact of [[Saw (2004 film)|''Saw'']] films inspired creators from all over the world to create [[Fan film|fan films]] based on their favorite franchaise.Those fan films are [[Unofficial]] & [[Unauthorized]] [[Bootleg recording|Bootleg]] [[Counterfeit consumer goods|Knock-off]] films that are in no way affiliated with [[Lionsgate Films|Lions Gate films]] inc or [[Twisted Pictures]]. Usualy made non-profit for private use only, and that are not intended for sales of any sort. On October 31, 2016, greek film director, film producer and writer [[Christos Arfanis]], released ''[[Saw: Heritage]]''<ref>{{Citation|title=SAW: Heritage|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6093012/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>, a fan film based on the franchaise. The film has recived mixed ratings. On the same year, ''[[Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage]]'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title|title=Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>was released. A short video documentary with b-roll footage from the behind the scenes making of the Bootleg fan film. \n\nOn 2020, two Unauthorized projects based on ''Saw'' are set to be released: [[He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw|''He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw'']]<ref>{{Citation|title=He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11915184/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and ''[[Saw:Blodlines|Saw: Blodlines]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Saw: Bloodlines|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11323584/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/saw/comments/b5k3g3/what_is_saw_bloodlines/|title=r/saw - What is saw bloodlines?|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\" border=\"1\"\n! align=\"center\" |'''Film'''\n! align=\"center\" | Release Date\n! align=\"center\" | Director(s)\n! align=\"center\" | Writter(s)\n|-\n|-\n| Saw: Heritage<ref>{{Citation|title=SAW: Heritage|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6093012/|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| 31 October 2016\n| Christos Arfanis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis (Based on Saw created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]])\n|-\n| Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage<ref>{{Citation|title=Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6304960/|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| 20 November 2016\n| Christos Arfanis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis (Based on Saw created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]])\n|-\n| Saw: Bloodlines<ref>{{Citation|title=Saw: Bloodlines|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11323584/|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| 31 October 2020\n|Thaine Tobio\n| align=\"center\" |Alen Alic, Robert M. Clarke, Thomas Claxton, Thaine Tobio (Based on Saw created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]])\n|-\n| He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw<ref>{{Citation|title=He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11915184/|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| 2020\n| Jay Anthony Gonato, Michael Welch\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis, France Cuiz, Alex Rieger, Tymetreus Thompson, Kiriakos Vilchez, Michael Welch (Based on Saw created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]])\n|}\n<br />\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[Splatter film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n; Databases\n* [http://allmovie.com/work/saw-film-series-356901 ''Saw'' film series] at [[Allmovie]]\n* [http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=Saw.htm ''Saw'' film series] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n; Official sites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041126235053/http://www.sawmovie.com/ ''Saw'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002065430/http://www.saw2.com/ ''Saw II'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061116073244/http://saw3.com/ ''Saw III website''] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161726/http://movies.break.com/saw4/ ''Saw IV'' website] (archive)\n* [http://www.saw5.com ''Saw V'' website]\n; Other links\n* [http://www.thorpepark.com/ Thorpe Park] - home to two ''Saw'' attractions\n* [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/scott-mendelson/goodbye-john-a-farewell-t_b_775552.html?view=print Goodbye John: A Farewell to Saw, as Jigsaw Lays His Last Trap] by Scott Mendelson\n\n{{Saw}}\n\n[[Category:Film franchises introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Horror film franchises]]\n[[Category:Splatter films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:Saw (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate franchises]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Saw'' (franchise)}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''Saw''\n| image = Saw film logo.png\n| imagesize = 210\n| caption = Official franchise logo\n| creator = [[James Wan]]<br />[[Leigh Whannell]]\n| owner = [[Lions Gate Entertainment]]\n| origin = ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n| comics = * ''[[Saw: Rebirth]]'' (2005)\n| films = * ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Saw II]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Saw III]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Saw IV]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Saw V]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Saw VI]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw 3D]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'' (2020)\n| shorts = * ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n* ''Full Disclosure Report: Piecing Together Jigsaw'' (2005)\n* ''The Scott Tibbs Documentary'' (2006)\n| vgs = * ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'' (2010)\n| radio = \n| soundtracks = * ''[[Saw (soundtrack)|Saw]]''\n* ''[[Saw II (soundtrack)|Saw II]]''\n* ''[[Saw III (soundtrack)|Saw III]]''\n* ''[[Saw IV (soundtrack)|Saw IV]]'' \n* ''[[Saw V (soundtrack)|Saw V]]'' \n* ''[[Saw VI (soundtrack)|Saw VI]]'' \n* ''[[Saw 3D (Original Score Soundtrack)|Saw 3D]]'' \n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)#Music|Jigsaw]]''\n| music = * \"[[Hello Zepp]]\"\n| otherlabel1 = Theme park ride(s)\n| otherdata1 = * [[Saw \u2013 The Ride]]\n| otherlabel2 = Haunted attraction(s)\n| otherdata2 = * Game Over<ref name=\"gover\">{{Cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2009/oct/12/sprawling-21st-century-freak-show/|title=Fright Dome: Circus Circus fear factory teems with terrific human horrors - Las Vegas Sun Newspaper|first=Joe|last=Brown|date=October 12, 2009|website=lasvegassun.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw's Revenge<ref name=\"gover\" />\n* Saw: Game Over<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3172917/a-bd-walkthrough-of-saw-game-over-jigsaw-s-horror-nights-maze/|title=A BD Walkthrough of \u2018Saw: Game Over\u2019, Jigsaw\u2019s Horror Nights Maze!|first=Bloody Disgusting|last=Staff|date=August 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* Saw: Game On<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldofpopculture.com/vampyrecastle-of-the-undead-added-to-halloween-horror-nights-2010/|title='Vampyre:Castle of the Undead' Added to Halloween Horror Nights 2010!|first=Kristyn|last=Clarke|date=September 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* Saw Maze<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parkz.com.au/update/2010/10/28/254-Warner_Bros_Movie_World_Halloween_2010.html|title=The Parkz Update: Warner Bros. Movie World, Halloween 2010|website=Parkz}}</ref>\n* Saw: The Games of Jigsaw<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/08/14/universal-studios-saw-the-games-of-jigsaw-to-set-new-traps-for-guests-during-halloween-horror-nights/|title=Universal Studios\u2019 \u2018SAW: The Games of Jigsaw\u2019 to set new traps for guests during Halloween Horror Nights|date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* Saw: Alive<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thorpepark.com/fright-nights/saw-alive|title=SAW: Alive - Live Action Horror Maze &#124; Thorpe Park|website=www.thorpepark.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw: Survive the Trap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/09/27/saw-jigsaw-escape-room-new-york-comic-con/|title='Jigsaw'-themed escape room to trap 'Saw' fans at New York Comic Con|website=EW.com}}</ref>\n* Saw Escape Room<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://attractionsmagazine.com/saw-escape-room-opens-in-las-vegas/|title=Official 'Saw' escape room now open in Las Vegas|date=January 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| otherlabel3 = Fan Film(s) Universe\n| otherdata3 = * ''Saw: Heritage'' (2016)\n* ''Behind the Scenes of Saw Heritage'' (2016)\n* ''Saw: Bloodlines'' (2020)\n* ''He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw'' (2020)\n}}\n\n'''''Saw''''' is an American [[horror film|horror]] [[media franchise|franchise]] created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]]. It consists of eight [[feature film]]s and additional media.\n\nIn 2003, Wan and Whannell made a [[Saw (2003 film)|short film]] to help [[Sales presentation|pitch]] a potential [[feature film]] concept. Their pitch was ultimately successful, and in 2004, [[Saw (2004 film)|the first installment]] of what would become the feature film franchise debuted at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]. The film was released theatrically that October, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. The sequels were directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], [[David Hackl]], and [[Kevin Greutert]], and were written by Wan, Whannell, Bousman, [[Patrick Melton]], and [[Marcus Dunstan]], and were released subsequently every October, on the Friday before [[Halloween]], between 2004 and 2010. Both of the creators remained with the franchise as [[executive producer]]s.\n\nOn July 22, 2010, producer [[Mark Burg]] confirmed that the seventh film, ''[[Saw 3D]]'', is the final installment of the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowles|first=Scott|date=July 22, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-22-saw22_ST_N.htm|title='Saw 3D' will be the final cut for horror franchise|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=July 22, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61r3dlvkb|archive-date=September 20, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, Lionsgate reportedly expressed interest in continuing the franchise with a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]].<ref name=\"Lionsgate Remaking Saw\">{{cite web|title=Lionsgate Remaking Saw?|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/58024/lionsgate-remaking-saw|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> In November 2013, it was reported that they were actively developing a sequel.<ref name=\"bloody-disgusting.com\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Lionsgate Is Actively Developing Next 'Saw'|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3262916/exclusive-lionsgate-is-actively-developing-next-saw/|publisher=Bloody Disgusting}}</ref> An eighth film, ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'', was eventually released in October 2017. In 2019, a ninth film was announced, ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'', with comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] attached to star, produce, and co-write.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/|title=\u2018SAW\u2019 Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct!|first=Brad|last=Miska|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise primarily revolves around [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]], also called the \"Jigsaw Killer\" or simply \"Jigsaw\". He was introduced briefly in ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' and developed in more detail in ''[[Saw II]]'' and the subsequent films. Rather than killing his [[List of Saw characters|victims]] outright, Jigsaw traps them in situations that he calls \"tests\" or \"games\" to test their will to live through physical or psychological torture and believes that if they survive, they will be \"rehabilitated\". Despite the fact that John was murdered in ''[[Saw III]]'', the films continue to focus on the posthumous influence of the Jigsaw Killer and his apprentices by exploring his character via [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]].\n\nThe franchise grossed more than {{US$|1 billion|long=no|link=yes}} from [[box office]] and retail sales by 2009,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lidz|first=Franz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html?_r=1&pagewanted=2&hpw|title=Limbs Pile Up, and Money, Too|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=October 21, 2009|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> and the films have collectively grossed over {{US$|976 million|long=no}} at the worldwide box office as of 2018. The film series as a whole has received mostly mixed to negative reviews by critics, but has been a financial success at the box office and is one of the highest-grossing horror film franchises of all time. While the films have been classified as [[Splatter film#Torture porn|torture porn]] by some critics,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sharrett|first=Christopher|title=The Problem of Saw: \"Torture Porn\" and the Conservatism of Contemporary Horror Films|magazine=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]|number=1|volume=35|date=December 2009|pages=32\u201337 |jstor= 41690851 |url=https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016013623/https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |archivedate= 2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442 | last=Nelson|first=Rob| title=Saw VI Movie Review | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] | date=October 23, 2009 | access-date=December 8, 2009| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nfI0IX | archive-date=January 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699|title=Saw VI \u2013 Film Review|last=Scheck|first=Frank|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 23, 2009|access-date=September 15, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQpk10a|archive-date=September 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> the creators of ''Saw'' disagree with that term.<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/|title=Saw creators Leigh Whannell and James Wan|last=Tobias|first=Scott|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=October 29, 2010|access-date=August 16, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/60zpLcBgr|archive-date=August 16, 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=100%\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Screenwriter(s) \n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" width=15%| Producer(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2004|10|29}}\n| [[James Wan]]\n| [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| James Wan and Leigh Whannell\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gregg Hoffman]], [[Oren Koules]] and [[Mark Burg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw II]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2005|10|28}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Leigh Whannell and Darren Lynn Bousman\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw III]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2006|10|27}}\n| Leigh Whannell\n| Leigh Whannell and James Wan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2007|10|26}}\n| [[Patrick Melton]] & [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan and [[Thomas Fenton]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw V]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2008|10|24}}\n| [[David Hackl]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2009|10|23}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Kevin Greutert]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2010|10|29}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2017|10|27}}\n| [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Josh Stolberg]] & Peter Goldfinger\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2020|5|15}}\n| Darren Lynn Bousman\n| Josh Stolberg & Peter Goldfinger\n| [[Chris Rock]]\n| Oren Koules and Mark Burg\n|}\n\n===Future===\n{{Main|Spiral (2020 film)}}\nIn May 2019, it was confirmed that a ninth film in the series was in production.  Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] will return to helm the film. Comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] will star in the film and will also be involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Rock stated \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/|title=Chris Rock To Reboot \u2018Saw\u2019 Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> ''Jigsaw'' writers Josh Stolberg and Pete Goldfinger are returning to write the screenplay. Stolberg later clarified that ninth installment will exist in the same continuity of the previous films, though it will not be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143993966049685504|title=The film is NOT a reboot. It is canon. All the films exist in the same universe. And who knows, maybe Saw X will tie all the stories together. You never know.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143028357610627073|title=I can say with pretty much certainly that our new film will NOT be called Jigsaw 2. But I don't make the decisions, so who knows. But it's NOT a sequel to Jigsaw. It's DEFINITELY in the timeline of ALL the films though.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe movie began filming in June 2019 and was scheduled to be released in theaters on May 15, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/112615/20190524/saw-9-release-date-spoilers-chris-rock-reboot-might-introduce-creepy-new-john-kramer.htm|title='Saw 9' Release Date, Spoilers: Chris Rock Reboot Might Introduce Creepy New John Kramer|first=Business|last=Times|date=May 24, 2019|website=Business Times|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/|title=New Saw Movie Set To Start Filming This Month|date=June 27, 2019|website=ScreenRant|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> but was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Short film===\n''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'', retrospectively referred to as ''Saw 0.5'', is a 2003 [[short film]] that served as a promotional tool in pitching the film's potential to [[Lionsgate]], included on the second disc of the uncut DVD release of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', released by itself, and on the ''Saw Trilogy'' DVD containing ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' Uncut Edition, ''[[Saw II]]'' Special Edition, and ''[[Saw III]]'' Director's Cut, packaged with a limited-edition 3D puppet head box version of [[Billy the Puppet]].\n\n==Cast and crew==\n===Cast===\n{{Details|List of Saw (franchise) cast members|List of Saw (franchise) characters|topic=the cast and characters}}\n\n{{Cast indicator|S|V|C|A}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=99%\n!rowspan=\"3\" width=\"14%\" | Character\n!